<FIRST>r a AM-GalloPullback     06-16 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gallo Pullback,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gallo Heeds `Safe-Sober' Group, Pulls Tenderloin High-Alcohol Wines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a startling first for the largest
winemaker in the world, the E.&amp; J. Gallo Winery said it will stop
for six months the sale of its its two brands of cheap high-alcohol
wine in the seedy Tenderloin district.
   The action came Wednesday after Tenderloin-area distributor
Gallo-Bay Cities, a Gallo-owned business, met with ``Safe and Sober
Streets'' activists, who have protested the sale of the fortified
wines in their district.
   ``If what we have done in this neighborhood improves the
alcoholism problem in this area, we'll do the same thing in other
neighborhoods,'' said Dan Solomon, a spokesman for the Modesto-based
winery.
   The protesters denounced fortified wines like Gallo's Thunderbird
and Night Train Express, and Canandaigua's Wild Irish Rose. They
said they were unable to walk through the Tenderloin without
tripping over or being menaced by a wino.
   Gallo has never removed a product from the shelves, Solomon said.
The privately held company has $1 billion in annual sales and 28
percent of the U.S. wine market.
   Sober Streets group went from grocery-to-grocery, trying to
persuade the proprietors to take the cheap goods off their shelves.
One grocer agreed but changed his mind, he said, after losing $850
in wine sales in a single day.
   Solomon characterized the action as an experiment by Gallo to see
whether or not ``our beliefs and the evidence are correct'' _ that
winos deprived of their cheap wine will turn to other alcohols.
   The wines involved are typically made from the cheapest vinous
ingredients and the merest hint of grape flavor, then hyped with
grape brandy to bring the alcohol to about 18 percent by volume.
They sell for around 90 cents to $1.25 a bottle.
   It's estimated that the two wines account for less than 3 percent
of company sales.
</TEXT>
