<DOCNO> AP890616-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-UndergroundSchools     06-16 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Underground Schools,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Battle Growing Illiteracy in Underground Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KAFR EIN, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A half dozen 8-year-olds sat
on the floor of a makeshift classroom in this West Bank village and
leafed through a science book on animals. Some drew Palestinian
flags in the margins, but none could read the simple text.
   ``If they were in school, they'd be able to read by now,'' said
Najah Mahmoud, the children's 15-year-old teacher. ``I'm trying to
get them to memorize some words, but it just isn't enough.''
   Illiteracy is growing among the West Bank's 230,000 elementary
school children, who have been deprived of an education for 16
months as a result of Israel's closure of schools. Classrooms have
remained empty for all but a few weeks since Feb. 3, 1988.
   Israeli authorities say they closed the West Bank's 1,194
schools, including 145 kindergartens, because they were breeding
grounds for violent protests during the 18-month Palestinian
uprising. Fifteen schools in the Gaza Strip also have been closed,
but the army has not shut down the entire system.
   Israel has come under increasing international pressure,
including a call from U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III, to
end what many consider a collective punishment and to reopen classes
when the closure order comes up for renewal on Monday.
   ``We would like to see the schools open but without an escalation
of violence and without an increase in danger that children would be
injured in the process. That's our concern, and Mr. Baker's concern,
as well,'' Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said in an interview.
   To try to keep students from falling too far behind, Palestinians
have been running underground classes in more than 100 West Bank
towns and villages in defiance of army orders outlawing such
alternative education.
   The lessons are taught in unused buildings, mosques, churches or
even in the open air, shaded by a tree. But, according to Arab
educators, these so-called ``people's schools'' have produced mixed
results.
   ``The problem we face now is illiteracy,'' said Khalil Mahshi,
principal of the Quaker-run Friends School in Ramallah. ``Instead of
consolidating reading skills at ages 7 to 9, we are dealing with
children as old as 9 years old who are illiterate.''
   Malashi said some children from poorer families, who have taken
on unskilled jobs to supplement meager family incomes, may become
permanent dropouts. And wealthy Palestinians, concerned about the
educational prospects for their children, are leaving for the United
States and Europe.
   ``Long term, the community is going to pay a price at the level
of development, production and skilled manpower. This is the biggest
asset of any society,'' he said.
   The second-graders studying in a cramped one-room stone house in
Kafr Ein, a village of 1,000 about 25 miles north of Jerusalem,
spent a recent science class drawing pictures of donkeys, chickens
and camels.
   Samir, a dark-eyed 7-year-old, carefully sketched two outlawed
Palestinian flags onto the hump of his camel. ``I'd like to be able
to read. It is important,'' he said in a small, serious voice.
``Instead, I can draw a Palestinian flag.''
   Grades one through six in Kafr Ein study two hours each day,
doubling up two classes at a time on opposite sides of the room.
There are no classes for the upper grades, and the only teaching
materials in evidence were two tattered primary-level science books,
some colored markers and two chalkboards.
   But teaching materials weren't the only thing missing. The
second-graders' 15-year-old teacher, Miss Mahmoud, only in 9th grade
herself, conceded she has no teaching qualifications.
   ``What I can give them is better than nothing, but it can't
compare with what they'd be learning in school,'' she said.
   Besides teaching basic Arabic and math to her fourth-grade class,
instructor Manah Abbas, 20 teaches a new subject called ``national
education'' ordered in April by uprising leaders linked to the PLO.
   ``I teach them about the intefadeh and how not to be afraid of
the soldiers when they come to the village,'' said Miss Abbas, who
wore an enamel necklace showing all Palestine, including Israel,
painted in the colors of the outlawed Palestinian flag.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
