<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-LastTemptation     06-16 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Last Temptation,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Court Reverses Ban on `Last Temptation' Film</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's Supreme Court has overturned a ban on
Martin Scorsese's film, ``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' though
the judges said the movie is likely to offend some people.
   The country's 27-member Theater and Film Censorship Board banned
the film last October. The panel cited a criminal law that forbids
practices offensive to the beliefs of any religious group.
   The movie, adapted from a 1955 novel by Nikos Kazanthakis,
touched off protests by Christian groups in the United States and
Europe. Some Christians have been offended by Scorsese's portrayal
of Jesus Christ as a human being with passions and weaknesses.
   In reversing the ban Thursday, the five-judge panel said it was
``not enough that the movie is likely to stir up opposition or even
offense against a portion of those who choose to see it.''
   Amnon Globus of Golan-Globus Cannon, the film's Israeli
distributors who appealed the case to the Supreme Court, said its
decision signaled ``the end of censorship'' in Israel.
   ``The ones who have to judge whether a movie should be shown or
not is the public,'' said Globus.
   He said the movie would be shown in Israel by next week, after
Hebrew subtitles are completed.
</TEXT>
