<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Unionist     06-16 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Unionist,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Leader Reported Free After Torture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union leader who claims he was
arrested by Treasury Police, accused of leftist ties and tortured
was released Thursday, a spokesman for his group said.
   The union official, Jose Tomas Mazariego, disappeared Monday
after leaving the U.S. Embassy in San Salvador. He reportedly sought
a U.S. visa because he was to leave the next day for a visit at the
invitation of U.S. labor groups.
   Witnesses said he was picked up by men in civilian clothes who
did not identify themselves.
   A spokesman for Mazariego's group, the National Unity of
Salvadoran Workers, said in a telephone interview that Mazariego was
released at 5 p.m. Thursday.
   The spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Mazariego
reported that police accused him of links to leftist guerrilla
organizations and burned his body with acid.
   A spokeswoman for the Communications Workers of America in
Trenton, N.J., said Mazariego had been scheduled to give a talk in
Philadelphia on Thursday and in New Jersey on June 19.
   The National Unity of Salvadoran Workers is the largest labor
union in El Salvador. Marzariego also serves as an official of the
Salvadoran Telecommunications Union.
