<DOCNO> AP890616-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Noriega-Laundering     06-16 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Noriega-Laundering,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Documents Show Noriega Deposited $50 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's leader Manuel Antonio Noriega has
deposited at least $50 million in secret bank accounts since 1982,
according to documents seized in a money laundering investigation,
NBC News reports.
   The network reported Thursday that the documents were seized in
October in London by British authorities after Noriega's bank, the
Bank of Credit and Commerce, was indicted in the drug money case in
Florida.
   British authorities this week gave U.S. investigators more than
1,000 documents and show that the Panamanian general controlled up
to seven secret accounts, according to NBC.
   According to the documents, Noriega deposited at least $50
million since he opened the accounts seven years ago while his Army
salary was about $50,000 a year, NBC said.
   In one transaction, $27 million of Noriega's money was
transferred out of a secret account in London to one in Luxembourg
just one day after Noriega was indicted on drug charges in the
United States, according to the report.
   Authorities whom NBC did not identify said one key document is a
letter from Noriega to his banker, Amjad Awan, instructing him that
the accounts must be kept secret and that no bank statements ever be
sent to Noriega in Panama.
   NBC said authorities believe that most of the money came from
Noriega's dealings with Colombian drug bosses, international arms
dealers and the CIA, which reportedly had Noriega on its payroll.
   The Bank of Credit and Commerce International was charged in
Tampa, Fla., in October 1988 with laundering millions of dollars in
cocaine profits collected in U.S. cities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
