<FIRST>r w PM-Gregg     06-16 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gregg,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee to Vote on Controversial Nominee Tuesday</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ambassadorial nominee Donald Gregg ended his
confirmation hearings by insisting he was unaware until December
1986 of Oliver North's secret resupply operation to the Contra
rebels in Nicaragua, but a leading Democrat says he's unconvinced.
   Gregg asserted Thursday he didn't tell then-Vice President Bush
about the resupply network because Gregg didn't learn the extent of
North's involvement until two months after one of the network's
planes was shot down in October 1986.
   Gregg told the Senate Foreign Relations Committee that had he
known about the resupply effort, he would have ``taken steps to stop
the operation.''
   The panel of 10 Democrats and nine Republicans will vote Tuesday
on whether to recommend to the full Senate that the CIA's former
station chief in Seoul be confirmed as ambassador to South Korea.
Gregg had been Bush's national security adviser when he was vice
president.
   Committee members said the vote is likely to be close, although
there were indications at least one Democrat on the panel might vote
for Gregg. Democrats repeatedly challenged Gregg's credibility and
said his alleged lack of judgment disqualifies him for confirmation
as an ambassador.
   Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., said through a spokeswoman that
``barring evidence of lying or perjury'' he is leaning toward
confirmation.
   ``He wants to review all of the evidence and he plans to make a
conscientious decision,'' said spokeswoman Julia Sutherland.
   At the hearing, Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., referred to a
two-page January 1985 memo to North which, according to Cranston,
showed that Felix Rodriguez, a longtime friend with whom Gregg was
in frequent contact, was involved with the Contras.
   The memo was dated several days after Rodriguez met with Bush and
Gregg in the vice president's office. Gregg said he couldn't
remember whether North also attended what turned out to be the first
of three meetings between Rodriguez and Bush.
   Gregg testified that Contra resupply was ``absolutely not''
discussed at the January meeting.
   Gregg, who said he sent Rodriguez to El Salvador to assist that
country's military, insisted he first learned Rodriguez had
something to do with the Contras in August 1986. That's when
Rodriguez complained that crooked arms merchants were gouging the
Contras in a scandal he said could become another Watergate.
   Gregg says he didn't tell Bush, but rather convened a meeting
four days later with representatives of various agencies, including
the CIA and National Security Council. North didn't attend, even
though Gregg asked that he do so.
   But Gregg asserted he didn't learn of the extent of North's
involvement in the operation until December 1986 when he said
Rodriguez detailed it for him.
   North had contacted Gregg to complain about Rodriguez' not using
secure communications equipment and about allegedly stealing a plane
belonging to the Contras. But Gregg said he failed to conclude from
those incidents or the August 1986 meeting that North was running a
resupply operation or that Rodriguez was part of it.
   In December 1986, Rodriguez telephoned Gregg and told him he and
North had agreed to keep Gregg in the dark.
   Gregg said he was ``furious'' with North and ``felt very let
down'' by Rodriguez. ``I faulted myself for not putting the pieces
together,'' Gregg said.
   ``You are trying to convince us of an elaborate conspiracy'' to
keep Gregg from knowing about Contra assistance run by North, said
Cranston.
   North and courier Robert Owen knew about Rodriguez' role, as did
U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering and Col. James Steele in El
Salvador, so ``why didn't you know?'' asked Cranston.
   ``That's a pretty sweeping assertion,'' responded Gregg, who said
at least two U.S. military officials who dealt with Rodriguez in
Central America testified they didn't know he was involved in the
resupply network.
   Cranston said he regards Gregg's performance Thursday as no more
complete or satisfactory than his testimony at the first round of
his confirmation hearing in May.
   In May, Cranston accused Gregg of sponsoring ``a free-lance
covert operation out of the vice president's office'' to help
resupply the Contras during a congressional ban on military aid to
the rebel force.
</TEXT>
