<FIRST>u i BC-Lebanon-Israel     06-16 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Lebanon-Israel,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Jetplanes Bomb Palestinian Guerrilla Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes bombed Palestinian
guerrilla bases on the outskirts of this southern port in two dawn
runs Friday, police said.
   They said the planes blasted bases of the Marxist Popular Front
for the Liberation of Palestine both in and around the Rashidiyeh
refugee camp on Tyre's southern border 10 miles north Israel.
   The planes destroyed all targets and returned safely, the Israeli
army said.
   The area has been used to launch guerrilla attacks against Israel
and its self-declared security zone in southern Lebanon, the army
said. It did not say which guerrilla faction it was attacking.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be identified under standing
regulations, said there was no immediate word of damage or
casualties.
   There was no comment from the Popular Front's offices in Beirut
or Damascus. The radical group, led by George Habash, is the
second-largest faction in Yasser Arafat's Palestine Liberation
Organization after the mainstream Fatah.
   It was Israel's second air strike into Lebanon in three days and
the eighth this year. By police count, nine people were killed and
58 wounded in the seven previous air attacks beginning Jan. 11.
   On Wednesday, Israeli warplanes bombed a hideout used by the
Popular Front and three other radical Palestinian factions in the
Chouf Mountains southeast of Beirut. Three guerrillas were killed
and nine wounded in that raid.
</TEXT>
