<FIRST>r a PM-Secord-DrunkenDriving     06-16 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Secord-Drunken Driving,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Figure Again Charged With Drunken Driving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran-Contra figure Richard Secord faces a new
charge of drunken driving, authorities in this Washington, D.C.,
suburb said.
   Secord is appealing a conviction last month for the same offense.
   The 56-year-old retired Air Force major general was arrested in
the town of Vienna early Wednesday morning, according to Marie
Kisner, public information officer for the town.
   She said the arrest occurred after a police officer spotted a
suspicious looking vehicle that was moving very slowly and came to
almost a complete stop at a green light.
   Secord, cited for drunken driving and refusing to give a breath
or blood sample, was released on $750 cash bond after spending
several hours in the Fairfax County jail, Kisner said.
   He was convicted May 11 in Fairfax County of driving with an
alcohol level of 0.20, twice the legal limit in Virginia.
   District Judge Barbara Kimble sentenced him to 30 days in jail,
suspended his driver's license for six months, fined $500 and
ordered to enroll in an Alcohol Safety Awareness program. Kimble
then suspended the jail time and $200 of the fine and allowed Secord
to drive his car to work and to the alcohol program.
   Secord filed an appeal and a new trial is scheduled for Aug. 24.
   Secord was a key figure who worked with former White House aide
Oliver L. North in the Iran-Contra affair. He is charged with paying
illegal gratuities to North during the period when the Reagan
administration was covertly selling arms to Iran and with perjuring
himself in testimony to Congress.
</TEXT>
