<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     06-16 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Celebrants drank champagne and sang at an
85th birthday party for Arnold Batliner, a ``money-launderer'' who
makes money the old-fashioned way _ he washes it.
   The octogenarian washes all the coins used at the St. Francis
Hotel, where the venerable if outmoded tradition once spared ladies
the mortification of white gloves begrimed by silver dollars.
   The hotel's coin-washing tradition began in 1936, when silver
dollars were in circulation, and was expanded to include all silver
change.
   Batliner estimated he has washed $15.5 million in coins at the
hotel over 27 years _ more than a million pounds of change since
1962.
   His workplace is a security-tight room deep in the bowels of the
famous Union Square hotel, which like Batliner is 85 years old this
year.
   When the coins come out of the ancient burnishing machine, they
are as bright as the day they were minted. Batliner said he enjoys
his work, adding with pride that he never encountered a coin he
couldn't clean.
   Some are tough, though. ``Sometimes there's chewing gum in
them,'' he muttered.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Jardin learned again a
fisherman's lesson: dash is more important than flash in scallop
shucking.
   Sporting Day-Glo sunglasses, a florescent windbreaker and plenty
of gold jewelry, all eyes were on Jardin at the International
Scallop Shucking Contest preliminaries Thursday.
   The 25-year-old fisherman entered as champion, but left knowing
how fleeting fame can be.
   In just over nine minutes, Jardin pryed 182 scallops from their
shells.
   Fast, but Mark Picanso and others were faster. Picanso took first
place by shucking 196 scallops in about the same time. He has been
shucking for a dozen years.
   Picanso will be one of four scallop shuckers representing the
United States in their annual face-off against Canada this year.
   There's one important tool of the trade: a point-sharpened butter
knife with its handle wrapped in friction tape to ensure a steady
grip.
   Picanso's secret? No flash.
   ``Concentration and rhythm, that's what you need. If you can keep
yourself from being distracted then you've got it all.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first thing most people look for when they
get their new telephone book is their name. Some people in northern
Nevada, though, will look to see how big their names are as well.
   Nevada Bell tried to save some paper in last year's telephone
books by printing names in 6-point type, the size type used for box
scores in most newspaper's sports sections.
   Many people complained the phone book was difficult, if not
impossible, to read.
   Nevada Bell unveiled its new look in this year's directory on
Thursday, featuring 8-point type for its 145,000 listings. People
can size up the book starting next week, when distribution begins.
</TEXT>
