<DOCNO> AP890616-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0556EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FernaldTrial     06-16 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fernald Trial,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Decides in Favor of Uranium Plant Neighbors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury recommended in a mock trial to award
$136 million to neighbors of a federal uranium processing plant, a
decision the neighbors' lawyer hopes will lead to a settlement.
   The jury issued the non-binding verdict Thursday on the second
day of deliberations in a summary jury trial, an abbreviated
procedure used by U.S. District Judge S. Arthur Spiegel to encourage
a settlement of the neighbors' $300 million lawsuit.
   ``We won 100 percent. We didn't lose a single issue of law,''
said Stanley M. Chesley, a lawyer for the 14,000 plaintiffs
represented in the class-action lawsuit.
   The jury ruled that National Lead of Ohio Inc. operated the U.S.
Department of Energy's Feed Materials Production Center in a way
that caused neighbors to suffer emotional distress and lowered
property values. National Lead, which operated the plant under
contract to the federal government from 1951 through 1985, was sued
with its parent firm, National Lead Industries Inc.
   Chesley said he hopes the Energy Department, which represented
the defendant companies in the lawsuit, will now settle the civil
lawsuit. The plaintiffs all live within five miles of the plant in
Fernald, which is 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati.
   Henry Gill Jr., the Energy Department's chief lawyer, declined to
comment on a settlement, saying he would continue discussions with
Chesley and would need to confer with his superiors.
   If there is no settlement, the case goes to a real trial Aug. 15
before Spiegel.
   The 38-year-old plant processes uranium used by Energy Department
reactors elsewhere in producing nuclear weapons.
   Environmentalists have been watching the case in hopes that the
advisory verdict would affect other Energy Department installations
nationwide that are reputed to be polluters.
   Energy Department lawyers argued that the defendant companies
could not be found liable because they could only carry out the
government's orders.
   The Energy Department estimates that 383,000 pounds of
radioactive uranium oxide dust has been released from faulty
exhaust-air filters since the plant opened. Government lawyers said
the material has not endangered residents or harmed property.
   ``The jury believed they were reckless and careless the way they
managed this plant ... They didn't give a hoot about us or the
environment and now they are going to have to pay for it,'' said
Lisa Crawford, spokeswoman for the Fernald Residents for
Environmental Safety and Health.
   The jury recommended the damage amount would include $80 million
for a fund to monitor the residents' medical problems, $55 million
for punitive damages and $1 million for property damage.
   Jury foreman Robert Caplinger, questioned by the judge after
Thursday's verdict, said the jury thought its decision could help
persuade other contractors not to manage plants like National Lead
ran the Fernald facility.
   Westinghouse Materials Co. of Ohio has operated the plant since
January 1986 and is not a defendant in the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Greece-Elections     06-16 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-Elections,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Controversial Premier Faces Toughest Test at Polls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surrounded by controversy, Premier Andreas
Papandreou faces the toughest test of his 25-year political career
in national elections Sunday.
   The results are expected to decide whether the 70-year-old former
U. S. university professor will continue dominating Greece's
often-turbulent politics or end his career on a discordant note.
   Papandreou first was elected in 1981 on an anti-American platform
and promises of significant social change. Instead, he and members
of his government have floundered since August over charges
involving a multimillion-dollar financial scandal and illegal arms
deals.
   Opponents often are critical of Papandreou's authoritarian style
and sensitivity to criticism. But they have not discounted him,
despite poor opinion poll ratings.
   ``He'll leave the country if he loses the election,'' said
opposition legislator Virginia Tsouderou of the center-right New
Democracy.
   Ms. Tsouderou claims Papandreou will leave whether his
Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK) gets second place or her
party wins an outright majority in the 300-member parliament.
   Papandreou said he will stay regardless.
   ``I know what it is to be in the opposition, I'm a fighter,'' he
said in a recent interview.
   But few political observers believe him, and even some party
members doubt him.
   ``Papandreou is too sensitive to sit in Parliament and listen to
criticism. If we lose, many of us in the party expect him to go, but
his magnetism could pull off a miracle'' agreed a Panhellenic deputy
running for re-election.
   He said Papandreou's style of ``one-man rule'' has alienated many
party members. Papandreou rarely showed up in Parliament, preferring
to govern from his suburban residence.
   ``We realize that without him PASOK would have little chance of
winning, but at the same time he could be a liability because of his
controversial private life and financial scandals we have been
burdened with,'' the deputy said on condition of anonymity.
   Harilaos Florakis, secretary-general of the Greek Communist
Party, believes Papandreou ``will be dumped as party leader if he
loses the election.''
   Observers speculate that if the Panhellenics loose their overall
majority, the elections would enable the Communist Party to play a
role in forming a new government.
   ``Despite statements by New Democracy and PASOK that they will
reject communist support to form a coalition government, anything
can happen,'' a West European diplomat said on condition of
anonymity.
   Papandreou was dean of the economics department at the University
of California at Berkeley. He returned to Greece in 1959 after a
20-year absence.
   With his charismatic personality and gift for oratory, he used
his father's Center Union to form his own party following the
collapse of the military dictatorship that ruled Greece from
1967-1974.
   Papandreou concedes his popularity has diminished.
   He told the pro-government daily Ta Nea that the financial
scandal and his open affair with a flight attendant half his age
have affected his popularity.
   Papandreou divorced his American-born wife, Margaret, on June 9
ending their 38-year marriage. The divorce frees him to marry
Dimitra Liani, who critics charge influences his decisions.
   Papandreou admits he ``bounces his ideas off Liani because she
has good instinct. But I do not always follow her advice.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NavyWaste     06-16 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy Waste,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Navy Wasting Billions in Intentional Sinkings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ocean floor is full of sunken treasure from
old military ships that have been blown up as targets or sunken as
artificial reefs, an investigative report says.
   Although there may be no doubloons or pieces of eight in the
newest denizens of Davy Jones's Locker, $17 million in recoverable
goods has been destroyed on board 24 ships sunk in recent years as
reefs or in target practice, the report by the Navy's inspector
general said.
   An additional $40 million will be lost unless something is done
to salvage items from 64 vessels that now await a similar fate, it
said.
   There are, in fact, ``significant amounts'' of gold and silver _
to be salvaged from communications and code equipment, the report
says.
   Mostly the wasted goods consist of power tools such as lathes,
drill presses, band saws, pumps and office and electronic equipment.
   Inspectors also said there were operating room and dental
equipment, including sterilizers; air conditioners and ice machines;
silverware; radios and teletypes; new mattresses, still in plastic
bags; and numerous spare parts.
   ``The Navy has been derelict in the proper management of the
public property under its control,'' the report concluded.
   Rep. William Broomfield, R-Mich., who released the report,
introduced legislation on Thursday to permit outside contractors to
reclaim scrap items from such ships. They would apply for the right
to salvage items under sealed bids, Broomfield said.
   ``America may be the most wealthy nation in the world, but we are
not so wealthy that we can afford to dump millions of dollars worth
of sophisticated equipment to the bottom of the ocean floor,'' he
said in a statement.
   The Navy continues to buy some of the same items it has wasted,
the inspector general's report said, and ``has ignored the
possibility of re-usage.''
   In a response, the service said it is ``reviewing the report to
determine any appropriate action. This will include reviewing the
cost estimates of the unrecovered materials, plus the associated
recovery costs, equipment condition and applicability to current
needs.''
   The Navy added that it ``also plans to review its instructions
governing the process and procedures for inactivating and stripping
ships.''
   The internal investigation was prompted by a complaint from
William R. Justen, whose Stuart, Fla., company had been hired to
sink an old Navy ship under the artificial reef program.
   Justen complained that some $300,000 worth of reusable items were
on the vessel, but he was unable to salvage them because of the time
constraints of his contract. He told the Navy that he was aware of
other, similar cases, as well.
   The inspector general found confusion in the handling of
decommissioned ships and few clear provisions for salvage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
