<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonStorm     06-16 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington Storm,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Thunderstorm Leaves More Residents Without Power</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An area still recovering from a devastating
thunderstorm was hit by showers and high winds for a second day in a
row, hampering efforts to clean up trees and leaving an additional
22,000 homes without power in the nation's capital and suburban
Maryland.
   The second storm swept through the area late Thursday afternoon,
creating havoc with rush-hour commuters for the second time in 24
hours. To make matters worse, dozens of traffic signals were out as
a result of Wednesday's storm, which caused an estimated 150,000
power outages and felled hundred of trees.
   Virginia Electric Power Co. spokeswoman Deborah Tompkins said an
estimated 12,600 homes in the northern section of the state were
without power at the height of the storm, around 6 p.m.
   Tom Welle, a Potomac Electric Co. spokesman, said the second
storm, not as strong as the first, hampered efforts to repair the
damage caused by the initial thundershower, which he said was the
most disruptive in the company's 93-year history.
   ``We have to rebuild almost all of the electrical system from
scratch,'' Welle said. ``At this rate, some people will probably be
without power through the weekend.''
   Pepco was giving out dry ice at two locations for people who
owned freezers filled with food that was thawing.
   Even before the new storm, hundreds of trees still blocked side
streets and were wrapped around felled power lines. City and county
police directed traffic at key intersections where traffic lights
were malfunctioning.
   Insurance industry analysts said private storm-related claims had
already passed the $5 million mark, and would likely climb much
higher.
   About 30 area schools were closed Thursday, due to the outages,
and at least 16 were to remain closed today. Three UHF television
stations, WETA, WHMM and WDCA, which share the same transmitter
site, remained off the air Thursday. WDCA still had not returned to
the air early this morning.
   PEPCO spokeswoman Eileen Griffin said about 300 crews were
working around the clock to restore electricity. The utility was
forced to call outside crews from as far as North Carolina to assist
them in the effort.
</TEXT>
