<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--PennyDrive     06-16 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Penny Drive,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Give Pennies to Teacher for Medical Expenses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HYATTSVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at an elementary school have
donated $1,000 in pennies collected for a class project towards the
medical expenses of a teacher who needs a liver transplant.
   The money was donated by students at the Langley Park-McCormick
Elementary School for Mary Alliata, who teaches at nearby Ridgecrest
Elementary School.
   Alliata suffers from a blockage of her bile ducts and needs the
transplant to survive. Her medical expenses are expected to be about
$200,000.
   Teacher Les Greenblatt organized the penny drive originally as a
class project to see if the school's students could raise a million
pennies. But, when the students realized they would not be able to
meet the goal, Greenblatt said they decided to give the money to a
good cause.
   ``I think it's really wonderful that these children can do
that,'' Alliata said. ``It's very touching.''
</TEXT>
