<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     06-16 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators' Mass Mailings Cost $52.7 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mass mailings by 100 senators during 1987-88
cost taxpayers more than $52.7 million, the congressional watchdog
Common Cause says in a report.
   The 27 senators seeking re-election last year spent $20.1 million
of the total, an average of 48 cents per household, according to the
Common Cause study released Thursday. The per-household figures
compared to an average of 31 cents for the 67 senators who were not
campaigning for re-election, and 15 cents for six senators who
retired in 1988.
   The study said taxpayer-financed mailing costs for both houses
have increased from $48.9 million in fiscal 1978 to $113.4 million
for fiscal 1988.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Probes Begin Into Some Reported Car and Truck Defects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal engineers have opened investigations
into reports of safety defects in up to 200,000 Subaru cars and
Nissan trucks, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
says.
   The investigations, both preliminary evaluations, involve
complaints of engine fires in 1987 Subaru DL and GL models and
complaints of steering problems in 1987 to 1989 Nissan pickup
trucks. Preliminary evaluation is the lowest level of investigation
conducted by NHTSA engineers when they receive complaints.
   NHTSA said the government received five complaints from Subaru
owners of engine compartment fires. It estimated that 67,000 of the
cars are on U.S. roads.
   NHTSA, in its monthly Defect Investigation Report, also announced
an upgrade of its investigation involving more than 640,000 Ford
Taurus and Mercury Sable 1986 and 1987 cars. An engineering analysis
will be conducted into the possibility of broken or cracked front
seat brackets in the cars, following 68 complaints received by Ford
Motor Co. and the government.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>FCC Stands By Decision to Allocate Frequency Band</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has
reaffirmed its decision to allocate to land mobile radio service a
frequency band that previously had been available to amateur radio
operators.
   The commission's August 1988 action had been appealed by the
American Radio Relay League and about 700 other amateur radio
organizations and individual ham radio operators. David Sumner,
ARRL's executive vice president, said the league plans further
appeals in federal court.
   At Thursday's meeting, the FCC stood by its decision to maintain
the 216-220 MHz band for maritime mobile communications, allocate
the 220-222 MHz band _ which earlier had been available to amateurs
_ to land mobile service and allocate the 222-225 MHz band
exclusively to amateur service. A number of other frequency bands
also are currently allocated to amateur radio operators.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Candidates Seeking High-Level Party Endorsements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just a week into the post-primary season, New
Jersey's gubernatorial candidates flocked to their party's biggest
Washington names in search of valuable support and solidarity.
   Both finished the day Thursday with promises of campaign
appearances.
   Democratic Rep. James Florio posed inside a Capitol dining room
with newly elected House Speaker Tom Foley, D-Wash., who said he
expected to stump in the Garden State for his congressional
colleague.
   Hours later, Republican Rep. James Courter emerged smiling from
beneath a White House portico after a meeting with President Bush.
   Asked if the support Bush was offering Courter, combined with the
popularity of outgoing Republican Gov. Thomas Kean, would make the
race difficult for a Democrat, Foley said, ``We think the tradition
of progressive leadership in New Jersey is a Jim Florio tradition.''
   The phrase ``progressive leadership'' came out again in Courter's
recounting of the session with Bush, First Lady Barbara Bush and New
Jersey's new GOP Chairwoman Kathleen Donovan.
