<FIRST>r i PM-Ireland-Elections     06-16 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ireland-Elections,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vote Count Begins Today in Irish Snap Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ireland began counting ballots today from
its snap national election, but politicians are already threatening
to force another contest.
   A heavy turnout was reported Thursday as Ireland also selected
members of the European Parliament. Counting for the European
Parliament begins Sunday.
   Prime Minister Charles Haughey called the election in hope of
winning a majority in the Dail, or parliament, which would be his
first in five tries.
   Leaders of the other parties offered no support.
   Alan Dukes of the Fine Gael Party and Des O'Malley, leader of the
Progressive Democrats, declared on the eve of the election that they
would not vote for Haughey for another term.
   The Labor Party and the Workers Party also ruled out any support
for the 63-year-old Haughey and his Fianna Fail Party, in part
because of economic problems in Ireland.
   That raised the possibility of a split parliament, requiring yet
another election to break the impasse.
   Haughey needed 83 seats to gain control of the 26th Dail, which
has 166 members. The speaker customarily votes with the government
and is automatically elected.
   Fianna Fail controlled 80 seats when the 25th Dail was dissolved.
   Even if Haughey musters a majority, or woos enough independents
and minor party deputies to form a government, the cooperation that
marked the 25th parliament appeared to be shattered.
   Fine Gael and the Progressive Democratic party had supported
Haughey on his main economic policies.
   But the day before the election, a spokesman for those two
parties said Haughey could expect no help, ``in view of him having
cast aside the historic and unique consensus he and his government
enjoyed in the last Dail.''
</TEXT>
