<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   06-16 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0498,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Raids Palestinian Terrorist's Base Outside Sidon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with two children wounded,
details. Picks up graf 5 pvs, `Abu Nidal ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes blasted a base operated by
Palestinian terrorist Abu Nidal at dawn today in twin bombing runs.
Two children were reported wounded.
   Six U.S.-built Skyhawk jets swooped down for the raid on the
beachside Rashidiyeh refugee camp, police said.
   An army spokesman in Israel said the planes hit all the targets.
The spokesman said the base that was bombed had been used to launch
guerrilla attacks against Israel and its self-declared security zone
in southern Lebanon. The camp is 10 miles north of the Israeli
border.
   A spokesman for Abu Nidal's Fatah-Revolutionary Council said only
that Israeli warplanes bombed positions of his group within the camp.
   A police spokesman said a 5-year-old girl and a 6-year-old boy
were wounded in a two-story house. A nursery was also hit, but it
had not yet opened for the day and no one was injured there, he said.
   No casualty figure at the military base was immediately available.
   Lebanese police initially said the target was a base for the
Marxist Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine. However, they
later corrected that report, saying the base belonged to Nidal's
group.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri Banna, split from Yasir
Arafat's mainstream Fatah group of the Palestine Liberation
Organization in 1973. Three years later, he formed his underground
group.
   He has since been blamed for dozens of terrorist attacks across
Europe, Asia and the Middle East.
   The attacks include simultaneous assaults at Rome and Vienna
airports in 1985 that killed 20 people.
   Nidal guerrillas also were held responsible for seizing a Pan
American jumbo jet Sept. 5 at an airport in Karachi, Pakistan. The
terrorists opened fire inside the aircraft, killing 20 people.
   Today's attack was Israel's eighth on Lebanon this year. By
police count, nine people have been killed and 58 wounded in the
previous raids beginning Jan. 11.
   On Wednesday, Israeli warplanes bombed a guerrilla hideout used
by the Marxist Popular Front and three other radical Palestinian
factions in the Chouf mountains southeast of Beirut. Three
guerrillas were killed and nine wounded in that attack.
</TEXT>
