<FIRST>r a PM-ChineseDissident     06-16 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chinese Dissident,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Invitation Still Open for Dissident Chinese Astrophysicist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Colorado will keep open
its invitation to Chinese dissident Fang Lizhi to serve as a
visiting fellow even though the Chinese government revoked his
travel plans.
   Fang, 53, and his wife, Li Shuxian, took refuge June 5 in the
U.S. Embassy in Beijing after the Chinese government cracked down on
students demonstrating for democracy.
   The two were targeted by the Beijing prosecutor's office, which
said their presence inside the embassy would heighten tensions
between China and the United States.
   The university's Joint Institute for Laboratory Astrophysics
invited Fang, an astrophysicist, to participate in a six-month
fellowship from December 1988 to May 1989. The school invited Fang
on Feb. 11, 1988, and he accepted the fellowship eight days later.
He was expected to arrive Dec. 1.
   But Chinese officials stepped in and Fang notified the institute
by letter in October that permission for him to leave China had been
withdrawn.
   ``The reasons are completely political,'' the letter said.
   Because Fang is so prestigious in the field of astrophysics, the
institute said will keep the fellowship invitation open for three
years, hoping Fang will be allowed to travel within that period,
according to Chairman Peter Conti.
</TEXT>
