<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Drought     06-16 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northeast Summer Drought Now Remote, But Florida Reports Water Shortages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Northeast's rains this spring have filled reservoirs, making
the possibility of a summer drought remote, but Florida residents
have been asked to conserve water due to sparse rainfall.
   Officials have placed all of Florida except the Panhandle under
some water-use restrictions. Most restrictions are voluntary, but
many south and central areas of the state have banned lawn watering.
   In the Northeast, an unusually dry winter brought drought
emergency regulations. But since then many areas received record
amounts of rain.
   Now the reservoirs are nearly full.
   ``It just goes to show that weather is a fickle thing,'' said
Christopher Roberts of the Delaware River Basin Commission on
Thursday. ``One month you're in a drought, the next month you have
rivers and streams overflowing their banks. It's just a whimsical
element you're dealing with.''
   A drought warning issued Jan. 16 for 7 million people in
Delaware, New Jersey, New York and Pennsylvania who depend on the
Delaware River basin ended May 12, thanks to the spring rain.
   New York City declared a drought emergency in March after a dry
winter dropped reservoirs to 55 percent capacity. City reservoirs
are now at 97.1 percent capacity and the city has ended the drought
emergency.
   Massachusetts officials announced Tuesday that they were easing
restrictions but stopped short of declaring a formal end to the
drought emergency for the 2.5 million people in Boston and 43
surrounding communities that get water from the Quabbin Reservoir.
</TEXT>
