<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-McAnally     06-16 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-McAnally,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acclaimed Irish Actor, Cardinal in `The Mission,' Dead at 63</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ray McAnally, the Irish character actor
who won acclaim for his portrayal of the cardinal in the 1986 movie
``The Mission,'' died at his home in Ireland. He was 63.
   Police said he died Thursday night, but gave no cause. Irish
newspapers said he had undergone a heart bypass operation several
years ago, and collapsed at his cottage in County Wicklow shortly
after voting in Thursday's general election.
   McAnally was one of the most accomplished character actors on
British and Irish stage and screen in recent years.
   Born in County Donegal, Ireland, he was a stalwart of Dublin's
famous Abbey Theater when, in his 50's, he began to gain a wider
audience through cinema and television.
   Chameleon-like in his ability to shape himself into a role, he
was the cultured Cardinal Altimirano in ``The Mission,'' about
Christian missionaries in 18th-century South America; the hard-edged
Protestant work boss in the movie ``Cal,'' about Northern Ireland's
conflict; and the dissolute Englishman Rick Pym in the TV
serialization of John le Carre's ``A Perfect Spy.''
   He scored an unusual double in 1987 when he won the Evening
Standard Film Award for best actor in both ``The Mission'' and ``No
Surrender,'' a black comedy about elderly, feuding Northern
Irelanders.
   McAnally also won kudos in the role of a blue-collar Yorkshireman
who becomes prime minister in last year's TV series, ``A Very
British Coup.'' Both ``Coup'' and `A Perfect Spy'' were seen PBS-TV
last season.
   Last year, he brought George Bernard Shaw vividly to life on the
London stage, playing the great playwright opposite Sir John Gielgud
in the hit ``The Best of Friends.''
   He recently filmed ``Venus Peter,'' about a 1950's Scottish
village, and a television serialization of Charles Dickens' ``Great
Expectations.''
   McAnally made his stage debut at 18, acted in numerous
Shakespearean parts, and played more than 150 roles at the Abbey
from 1947 to 1963. He also spent time with the Royal Shakespeare
Company in London.
   Entering movies in 1938, he played supporting roles in ``Billy
Budd,'' and ``Shake Hands with the Devil,'' but only with ``The
Mission'' did he begin to make his name internationally.
   ``He sank himself into the character he was playing. Because of
that he played whatever character it was with tremendous belief,
conviction and extraordinary detail,'' said actress Vanessa Redgrave.
   Robert Carrickford, president of the Irish actors' union, called
him ``one of the finest character actors Ireland has ever produced.''
   McAnally was separated from his wife, actress Ronnie Masterson.
His sons, Conor and Aoghus, and daughters Maire and Niamh, were with
him when he died, police said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-16 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Thrash East Coast; Tornado Hits Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Powerful thunderstorms thrashed much of the eastern seaboard,
downing trees and power lines and spawning a tornado that injured
seven people in Pennsylvania.
   The storms developed Thursday evening in warm, moist air that
stretched from Florida to Pennsylvania. A funnel cloud touched down
in York County in southern Pennsylvania, destroying seven houses and
damaging six others across a 15-mile area, authorities reported.
   Michael Herr said he got his wife and two children into the
basement just before the tornado leveled their Manor Township home.
   ``The whole house just started shaking. In 30 seconds it was over
with,'' he said. ``The whole thing was gone.''
   Seven people were taken to hospitals with minor injuries.
   The tornado and associated thunderstorms knocked out power to
about 9,000 consumers in York and Lancaster counties, power
companies reported.
   Another round of thunderstorms in the Washington, D.C., area
hampered efforts to recover from Wednesday's big storm. An
additional 34,000 homes were left without power in the area, on top
of the 150,000 affected by the previous day's storm.
   Thunderstorm winds downed trees and power lines across much of
Florida, cutting power to 15,000 homes alone in Duval County, which
contains Jacksonville. The storms also damaged a half-dozen mobile
homes near Arcadia in south-central Florida.
   Strong storm winds also downed trees in Alabama, the Carolinas
and Virginia, where gusts reached up to 80 mph at Norfolk. In New
Jersey, winds gusted to 60 mph at Cumberland and blew the roof off a
house in Glassboro.
   Hail was widespread, with stones up to an inch in diameter
hitting Florida, South Carolina and Pennsylvania.
   This morning, showers and thunderstorms stretched from northwest
Florida to northern Georgia, and were over eastern South Carolina
and along the mid-Atlantic coast. Showers prevailed from the upper
Ohio Valley and the lower Great Lakes across New England.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were continuing over Idaho and
western Montana this morning after severe storms whipped the
northern Rockies Thursday.
   Storms in southern Idaho dropped 1{ inch hail north of Cascade,
breaking some car windows, and winds gusted to 87 mph in Oneida
County. A thunderstorm in western Montana dropped 1{ inch hail at
Holter Dam.
   The first tropical depression of the season formed in the
southwestern Gulf of Mexico Thursday evening, about 440 miles east
of Tampico, Mexico.
   Today's forecast called for widespread showers and thunderstorms
from the eastern Great Lakes across New England, the upper Ohio
Valley, the Appalachians and the Atlantic Coast into northern and
central Florida. Showers and thunderstorms, some heavy, were
expected from the western and central Carolinas into the Florida
Panhandle. Rain also was expected to be widespread across the
northern Rockies, Idaho and western parts of Washington and Oregon.
Showers and isolated thunderstorms were possible across the northern
and central Plains.
   Predicted highs: 60s along the central and northern Pacific Coast
into the northern Rockies, and from the Great Lakes into northern
New England; 90s in the central California valleys, much of Nevada
and Utah, and the Rio Grande Valley of Texas, and the central North
Carolina coast and much of the Florida Peninsula; and 100 to 110 in
the desert Southwest.
   Highs in the 70s and 80s were expected elsewhere.
   Temperatures at 2 a.m. EDT ranged from 40 degrees at Duluth,
Minn., to 95 at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 68 rain; Boston 56 foggy; Buffalo 58 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 72 cloudy; Cincinnati 61 cloudy; Cleveland 61 rain;
Detroit 61 foggy; Miami 82 windy; New York 63 foggy; Philadelphia 70
fair; Pittsburgh 63 foggy; Portland, Maine 50 rain; Washington 72
partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 55 partly cloudy; Chicago 54 foggy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 64 fair; Denver 63 fair; Des Moines 55 fair;
Indianapolis 56 partly cloudy; Kansas City 51 fair; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 59 cloudy; Nashville 63 cloudy; New Orleans 72 cloudy; St.
Louis 56 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 71 fair; Anchorage 51 partly cloudy; Las Vegas
91 windy; Los Angeles 62 foggy; Phoenix 95 fair; Salt Lake City 84
fair; San Diego 64 cloudy; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle 55 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 57 cloudy; Toronto 57 hazy.
</TEXT>
