<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0650EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DogExtortion     06-16 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dog Extortion,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Arrested For Allegedly Holding Woman's Dog</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheila Hawkins knew something was amiss
when Bentley, her 5-year-old miniature Yorkshire terrier, turned up
missing.
   Ms. Hawkins said she knew from the beginning that her dog had not
just run away. ``I was just hoping whoever had him wouldn't mistreat
him,'' she said.
   Ronnie Blackwell, 18, found his neighbor's missing dog and later
was arrested with three others and charged with conspiracy to commit
extortion. Blackwell allegedly tried to force the owner to up the
reward to $200 and set up a drop at a gas station.
   But his intent wasn't malicious, officials said.
   Blackwell told police he had grown fond of the shaggy little dog
he said he found near the Spartanburg Library last week. After
inquiring about how much the dog's owner was prepared to pay for its
return, he apparently decided to keep the dog.
   ``He said he had become really attached to the dog and felt if he
kept upping the price the lady would just think the dog wasn't worth
it,'' said Detective Audrey McNair of the Spartanburg Police
Department.
   Bentley had been missing since June 8. Three days later, Ms.
Hawkins received a call from a man who said he had the dog and would
bring him to her house for the $50 reward she had promised on
fliers, authorities said.
   He never arrived.
   Instead, a woman called three different times Sunday and told Ms.
Hawkins, ``We have the dog,'' and that the $50 reward was not
enough, police said.
   During one phone call, a man said the captors wanted $200,
according to police.
   Ms. Hawkins agreed to the price, but the dog was not returned.
   During one of the phone calls Sunday, a woman identified herself
as a mother whose son had found the dog and was very attached to
him. Ms. McNair said the caller was Blackwell's girlfriend, Rebecca
Entsminger, 18, who was also charged with conspiracy to commit
extortion.
   Ms. Hawkins, a 30-year-old hair stylist, said Wednesday she
offered to give the callers a puppy the next time she had Bentley
bred. But they were not interested, she said.
   A relative of one of the captors saw a television news report
Tuesday about the missing dog and apparently convinced the four to
return it, authorities said. They called Ms. Hawkins to say they
would give Bentley back that night.
   Ms. Hawkins got a call Tuesday night telling her to go to a local
gasoline station to get her dog.
   Ms. McNair, who was at Ms. Hawkins' home at the time of the call,
rode with her to the station, where three suspects were arrested and
the dog was recovered in good condition. Miss Entsminger was later
arrested when she came to the police station.
   Also charged with the misdemeanor conspiracy offense were
Blackwell's sister, Theresa Blackwell, 19, and Kipling Messer, 19.
   They have been released on a $2,000 bond each, Ms. McNair said.
   Conspiracy to commit extortion carries a maximum penalty of five
years in prison or up to a $5,000 fine.
</TEXT>
