<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0703EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Subways     06-16 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Subways,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Commuters Battle Subway Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Subway drivers today mounted their sixth 24-hour
strike in two months to back pay demands, creating travel chaos for
city commuters.
   Although more subways were running than during the previous
strikes, many commuters were forced to use cars, buses, trains and
their feet to get to work.
   Spokesman Roger Shire of London Underground, which runs the
subway system, called the strike ``sheer anarchy at the public's
expense.''
   Some bus drivers in south London also staged a wildcat walkout.
   The subway dispute centers on introduction of driver-only trains.
   Drivers want a $99 weekly increase for operating without a guard.
Management is offering $46 with extra vacation.
   In another labor dispute, the National Union of Railwaymen has
called a 24-hour strike by its 75,000 rail workers for Wednesday.
   It is protesting British Rail's refusal to increase its pay offer
above 7 percent.
   On the same day, the union's 10,500 members employed by London
Underground have been called out over management proposals to change
working and promotion rules.
</TEXT>
