<FIRST>r a PM-Navajos-MacDonald     06-16 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navajos-MacDonald,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navajo Chairman Arraigned on Tribal Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navajo chairman has pleaded
innocent to tribal charges accusing him of violating court orders
that barred him from acting as chairman after he was suspended by
the Tribal Council.
   Peter MacDonald, facing seven counts of interfering with judicial
process, was released on his own recognizance after he appeared
Thursday before Window Rock District Judge Robert Yazzie, officials
said.
   A July 7 pretrial conference was scheduled, said Duane Beyal,
spokesman for interim Chairman Leonard Haskie.
   A Tribal Council majority placed MacDonald on administrative
leave with pay Feb. 17 after U.S. Senate hearing testimony indicated
MacDonald accepted kickbacks and gifts from parties doing business
with the tribe.
   Beyal said the charges, filed by tribal Prosecutor Melvin Tso
Scott, accuse MacDonald of failing to comply with court orders
stemming from the council's decision.
   MacDonald has denied any wrongdoing and contends the council
action was illegal under tribal law. However, tribal courts have
upheld the council's placement of MacDonald and Vice Chairman Johnny
R. Thompson on leave and its appointment of Haskie as interim
chairman.
   MacDonald specifically is accused of violating a temporary
restraining order and a preliminary injunction issued by Yazzie. The
orders prohibited MacDonald and other tribal officials from entering
tribal offices and carrying out their offices' duties. Yazzie also
restrained MacDonald from using tribal airplanes and resources.
   The U.S. attorney's office in Phoenix has been conducting a grand
jury investigation of tribal finances under MacDonald's
chairmanship, but assistant U.S. attorney Allen Stooks said the
office was not involved in the tribal proceedings. Stooks declined
to discuss the grand jury investigation.
</TEXT>
