<FIRST>r a PM-BishopsConference 1stLd-Writethru a0487 06-16 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bishops Conference, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0487,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Conference of Catholic Bishops to Discuss AIDS, Religious
Disputes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with conference under way with Mass.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Roman Catholic bishops are
aiming to tackle a number of lingering controversies, including what
their stand should be on AIDS education and how to settle disputes
with religion teachers.
   About 300 cardinals, archbishops and bishops gathered today at
Seton Hall in South Orange for the National Conference of Catholic
Bishops, opening the conference with a morning Mass. The meeting
ends Monday.
   Tension has increased over the last few years between the bishops
and religion teachers, some of whom have been disciplined for
advocating birth control and female priests, and taking other stands
that contradict church teachings.
   ``The doctrinal statement hopes to resolve these types of things
without doing too much damage,'' said Bob Wonderly, spokesman for
the bishops conference. ``In recent years there has seemingly been
an increase in these types of cases, at least in perception.''
   The dispute itself indicates a shift within the church.
   During a conference in 1968, the bishops specified the right of
priests and laymen to disagree with the church in the classroom. But
that right has since been questioned and theologians have been
punished for doing so.
   The policy to be considered this weekend would not solve disputes
over specific issues, but would establish procedure for settling
such arguments.
   In a widely publicized case, the Rev. Charles Curran was barred
from teaching theology at the Catholic University of America in
Washington. The university's action came after the Vatican strongly
criticized him for his positions on abortion, homosexuality and
other matters of sexual ethics.
   Disputes within the church have not been confined to the bishops
and theologians. The bishops themselves were divided over a
statement on AIDS issued by the group's 50-member administrative
board in December 1987.
   The AIDS statement insists on the church's teaching that the only
sure safeguards against contracting the disease are abstinence from
sex before marriage and fidelity within a marriage.
   But one paragraph said public education programs, directed at
people who may reject church standards, could include information
about condoms, which most medical experts say can help prevent the
disease.
   Critics charged this paragraph implied approval of condoms, which
the church has condemned as a form of birth control. Defenders
insist the document did not approve condoms, but said that they were
an alternative to halting the spread of the deadly disease.
   The bishops plan to issue a new report on the topic Saturday.
   The bishops also are scheduled to vote on a statement calling for
a normalization of relations between the United States and Vietnam,
said Michael Hurley, spokesman for the Newark Archdiocese.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
