<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     06-16 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Threatens to Attack Highways After Shells Hit Tanker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun today
threatened to attack roads to Syria's capital after Syrian shells
hit a tanker carrying gasoline to the Christian area. A sailor was
missing and presumed dead.
   ``Roads leading to capitals of occupation (forces) will not be
safe henceforth,'' the army commander said in a statement broadcast
by the state-run radio.
   ``We shall confront this foreign enemy with the courage of a
warrior at the front,'' Aoun said.
   The roads between Damascus, the capital of Syria, and Lebanon are
vital to Syria's 40,000 troops in Lebanon, stationed there under a
1976 peacekeeping mandate. Attacking the highways would mark a sharp
escalation in the 3-month-old confrontation between Aoun's mainly
Christian army units and an alliance of Syrian and Druse Moslem
militiamen.
   Aoun did not spell out how he would strike. His artillery has
shelled the network of roads, mainly in the Syrian-controlled Bekaa
Valley of east Lebanon, but he could also use hit-and-run commando
raids, land mines or car bombs on the highways.
   Syrian shells hit the oil tanker late Thursday, and the ship
burned out of control through the night. Firefighters brought the
blaze under control today, but the 660,000 gallons of badly needed
gasoline were lost.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations, identified the vessel as the Timex Star.
   But Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit in London, which monitors
shipping around the world, said its agents in Beirut identified the
ship as the 1,507-ton tanker Chemicoral, owned by the Chemicoral Co.
of Piraeus, Greece.
   Officials rescued nine Indian and four Lebanese sailors who
abandoned the burning vessel, but an Indian crewman was missing and
presumed dead, said the police spokesman.
   The Christian enclave suffers from an acute shortage of fuel
because the main depots in the east Beirut neighborhood of Dora were
devastated by Syrian shellfire March 30.
   The ship was hit about 500 yards off Tabarja, a tiny port 15
miles north of Beirut.
   Syrian gunners shelled the Christian coastline again today, but
no casualties were reported.
   Syrian and Moslem militia forces have been battling Aoun's forces
in the latest round of Lebanon's civil war.
   The outbreak in fighting, which began March 8, has killed 372
people and wounded 1,450 wounded.
</TEXT>
