<FIRST>r a PM-INS-Drugs     06-16 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-INS-Drugs,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigration Employees Among Nine Indicted on Federal Drug Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven employees at an Immigration and
Naturalization Service detention center were among those indicted on
federal drug charges after a six-month undercover investigation,
authorities said.
   The sealed indictments were returned Tuesday and were ordered
unsealed Thursday after all but one had been arrested.
   The indictments allege that cocaine and marijuana were sold to an
undercover agent, Assistant U.S. Attorney John Crews said.
   ``The amounts of drugs are relatively small,'' he said. ``What
makes it exceptionally significant, to us, however, is that the
offenses are alleged to have occurred either at the service
processing center or by individuals employed by the United States.
And it's the position of this office that any amount is too much
when it comes to that.''
   Crews said no detainees were involved in the alleged offenses.
   In all, nine people were named in the indictments, officials
said. Seven had worked either for the INS or a private security
company at the Port Isabel Service Processing Center, where
undocumented aliens are detained before deportation, authorities
said.
   The center has a detainee population of about 1,300.
   Eight suspects appeared Thursday before U.S. Magistrate Fidencio
Garza and each was released on a $10,000 unsecured bond. Garza
scheduled arraignments for Wednesday.
   The two employees still working for the INS have been suspended
until the matter is resolved, said INS spokeswoman Virginia Kice.
She said the INS initiated the investigation after becoming
suspicious of activity at the detention center.
   Officials said no more indictments are expected in the case,
which stemmed from a six-month undercover investigation by the
Justice Department's Office of Inspector General.
</TEXT>
