<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Gorbachev     06-16 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Gorbachev,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Predicts Conventional Arms Accord Within a Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Germany-Gorbachev Postscript, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl, euphoric over
the recent visit by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, predicted
today there will be an East-West accord on reducing conventional
forces in Europe within a year.
   In a parliamentary address recapping the Gorbachev visit, Kohl
also sharpened his denunciation of the crackdown by Chinese
officials on pro-democracy demonstrators, calling it a ``relapse
into unmasked suppression.''
   Kohl and his main political opponents were united in their
celebration of Gorbachev's four-day visit.
   Kohl said Gorbachev's visit was a ``huge and important success''
that would ``widen the trust between the two nations and
governments.''
   The chancellor also said he and Gorbachev ``were in agreement
that the Vienna negotiations on (reducing) conventional weapons must
be carried out with all energy. We decided to remain in close
personal contact over this matter.''
   Kohl said he and Gorbachev agreed it is possible to forge an
initial agreement on reducing conventional forces within six to 12
months and for its terms to be carried out through 1992 and 1993.
   At a NATO summit in Brussels last month, President Bush announced
a major disarmament initiative aimed at producing a conventional
forces agreement at the East-West negotiations in Vienna within a
year.
   In his wide-ranging parliamentary speech, Kohl again criticized
the killing of Chinese students by troops in Beijing and the arrests
resulting from the crackdown on the pro-democracy movement.
   ``The peaceful protest by thousands of students and workers was
strangled by tanks. And now a decreed wave of denunciations and
planned arrests has begun,'' Kohl said.
   ``We mourn for the victims with all Chinese in the world and
denounce with all friends of China this relapse into unmasked
suppression,'' Kohl said.
   Gorbachev returned to the Soviet Union on Thursday after
receiving an enthusiastic welcome on every stop of his West German
visit.
   Gorbachev is the most popular foreign leader among West Germans,
who view him as the most important element in a new atmosphere of
peace and trust in East-West relations.
   Even West Germany's opposition Social Democrats, normally at odds
with Kohl, congratulated the chancellor for his talks with Gorbachev.
   A veteran member of the opposition Social Democrats, former
Chancellor Willy Brandt, said Gorbachev's trip was ``a success for
the federal government, which we applaud.''
   Brandt also reminded Parliament that as chancellor he was the
architect of the first postwar thaw between West Germany and the
Soviet-led East bloc, which earned him the 1971 Nobel Peace Prize.
   West German relations with the Soviets slid again in the early
1980s following Bonn's decision to permit the deployment of new NATO
missiles.
</TEXT>
