<FIRST>r a PM-RunawayFire 1stLd-Writethru a0554 06-16 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Runaway Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0554,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prescribed Burn Escapes Firefighters, Blazes Out Of Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with fire contained. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, `San Bernardino ...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HEMET, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that was supposed to be a controlled
blaze to clear brush leaped fire lines, charring at least 400 acres
and injuring at least three people before being contained early
today, forest officials said.
   The fire in Bautista Canyon 10 miles southeast of Hemet was
ignited Thursday afternoon in heavy brush known as chaparral and had
blackened 400 acres by early today, said Tom Sintaffar, a dispatcher
for the San Bernardino National Forest.
   About 500 firefighters were battling the blaze and had it
contained by 6 a.m. They expected to have it extinguished by
Saturday, Sintaffar said.
   San Bernardino National Forest officials intentionally set the
fire to clear bursh, but it escaped their control, said Forest
Service spokeswoman Lindsay Maierhofer.
   ``This happens very rarely, because prescribed burns are
conducted under very controlled conditions. Apparently they got some
unexpected winds,'' she said.
   Winds had calmed overnight, but firefighters were anticipating
dry, hot temperatures and the possibility of the wind kicking up
later in the day, Sintaffar said.
   Two firefighter suffered minor injuries and a California
Department of Corrections prison inmate fighting the fire broke a
leg in a fall, said Sintaffar and Maierhofer.
   Sintaffar said no structures were in danger early today, although
reports Thursday indicated there had been some threat to scattered
small homes and a U.S. Forest Service training facility and station.
</TEXT>
