<FIRST>u i PM-SAfrica-SowetoDay 3rdLd-Writethru   06-16 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Soweto Day, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0536,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Work Boycott Marks 13th Anniversary of Soweto Riots</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with reports of sporadic violence. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businesses shut down as thousands of
blacks stayed away from work today to observe a self-declared
national holiday on the 13th anniversary of the Soweto township
riots.
   Police reported sporadic violence in several areas.
   A group of blacks apparently attempting to enforce the work
stoppage fatally stabbed a black motorist in Guguletu, a township
outside Cape Town, police said.
   Police used tear gas to disperse 3,000 people who attended a
rally at the Regina Mundi Roman Catholic Church in Soweto, the huge
township outside Johannesburg. Police also fired tear gas to break
up a church service outside Durban, witnesses said.
   Vandals during the night smashed the tombstone of Hector
Pieterson, a 13-year-old boy who was the first person killed in 1976
when police fired at students protesting the requirement that they
be taught in Afrikaans, the language of the white Afrikaners who
dominate the government.
   Friends said the smashed grave marker at Avalon Cemetery in
Soweto was discovered when Pieterson's mother arrived to place
flowers on the grave today.
   Commonly known as ``Soweto Day,'' June 16 has no official status
as a holiday. But many businesses closed because so many black
workers and customers take the day off. Hundreds of employers have
negotiated contracts with workers to make it a paid holiday, while
others have adopted a ``no work, no pay, no disciplinary action''
policy on June 16.
   ``The anniversary must be used not as a weapon in a war of
bitterness, but as a repeated catalyst for constructive change,''
The Star, the country's largest daily, said in an editorial.
   ``Freedom for all remains an unattainable goal unless the
government is willing to break away from the basic concepts of
apartheid,'' it added.
   In the major cities of Johannesburg, Durban and Cape Town, black
commuter traffic was less than half the weekday average, according
to various estimates. Bus stops, railway stations, and taxi stands
were unusually empty. Black schools nationwide were deserted.
   Buses in Durban traveled under police escort to prevent attacks
by black militants attempting to enforce the work stoppage.
   The 1976 Soweto riots spread nationwide and an estimated 700
blacks were killed in the ensuing months, a period that brought a
new level of militancy to the anti-apartheid movement.
   Thousands of blacks fled the country at that time to join the
outlawed African National Congress guerrilla movement, the main
black group attempting to undermine the white-led government.
   The country's largest black-oriented daily newspaper, The
Sowetan, said Thursday in an editorial: ``Thirteen years ago we went
through a bloodbath over the country's education system _ to this
day very little has changed.''
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 5 million whites exercise
political and economic control over 28 million blacks. Whites
maintain segregated schools, neighborhoods and hospitals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
