<FIRST>u w PM-Republicans 2ndLd-Writethru a0537 06-16 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Republicans, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0537,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republicans Commend Atwater</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with committee action, Atwater speech; picks
up 2nd graf pvs, Most committee members.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans today commended GOP National
Chairman Lee Atwater for his aggressive leadership and said he had
been subjected to ``unremitting attacks'' from Democrats.
   Atwater repeated his call for the election of a Cuban-American to
succeed the late Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., a stance termed
inflammatory by a Democratic state senator.
   Members of the Republican National Committee adopted a resolution
commending Atwater's leadership and saying it had made him ``the
target of unremitting attacks from Democrats and their surrogates.''
   In debate on the resolution, Jack London, the GOP national
committeeman from Arizona, praised what he called Atwater's courage
and asked, ``Why do you think the Democrats want to get rid of him?''
   Atwater pledged that ``every ounce of energy I have is going to
be dedicated to doing the best job I can to promote this party.''
   Atwater said at a meeting of the Cuban-American National
Foundation in Washington on Tuesday that he gave priority to the
election of a Cuban-American to Pepper's seat.
   ``I'm saying it again because I believe it,'' Atwater told the
GOP committee today. ``I believe there is a place in the U.S.
Congress for a Cuban-American and if the Democrats don't like that,
fine ... they can keep attacking me and keep attacking me and keep
attacking me.''
   On Thursday, a Democratic state senator, Jack Gordon, withdrew
from the race to succeed Pepper and attacked Atwater's call for the
election of a Cuban-American.
   ``No statement would more inflame a city that has more tension
and antagonism than it can possibly deal with right now,'' Gordon
said, calling Atwater's statement ``outrageous'' and
``irresponsible.''
   Atwater, however, said, ``I think it would be great if we could
elect a Cuban-American to Congress, and this party is dedicated to
doing that.''
   Atwater made no mention of the controversial memo sent out from
the RNC office earlier this month attacking the voting record of
Speaker of the House Thomas S. Foley. The resolution commending him
also made no direct mention of the memo.
   Most committee members and state GOP chairmen interviewed as they
opened the two-day meeting predicted Atwater would ride out the
controversy generated by the memo comparing the new House speaker's
voting record to that of Rep. Barney Frank.
   Critics of the memo say it was unfair because it was headed ``Tom
Foley: Out of the Liberal Closet'' and Frank, a Massachusetts
Democrat, is an acknowledged homosexual.
   An Atwater aide, Mark Goodin, resigned after saying he had
approved the memo. Democrats have called on President Bush to fire
Atwater, but the president has said he accepts the chairman's
statement that the memo was written and mailed without his knowledge.
   Donald Devine, chairman of the conservative political action
group Citizens for America, told reporters at Thursday's session,
``I would say he (Atwater) is home safe.''
   ``He may take a low profile but his real talent is organizing and
setting plans, and for that he doesn't need to be on the front
page,'' Devine said. ``I would be personally upset if he did not
stay on as chairman.''
   Michigan State Republican Chairman E. Spencer Abraham said he did
not believe the distribution of the memo would cause continuing
problems for Atwater.
   ``I think everybody agrees it was inappropriate and I think the
proper actions were taken and Mark Goodin resigned and that's the
end of it,'' the Michigan chairman said.
   However, Richard M. Rosenbaum, the national committeeman from New
York, said, ``I find what happened to be very embarrassing and
regrettable.'' Asked if the incident would be crippling to Atwater,
Rosenbaum said: ``I don't know. It's still a little early to get a
real consensus.''
   Jennifer Dunn, the Republican chairwoman in Foley's home state of
Washington, said she had received ``very few calls'' about the memo.
   ``It was a very unfortunate thing, but I think it turned into a
media issue and a Democratic issue,'' Ms. Dunn said.
</TEXT>
