<FIRST>u w PM-RobinHUD 2ndLd-Writethru a0587 06-16 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Robin HUD, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0587,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Starts HUD Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs graf 7, HUD has not, to include first reference to Adams.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private escrow agent nicknamed ``Robin HUD''
told Congress today she considers her diversion of millions of
dollars from government housing programs ``sin'' and intends to
repay the money.
   And the inspector general at the Department of Housing and Urban
Development said accountability problems in the agency that
permitted such schemes still exist.
   ``I, in no way, justify what I have done as being anything less
than sin,'' Marilyn Harrell told the House subcommittee on housing
and employment, adding that she expected ``no leniency or immunity
from prosecution.''
   ``Allow me to state, for the record, that I do _ regardless of
where my life takes me from here _ intend to repay in full all
monies taken,'' she said.
   Harrell, who has admitted to investigators that she did not
forward at least $5.5 million to the federal housing agency,
repeated claims that she donated much of the money to charitable
projects to provide housing for the poor.
   ``What was spent over and above what we needed to run the company
was directed legitimately to help the poor and homeless and assist
those ministries that did the same,'' she said.
   ``HUD has not established effective monitoring systems to assure
that closing agents properly carry out their responsibilities,''
said Paul Adams, inspector general at the department.
   ``Moreover, planned changes to its automated systems have been
slow, and current systems do not contain all information field
offices need to properly monitor agent activities,'' he added.
   ``I would be surprised if this would be the end of the
revelations,'' said subcommittee chairman Tom Lantos, D-Calif.
   Last week four senior HUD employees in the Washington, D.C.,
field office were placed on administrative leave after HUD
investigators found escrow agents may have embezzled as much as $10
million through the program without being noticed.
   Washington authorities also want to question Earl Martin, an
attorney who has been missing for about a year about the
disappearance of another $3 million.
   Another agent has been indicted by a federal grand jury in Fort
Worth, Texas, on charges of stealing $2.5 million from the sales of
55 homes in the Dallas area.
   ``It appears that HUD monitored these settlement agents with the
same vigilance Exxon used in watching over the skippers of its
tankers,'' said Lantos, comparing former HUD Secretary Samuel
Pierce's tenure at the agency to the recent Alaska oil spill.
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp reportedly has ordered all 53 field
offices to conduct reviews and give an accounting for all proceeds
from the sales of the agency's property.
   On Thursday, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh also ordered
federal prosecutors to examine the property-sales programs for
evidence of criminal fraud and embezzlement.
   HUD already is reeling from allegations of mismanagement,
favoritism and influence-peddling in the administration of a
rehabilitation program to renovate housing for the nation's poor.
   Lantos decided to proceed with hearings on the property-sales
program despite Adams' objections they might endanger the agency's
probe.
   ``I rarely find that it jeopardizes an investigation,
particularly if you're not granting use immunity,'' said
subcommittee member Christopher Shays, R-Conn.
   ``The more we investigate the more we uncover. It just doesn't
seem to end.''
</TEXT>
