<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-Rhetoric 1stLd-Writethru a0513 06-16 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Rhetoric, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0513,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Media Rhetoric Against Dissidents Heats Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts grafs 1-5 to clarify that editorials aimed at influening
people's view of protesters. Pickup graf 6, ``But today's...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Editorials in China's official media in the past
few days indicate the leadership wants to turn the public against
people the authorities have branded counterrevolutionaries.
   ``A gang of political hoodlums, the evil remnants of the Gang of
Four and other dregs of society,'' is how the People's Daily
described students and supporters, now condemned for seeking greater
political freedoms.
   The Gang of Four were the radical leaders of the 1966-76 violent
far-left Cultural Revolution.
   One of the four, Yao Wenyuan, was a former journalist who became
known for the kind of vitriolic editorials that have appeared three
straight days on the front page of the People's Daily, the Communist
Party paper.
   Some Chinese said privately that the recent string of editorials
were not up to the standard of Yao and other Cultural Revolution
propagandists, who condemned so-called class enemies with a wide
range of epithets including ``cow demon and snake spirit.''
   But today's editorial called the protesters an ``ideological
pimple'' and said the words of senior leader Deng Xiaoping, who
ordered the crackdown, were ``the most powerful ideological weapon
for lancing (it).''
   Biting language also was used to condemn two American reporters
who were ordered out of the country. The Economic Daily called John
Pomfret of The Associated Press and Alan Pessin of the Voice of
America ``gods of plague'' who took advantage of and stirred up
``naive, pure and innocent'' students.
   ``They spread the plague to Tiananmen Square, to all of China and
the whole world. It is time to sterilize it,'' the paper said.
   The name-calling reflected traditional emphasis on names and
labels, but also an urgent drive to convince anyone still in doubt
about the correctness of the crackdown. Several editorials played on
fears of a return to past turmoil.
   ``If (the protesters') plot had succeeded, greater turmoil and
division would have occurred nationwide and the people's republic
that was paid for with the lives of countless martyrs would have
been destroyed in a single day,'' the People's Daily fumed Thursday,
``and the whole nation would have been enveloped in a `white
terror.'''
   ``White terror'' was a reference to Nationalist executions and
imprisonments of communist underground workers during the civil war
in the 1930's and '40s.
   ``If we show weakness or turn backward in the face of capitalist
attack ... the achievements of 40 years of socialism would be wiped
out in a single day and China would once again become a dependency
of imperialism,'' said today's editorial.
   ``Some comrades haven't opened up their minds and are still
confused about certain issues,'' it said. ``Abroad there is
anti-Chinese and anti-Communist clamor, and in China there is a
market for every kind of rumor.''
   For these comrades, Beijing television continued its expanded
nightly news report, double the usual 15 minutes, while the usual
30-minute national news ran more than an hour. Most of the
television reports have shown arrests of protesters, visits by top
officials to soldiers enforcing martial law, and workers gathered to
study Deng's recent speech applauding the crackdown.
   In one report, a group of workers in hardhats clapped hands and
sang the children's song, ``Without the Communist Party, there would
be no new China.''
   Most newspapers have been published with only four pages instead
of their usual eight for the past week because of a shortage of
newsprint caused by martial law-related disruptions in
transportation. But almost all the space has been taken up by
stories related to the crackdown.
</TEXT>
