<FIRST>u i PM-China-Shooting 2ndLd-Writethru a0566 06-16 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Shooting, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0566,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Gives Contradictory Accounts of Army Shooting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to give details of how general's comments
were obtained. Pickup 11th graf pvs, `Reporters who...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY CHENAULT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army general told Western reporters today that
soldiers of the People's Liberation Army fired on unarmed civilians
in Tiananmen Square, then he contradicted himself and denied troops
shot at the protesters.
   In the government's first news conference for Western reporters
since it began cracking down on the movement for democracy, Gen. Li
Zhiyun said troops were forced to use violence to enter the city
because ``people who didn't know the truth'' blocked them on the
outskirts of Beijing.
   Li said soldiers in tanks and armored personnel carriers later
``exercised restraint'' while clearing student-led demonstrators
from Tiananmen June 3-4.
   ``But still there were some thugs, they (were) still provocative
to the troops. At this time, some of the soldiers in our troops
directed their fire into the square and especially those troops that
have wounded or dead soldiers within their troops,'' the army
spokesman said.
   ``The rest of the soldiers started to fire on those thugs who
were provocative to them.''
   But at another point during the news conference inside the Great
Hall of the People, Le said of the deaths: ``It is not from any
instances from the soldiers directing their guns at the people. This
incident (soldiers firing on citizens) never happened within the
area of Beijing.''
   Li did not clarify the contradiction.
   No news agency reporters were allowed to attend the news
conference or join a subsequent tour of Tiananmen Square. Associated
Press reporters viewed a videotape by CBS television that showed Li
speaking in Chinese and another army official translating his
remarks.
   The government previously denied firing a single shot inside
Tiananmen Square, but has not commented on shooting elsewhere in the
city. Some of the heaviest fighting was a mile away, where civilians
threw firebombs at tanks rolling through barricades erected by
people trying to protect the students.
   The military-sponsored tour of Tiananmen gave selected foreign
reporters their first look at the vast plaza since the military
moved to crush the pro-democracy demonstrations there.
   Reporters who were in the square the night of the crackdown said
there appeared to be less firing there than in other parts of the
city, possibly because the army was trying to avoid scarring it.
   There were reports in the Hong Kong media that tanks rolled over
tents in which students were sleeping, and that soldiers later
burned the bodies. However, Western reporters said they only saw
tanks roll over piles of bedding, but were not sure if people were
crushed.
   All Western reporters fled the square shortly before dawn, after
the army had begun moving into it.
   The government says variously that 200 to 300 people died June
3-4, and that most of those killed were soldiers. Unofficial Chinese
and Western intelligence reports say troops fired on unarmed crowds,
killing up to 3,000 people.
   Li said snipers on buildings on the edge of the square opened
fire on soldiers.
   ``In the process of clearing up the blockade (on the square),
some of the thugs, they throw bricks and stones onto the soldiers
and they use sticks to beat up soldiers. Sometimes there were
gunshots from the high buildings.
   ``Some of the soldiers were beaten until they fainted, and even
some were beaten until death,'' Li said.
   Reporters saw soldiers firing indiscriminately at crowds as the
troops moved toward the square.
   Students had occupied the 100-acre square for several weeks
before the crackdown. Tiananmen is in the center of Beijing and is
the symbolic heart of China. On one side stands the former Imperial
Palace; on another is the Great Hall of the People, the current seat
of government.
   Beijing television said the cleanup at the square had been
completed, but it did not say when it would be reopened to the
public. Authorities opened the streets around the square on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
