<FIRST>u a PM-SwindallTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0580 06-16 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Swindall Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0580,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Closing Arguments Held In Swindall Trial; Jury Could Get Case Today</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with defense closing arguments.
Picks up 10th graf pvs, `One juror ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor in the perjury trial of Pat
Swindall told jurors today that the former congressman got deeply
involved in negotiations for an illegal money deal and lied
repeatedly about it to a federal grand jury.
   But Swindall's attorneys argued that, throughout his grand jury
testimony, he acknowledged the very matters he is charged with
trying to conceal. And they accused the government of vindictive
prosecution.
   In his closing statement at the 4-week-old trial, prosecutor
Craig Gillen detailed for the jury the nine perjury counts against
Swindall. The two-term Republican lost his congressional seat in
Atlanta's eastern suburbs to Democrat Ben Jones last November.
   Gillen began by citing Swindall's testimony that he was ``never
satisfied with respect to criminality'' of the proposed money deal.
   But the prosecutor said after Swindall was told to his face that
the money he was seeking was the product of narcotics trafficking,
``What does the former representative from the Fourth District have
to say? ... He says, `I can assure you that anything you tell me is
in total confidence.'''
   The undercover agent at that meeting was ``telling this to a
citizen, a lawyer, a United States congressman. Did Patrick L.
Swindall know it was illegal? He sure did,'' said Gillen.
   Gillen also slammed Swindall for telling the grand jury he didn't
recall being told narcotics dollars were involved, even though tapes
played for the jury showed that statement was made to him three
times at a posh West Virginia resort.
   ``Do you think you would remember,'' Gillen asked the jury, ``if
you took a walk with a man you believed to be a criminal at one of
the ritziest resorts in America? He tells you narcotics dollars are
involved ... and what he does violates currency laws. Do you think
you would remember? Do you think you could ever forget?''
   In a closing statement for the defense, attorney Tom Thrash
charged that the U.S. attorney's office was ``trying to add a former
congressman to the trophy case. Truth, justice, fairness is all
thrown out the window in their desperation to convict Mr. Swindall.''
   Thrash discussed each of the counts in the indictment, as Gillen
had, but he pointed to numerous times during the grand jury
testimony when Swindall acknowledged details that he elsewhere said
he could not recall.
   He urged the jury to look at Swindall's testimony in its entirety
and ask themselves, ``Did he have a specific intent to lie? ...
You've got to believe that he did not. He would not have said what
he said if it was his intent to deceive the grand jury.''
   Another defense attorney, Richard Hendrix, said Swindall was
tired on the day of his grand jury testimony and that the former
congressman's attorney had tried to get the testimony delayed
because of Swindall's condition. He said Swindall ``did the best he
could.''
   The judge was to instruct the jurors after a lunch break, and
they could get the case as early as this afternoon.
   One juror was excused this morning and will be replaced by an
alternate after he reported that a friend had approached him to talk
about the case.
   Swindall is charged with nine counts of perjury in his Feb. 2,
1988, testimony to a federal grand jury investigating his dealings
with undercover agent Mike Mullaney, posing as a drug-money
launderer, and with Swindall associate Charles LeChasney, later
convicted of money laundering and awaiting sentence. LeChasney
cooperated with prosecutors in Swindall's case.
   Swindall, 38, faces 10 months to five years in prison on each of
the nine counts. Under federal sentencing guidelines which apply to
the case, a conviction brings prison time.
   He negotiated over a period of one month in August and September
1987, seeking $850,000 from the undercover agent's sources for
construction work on the then-congressman's luxurious suburban home.
The money was to go to Swindall through a mortgage company set up by
LeChasney, according to testimony.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
