<FIRST>r w AM-GarbageMagazine     06-16 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Garbage Magazine,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Throwaway Society Gets a Magazine of Its Own</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new magazine, called Garbage, is coming along
to worry about the ecology of diapers and whether the gasoline you
burn driving to the recycling center does more damage to the
environment than recycling the old newspapers will do good.
   It is intended for people like its editor-publisher, Patricia
Poore, who says she worries about how much she throws away.
   ``I think,'' says Ms. Poore, ``we all feel vaguely uneasy and
vaguely guilty when you bring the groceries home and realize that 60
percent of what you've bought is packaging.''
   She thinks there are plenty of potential readers who worry about
what the throwaway society is doing to the quality of life _ to use
two buzzwords of the environmental movement.
   The magazine's full name is Garbage: The Practical Journal for
the Environment. It will start publishing in August.
   Ms. Poore promises the magazine will look at both sides _ the
downside as well as the benefits of environmental actions _ despite
its basic bias.
   ``You have to be pro-environment if you want any quality of life
and possibly if you want any life at all,'' she says.
   When an environmentally sound way of doing things turns out to be
more costly or more inconvenient, Garbage won't whitewash that fact,
Ms. Poore says. ``There often is no easy solution.''
   To show the conflicts that can arise even among those who want to
do the environmentally correct thing, Ms. Poore points to her own
quandry over whether to print the magazine on recycled paper. The
answer may seem obvious, Ms. Poore says, but it was not easy.
   ``The editor in me wanted recycled paper,'' she says. ``The
publisher in me didn't.
   ``Recycled paper looks like whole wheat,'' she says, in her
publisher's pose. ``It has gooky things in it. They say it will
break on the press.
   ``The publisher in me said there was nothing wrong with premium
paper. And the printer told us they would charge 30 percent more to
print it on recycled paper!''
   But the art director and the managing editor confronted her and
said she would be a hypocrite to use virgin paper.
   And the printer, in environmentally conscience Burlington, Vt.,
relented and promised to charge no extra for the first three issues
and see how things come out.
   Further research found ``cross-pointe troy book paper,'' a
recycled paper that ``is very white, and film coated and is easily
recyclable itself,'' Ms. Poore says, so the environment (and the
editor) won the battle, for the moment.
   Ms. Poore is the owner and publisher of The Old-House Journal. It
was a neighborhood paper for owners of brownstones in Brooklyn, N.Y.
when she bought it 11 years ago, just as the preservation movement
was catching on. It now has a circulation ``approaching 165,000.''
   Garbage, she says, will be the only environmental magazine that
is not issued by activists and thus free ``to take the moderator
point of view and to have a sense of humor. If you're the Sierra
Club, you've got to take a worst-case view, and a sense of humor is
a dangerous thing to have.''
   The pros and cons of biodegradable diapers will be examined in
the first issue. The pro is that they self-destruct while the con is
that they introduce human waste into landfills and possibly water
tables.
   The magazine's conclusion: cloth diapers are better.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Robins 1stLd-Writethru a0590 06-16 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Robins, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0590,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Reorganization of Dalkon Shield Maker</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with detail from settlement. Picks
up 4th graf pvs, `Robins sought...'. ADDS byline. A longer version moved
on financial wire. Guerry is cq in 6th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court today approved A.H.
Robins Co.'s bankruptcy reorganization plan, which will create a
$2.5 billion fund to cover claims against its ill-fated Dalkon
Shield birth control device.
   The plan also calls for the acquisition of Robins by American
Home Products Corp. of New York in a $700 million stock-swap deal.
American Home had the option of backing out of the deal if appeals
in the case were not settled by next month.
   ``We are extremely gratified ... that our legal position has been
upheld on all accounts,'' said Dennis Drebsky, a Robins attorney.
   In a series of four unanimous opinions, a three-judge panel of
the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the entire scope of the
reorganization.
   The ruling includes a one claimant-one vote plan by which women
injured by the intrauterine device ratified the settlement, and a
separate cash settlement by Robins' insurance company.
   ``I think it's just tremendous news for all Dalkon Shield
claimants,'' added Guerry Thornton, attorney for the Dalkon Shield
Victims Association. ``It means the decade wait for fair treatment
and vindication of their rights is almost over.''
   Robins sought protection from its creditors in August 1985 in the
face of millions of dollars in lawsuits brought by women who said
they suffered injuries ranging from infections, sterility and
miscarriage to children with birth defects caused by the Dalkon
Shield.
   The Richmond-based pharmaceutical manufacturer's reorganization
plan was approved in July 1988 by U.S. District Judge Robert R.
Merhige Jr. and U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Blackwell N. Shelley, who
jointly presided over numerous court proceedings.
   The reorganization plan created a $2.5 billion trust fund to
compensate about 200,000 women with injury claims against the Dalkon
Shield, which was sold by the company in the early 1970s.
   An appeal argued before the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
December challenged the way the court determined that users of of
the intrauterine device had approved the reorganization.
   More than 95 percent of claimants who returned ballots to the
bankruptcy court voted in favor of the plan. But Alan B. Morrison, a
lawyer for the Public Citizen Litigation Group in Washington, said
the votes should have been weighted so that women with larger claims
would have a greater voice in deciding the issue.
   He also said claimants should not have been barred by the
reorganization plan from filing third-party lawsuits to seek damages
from Robins' officers or its insurer.
   Aetna Casualty &amp; Surety Co., Robins' insurer, paid $425 million
to the trust to settle any claims against it.
   Merhige and Shelley tried to come up with a weighted voting plan
but could find no way to estimate each claim in advance, said
Robins' attorney James C. Roberts of Richmond.
   Based on expert testimony, $2.5 billion was the estimated cost of
full compensation for all Dalkon Shield claimants, Roberts said.
Only $100 million of the $2.5 billion compensation package to Dalkon
Shield claimants has been available during the appeal.
   Robins pulled the IUD off the market in 1974 after about 4.5
million of the devices had been distributed in the United States and
abroad. Before entering bankruptcy proceedings, Robins settled 9,400
of approximately 15,000 Dalkon Shield lawsuits with payments of
about $520 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0103 </DOCNO>
