<HEAD>Two British Journalists Ordered to Leave China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 6th, `The BBC...' to ADD earlier report
that Barron was expelled. Pickup 7th pvs, `Chinese authorities...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese authorities today ordered two British
journalists from Independent Television News to leave the country
within 24 hours, the commercial network said.
   Reporter Vernon Mann and cameramen John Elphinstone, both based
in London, were detained on Wednesday while filming the aftermath of
the unrest in Chengdu, the capital of Sichuan province in western
China, and had been held under house arrest in their hotel, ITN said.
   Chinese authorities accused them of violating martial law
regulations, which effectively ban news coverage of the
pro-democracy movement and the enforcement of martial law. ITN said
its journalists had entered China on tourist visas.
   Today, authorities in Chengdu ordered them to leave within 24
hours and told them their passports would be returned at the
airport, the network said. Authorities confiscated their film and
camera equipment.
   The Foreign Office said it had been seeking the release of Mann
and Elphinstone, and was still trying to get television
correspondent Brian Barron of the British Broadcasting Corp. and his
camera crew out of China.
   The BBC said Barron and his crew were detained on Monday and made
to sign confessions. Their passports and travel documents were
confiscated, it said.
   On Wednesday, the BBC in Beijing reported that Barron had been
ordered expelled from China, but the BBC later said that was a
mistake and blamed the error on a problem in translation.
   Chinese authorities on Wednesday ordered the expulsion of two
Beijing-based American journalists, John E. Pomfret of The
Associated Press and Alan W. Pessin of the Voice of America. The
government accused them of violating martial law regulations and
gave them 72 hours to leave the country.
