<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank robbers wounded a police officer
today and briefly held another hostage in a siege and shootout in
which one suspect was killed and two may have escaped, authorities
said.
   The four-hour drama ended shortly before 11 a.m., when a
helicopter dropped SWAT team members onto the roof of City National
Bank and a search of the building turned up no suspects, said Police
Chief Richard Fox.
   ``We have one suspect in custody,'' Fox said. ``There currently
may be two more suspects at large.'' They could have escaped during
the shootout, and one may have been wounded, police said.
   As officers surrounded the bank for what they assumed was a
standoff with robbers inside, one suspect's body lay outside. When
the incident ended, police confirmed he was dead, but did not
release his identity.
   The robbers were discovered just before 7 a.m. when a silent
alarm summoned police to the bank, FBI spokesman Paul Miller said.
The first policeman to arrive, Daniel O'Connel, encountered a robber
dressed as a bank guard.
   ``Of course, the officer thought he was a security guard,''
Miller said. ``He went into the bank and was confronted with a
handgun. The gun was pointed at his head. He was disarmed and tied
up.''
   That officer was followed by police Lt. David Miles, who
exchanged shots with the suspects and suffered minor wounds that
would have been more serious except for his bulletproof vest, the
FBI spokesman said.
   ``The officer who had been held hostage broke away and as he went
out of the bank, exchanged shots,'' Miller said. Four bank employees
were taken out a side door by police.
   Police arrested one man outside the bank, and called for a
Spanish translator to mediate between authorities and the person or
persons they believed were inside the bank, Miller said.
   Miles was airlifted to Hollywood Memorial Hospital where
spokeswoman Linda Hamlin said he was in stable condition with
gunshot wounds to the cheek and the groin.
   ``He seems to be OK,'' Hallandale police spokeswoman Marcia
Sanders said.
</TEXT>
