<FIRST>r w AM-HousingStarts 1stLd-Writethru a0625 06-16 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Starts, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0625,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Falls, Industry Turnaround Expected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Berson, sted Bersen, in 6th graf, bgng
David Berson</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction fell 2.1 percent in May to
the lowest level since the last recession in 1982, the government
reported Friday, but analysts said declining interest rates will
turn the industry around in coming months.
   Mortgage rates peaked at 11.22 percent in March and fell to 10.2
percent by last week, causing many analysts to anticipate a jump in
housing construction last month.
   But after the Commerce Department on Friday reported a decline in
housing activity in May, economists said the drop in rates had come
too late to help last month, but predicted improvement in months
ahead.
   ``It seems to us that the drop in interest rates occurred late in
May and continued in June, so the drop really was not felt in the
May figures,'' said Robert Rosenblatt, an economist for the Mortgage
Bankers Association of America.
   ``The impact of interest rates, which we expect to trend downward
for the rest of the year, will have a positive effect on (housing)
starts and we should see an appreciable pickup in the
fall,''Rosenblatt said.
   David Berson, chief economist for the Federal National Mortgage
Association, agreed, saying that ``we expect single family units to
start going up in the next several months.''
   Until recently, the Federal Reserve had boosted interest rates
for over a year as it sought to restrain economic growth in an
attempt to restrain inflation.
   John A. Tuccillo, chief economist for the National Association of
Realtors, said many builders thought last month's drop in mortgage
rates might have been temporary.
   ``Further interest rate declines in June will provide the
evidence needed to bring the markets around,'' he said. ``We expect
the June numbers for housing starts to be higher.''
   At the same time, some analysts were not so sanquine about the
immediate future.
   ``Consumer sentiment generally is slackening,'' said David
Seiders, chief economist for the National Association of
Homebuilders.
   ``It doesn't seem the trend is getting any better, particularly
single family units,'' contended real estate economist Michael
Summichrest. ``I don't see anything more than a dropoff for the rest
of the year.''
   The Commerce Department reported that new homes and apartments in
May were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.31 million
units, down from 1.34 million in April when construction fell 5.0
percent.
   The pace in May was the slowest since the 1.30 million rate in
December 1982 and represented the fourth consecutive monthly
decline, the longest string since activity slowed for five months in
a row from February through June 1987.
   Commerce said construction of single-family homes was off 4.6
percent in May to an annual rate of 980,000 units, after rising 4.7
percent in April. The April pace followed drops of 4.7 percent in
March and 14.2 percent in February.
   Apartment construction, meanwhile, rose 6.1 percent last month to
an annual rate of 331,000 units. Construction of multi-family units
had fallen 27.1 percent in April and 1.8 percent in March.
   The Northeast led the overall decline in housing construction
last month, down 9.7 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
186,000 units.
   Declines also were recorded in the Midwest, down 8.9 percent to
245,000 units, and the South, down 1.7 percent to 516,000 units.
   Construction was up 7.4 percent in the West to an annual rate of
364,000 units.
   Applications for building permits, a barometer of future housing
activity, turned up 0.1 percent in May after a 8.5 percent hike in
April. They had fallen the three previous months.
</TEXT>
