<SECOND>PM-Explosives Found, 1st Ld - Writethru,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands In Akron, Ohio, Evacuated After Explosives Found</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Goodyear HQ evacuated; number
of affected people in the thousands, evacuation area expanded to 2,000
feet. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `O'Leary said...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Old dynamite was found in an industrial area
near the city's downtown today, forcing an evacuation of a nursing
home and 4,000 Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co. workers, authorities said.
   Goodyear spokesman Bill Fair said 4,000 employees from
headquarters, several nearby company offices and a factory were
evacuated about noon. The headquarters are about 100 yards from
where the dynamite was found.
   Officials ordered an evacuation of people within 2,000 feet of
the site, between one-third and one-half mile, said fire Capt. John
Roble. The affected area is just east of the downtown and about five
blocks north of Interstate 76.
   The total number of people affected by the order, in addition to
the Goodyear workers, could not immediately be determined. A woman
who answered the telephone at Middlebury Manor nursing home said 150
people were evacuated there.
   Roble said the dynamite was found at Guran Concrete &amp; Supply Co.
as workers were cleaning a warehouse. They forced open the lid of a
container and found the explosives inside.
   Roble said the dynamite may have been for highway construction in
the 1960s.
   About 10 to 12 cases of dynamite were found on the grounds of a
cement company adjacent to a Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co. plant, said
Tony O'Leary, an aide to Mayor Don Plusquellic.
   O'Leary said earlier that a bomb squad would try to determine
whether the dynamite could be moved. If not, he had said, people in
nearby homes and businesses would be evacuated.
   He said officials then would neutralize the dynamite and burn it.
   Traffic in the area was rerouted.
   O'Leary said the mayor's office was alerted to the discovery
about 11 a.m.
</TEXT>
