<FIRST>u a PM-BishopsConference 3rdLd-Writethru a0581 06-16 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bishops Conference, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0581,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S.-Vatican Relations Never Better, Archbishop Says at Bishops'
Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to DELETE reference to AIDS report, which was
originally on the group's agenda but was taken off the agenda some time
ago. SUBS 12th graf to end, `Disputes with...', with 2 grafs to DELETE
subsequent references to AIDS report.</HEAD>
<UNK>By DAVID BRIGGS ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relations between the Vatican and the
U.S. Catholic Church have never been better, the president of the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops said today.
   ``I believe that the bridge between Rome and the United States is
stronger than it has been in recent memory,'' said Archbishop John
L. May of St. Louis.
   May spoke after a morning Mass that opened the annual spring
meeting of the nation's 300 bishops. His address also expressed
support for a document that proposes ways to resolve disputes
between bishops and theologians.
   The bishops are scheduled to vote Saturday on the proposal, which
has been criticized by the Vatican for appearing to place bishops
and theologians on equal levels. The bishops also were expected to
tackle other controversial topics, such as normalizing relations
with Vietnam.
   The tone of May's talk contrasted markedly with a speech given by
his predecessor, Archbishop James Malone of Youngstown, Ohio, before
a bishops' meeting in 1986. Malone spoke of a growing disaffection
among segments of the church in the United States with Rome.
   May said today he believes relations have improved because of a
series of encounters among the two groups, including the pope's U.S.
visit in 1987, meetings with individual bishops last year, and a
March meeting of cardinals and archbishops with Vatican officials.
   The recent meetings showed that ``whatever differences there are
have to do with approach and not with doctrine,'' he said.
   May also appealed for the bishops to approve a proposed document
on doctrinal responsibilities that has drawn substantial criticism
from the Vatican.
   He said the document submitted by the bishops' Committee on
Doctrine tries to foster legitimate diversity in theology, while
upholding the authority of the magisterium, or church hierarchy.
   In March, the Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith in Rome
said the proposed document, which advocates the ``rights'' of
theologians to lawful freedom of inquiry and expression of scholarly
opinion, gives the impression bishops and theologians are on an
equal footing, and ``tends logically to the erection of a second
teaching authority in the Church.''
   The most celebrated dispute in the U.S. involves the Rev. Charles
Curran, a priest who lost his license to teach moral theology at the
Catholic University of America in Washington for his opposition to
some church teaching, particularly in the area of sexual ethics.
   The bishops also are scheduled to vote on a statement calling for
a normalization of relations between the United States and Vietnam,
said Michael Hurley, spokesman for the Newark Archdiocese.
   The four-day meeting at Seton Hall University ends Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
