<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Economy     06-16 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Economy,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Agriultural Reforms Needed to Prevent Hunger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of parliament on Friday predicted a famine
if radical agricultural reform is not undertaken in the next year,
and he blamed bureaucrats for the miserable performance of Soviet
farms.
   Other members of the parliament, the Congress of People's
Deputies, told a news confernce that agricultural reform must be a
top priority, but said widespread hunger was unlikely.
   ``I am sure that if radical transformations are not undertaken
next year there will be famine waiting for us,'' said deputy
Vladimir Tikhonov, an economist.
   Tikhonov noted that the Soviet Union is forced to import potatoes
even though large tracts of land are well-suited to raising a
substantial crop.
   He also criticized low agricultural productivity that results in
chronic shortages of meat, fruit, vegetables and grain needed for
flour. The Soviet Union also must import grain.
   He said the country may have to reduce imports because of a
shortage of hard currency.
   Despite attempts at agricultural reform in President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's economic revival program, such products as meat, sugar,
butter and potatoes are rationed in many parts of the country.
   Tikhonov said the key to improving farm production lies in land
reform and reducing the massive state bureaucracy. ``Administrators
are responsible for the crisis,'' he said without elaborating. The
state controls distribution of seed, gasoline, farm machinery and
fertilizer.
   The Communist Party's policy-making Central Committee in March
approved a policy of leasing land to farmers for 50 years, but
maintained the state and cooperative farms that many blame for
shortages.
   Politburo member Yegor K. Ligachev, who heads a party commission
to redress agricultural problems, was criticized as incompetent at
the session of the Congress that ended last week.
   Oleg Bogomolov, director of the Institute of Economics and World
Socialist Systems and a parliament deputy, told the news conference
economic reform must begin with agriculture and that peasants must
be given land.
   Commenting on Tikhonov's prognosis, Bogomolov said, ``While the
possibility of famine exists, I don't think it is a probability.''
Bogomolov said a lack of agricultural reform could have
destabilizing effects on the economy in general.
   Leonid Abalkin, head of the Institute of Economics and a
parliament deputy named to head a new government commission on
economic reform, said he didn't think the word ``famine'' was
``quite right,'' but did not offer his own prediction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
