<HEAD>Time, Warner Pursuing Merger</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf pvs with Paramount response. SUBS
9th graf, `Paramount did...', with 5 grafs to add further Paramount comment,
and to UPDATE with Time filing suit. Picks up 10th graf pvs, `Securities
analysists...'. Longer version moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. today rejected a $10.7 billion buyout
offer from Paramount Communications Inc previously
planned tender offer for Warner Communications that values Warner at
more than $12.4 billion.
   The move comes amid a complicated, three-way ba. and launched attle
for Time,
which had announced a merger with Warner before Paramount jumped in
with its own bid for Time that was launched June 7.
   Paramount said today it will proceed with its unwanted
$175-a-share bid.
   Time and Warner had been expected to try to salvage their deal,
which would create the world's largest media company.
   After the announcement, Warner stock jumped $3.87{ to $59.50 a
share on the New York Stock Exchange, and Time's slipped $3.87{ to
$167.62{ a share. Paramount stock was down $1 to $58.50 a share.
   Paramount's unsolicited $175-a-share offer was not in the best
interests of the company because it is financially inadequate and
highly conditional, Time said.
   Time said it would pay r either
company.
   In addition, Time filed a lawsuit to block Paramount from taking
any steps ``to disrupt the merger'' of Time and Warner
Communications Inc.
   The suit, filed at federal court in Manhattan, charged securities
laws violations and sought a preliminary injunction to prevent
Paramount from ``aquiring or attempting to acquire any shares of
Time's stock'' and ``making or attempting to make any tender offer''
for Time's securities.
   The lawsuit charged that Paramount made false and misleading
statements in its tender offer.
   Paramount, calling Time's bid for Warner ``a defensive device,
pure and simple,'' said it would continue its pursuit of Time.
   ``From the standpoint of Time shareholders, we don't see how it
begins to compare with our offer of $175 a share in cash for all
share,'' Paramount said.
   Securities analysts said the bid for Warner does little to
resolve Time's battle with Paramount.
   Peter Appert, the media analyst for the investment firm C.J.
Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc., said Time still has the problem of
``figuring out a way to get to its shareholders value that is
equal'' to the $175 a share Paramount has offered.
   One way for Time to increase shareholder value would be to pay a
special cash dividend. But Appert doubted whether Time could afford
to acquire Warner and pay the dividend.
   He said the decline in Time's stock price today indicated Wall
Street is skeptical that the Time bid for Warner will be successful.
If the market thought the bid would be successfully completed, he
said Time's stock price would be down ``substantially more.''
   Time and Warner agreed in March to merge in an all-stock deal
under which Time stockholders would get a share in the new company,
Time-Warner Inc., for each Time share while Warner shareholders
would get 0.465 of a share of the new company for each of their
Warner shares.
   In today's statement, Time reiterated that it is not for sale.
   ``We are convinced that remaining independent and combining
operations with WCI will best serve the interests of Time, its
stockholders and its other constituencies,'' Time Chairman J.
Richard Munro said.
   Time said its board turned down the Paramount offer because the
bid was highly conditional in terms of obtaining the required $14
billion in financing and securing regulatory approval, which Time
said Paramount might never receive.
   ``An extended delay in the closing of the tender offer would
substantially reduce the present value of the offer to Time
shareholders,'' Time said.
   Paramount, formerly called Gulf &amp; Western Inc., announced its bid
for Time on June 6, just 2{ weeks before Time and Warner
shareholders were to vote on the proposed merger. The tender offer
was formally launched the next day.
   Time and Warner did not immediately say whether their shareholder
meetings, scheduled for June 23, would take place.
   Since Paramount announced its bid there has been intense
speculation on Wall Street over what steps Time and Warner would
take to preserve their planned merger. A Time tender offer for
Warner was among the options the two companies were expected to
explore.
   On Thursday, Paramount Chairman Martin Davis sent a letter to the
Time board, complaining he had not heard from the company, and
indicating he might be willing to sweeten his offer, reportedly to
pressure the Time board.
   In a separate development Thursday, Time and Warner said New York
city officials approved the proposed transfers in ownership of the
six cable franchises in the city owned by either Time or Warner.
   Time and Warner together own cable systems serving about 5.5
million subscribers, but must get permission from local cable
authorities in each case to transfer the ownership to the new
company.
</TEXT>
