<HEAD>Foreign Minister Says Chinese Officials Seeking Refuge in Canada</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials from the Chinese Embassy have asked to
remain in Canada as refugees, External Affairs Minister Joe Clark
confirmed Friday.
   ``I can confirm that there have been approaches by some officials
of the Chinese Embassy indicating the desire to stay in Canada,''
Clark said outside the House of Commons.
   ``I don't propose to discuss names or numbers or locations or any
details,'' he said. ``I think you will understand that it is in
nobody's interest to get into details at this moment.''
   The Canadian Press news agency quoted an unidentified source as
saying that as of Thursday night, five officials from the Chinese
Embassy and two from the Chinese Consulate in Vancouver, British
Columbia, had asked for refugee status. More may have approached
Canadian immigration officials since then.
   The Canadian Broadcasting Corp. reported at least nine people
have asked for refugee status as a result of the violence and
repression used by Chinese authorities this month to end a
pro-democracy movement in China.
   External Affairs spokesman Laurie Storsater said the reluctance
to provide details was ``for primarily security reasons. ... We're
not doing anything that would jeopardize either their safety or that
of their families.''
