<FIRST>r w AM-US-Gorbachev     06-16 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Gorbachev,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Disappointed by Gorbachev's Comments on Berlin Wall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokeswoman said Friday that the State
Department was disappointed that Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev failed to promise unconditionally to tear down the Berlin
Wall.
   Gorbachev, drawing praise Thursday from West German officials,
said the wall between East Germany and West Germany could come down
``when those conditions that created it fall away.''
   ``We noted President Gorbachev's remarks that the wall could come
down some day,'' said State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.
   ``We just wish he would drop the words `some day,''' she added.
``The West consistently has called for the wall to come down
immediately,'' she said.
   The most recent such appeal was made by President Bush in a
speech he gave in the West German town of Mainz earlier this month.
   ``It is disappointing that Gorbachev said that the wall could
only come down'' when conditions that created a need for it
disappear, Ms. Tutwiler said. ``The wall can never be justified.''
   East Germany has maintained the 100-mile wall is needed to
prevent skilled workers from leaving the country and endangering the
economy. The United States has responded that the wall drives a
wedge between the German people and perpetuates tensions in Europe.
   Gorbachev, winding up a visit to West Germany, told reporters
that ``the wall was raised in a concrete situation and was not
dictated only by evil intention.'' It ``can disappear when those
conditions that created it fall away,'' he added.
   West German officials praised the remarks, saying Gorbachev's
willingness to discuss the matter suggested a new phase in the
Kremlin's dealings there.
   But Ms. Tutwiler disagreed, saying ``such a statement represents
what Gorbachev himself calls `old thinking.''' The Bush
administration has urged the reform-minded Soviet leader to
demonstrate new thinking by allowing more domestic liberalization
and relaxing Kremlin control over its allies.
</TEXT>
