<FIRST>u i PM-China 4thLd-Writethru a0600 06-16 1000</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0600,1031</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissent is Out: Party Paper Lauds Party Line</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1 graf for 13th pvs, ``New agencies...'' to correct to
News agencies. Pickup 14th pvs, ``The government's...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities took Western reporters to Tiananmen
Square today and told them that soldiers did not shoot any
demonstrators there.
   One army general said troops did fire into the square because
they were forced to use violence to clear the area of pro-democracy
protesters. Then the general reversed himself and said soldiers did
not shoot at protesters.
   In other developments:
   _The leading national daily lauded the hard-line tactics of
senior leader Deng Xiaoping and appealed for ``unity of thinking''
in a sign that China's rulers intend to stamp out all political
dissent.
   _An aide to Premier Li Peng said members of the Chinese
leadership were guilty of supporting the demonstrators.
   _British officials said Chinese authorities have ordered two
British journalists to leave the China within 24 hours.
   _The American Committee of the International Press Institute
criticized China for expelling two American journalists earlier this
week.
   The government previously said troops did not fire a single shot
in Tiananmen Square, which soldiers and tanks cleared of thousands
of protesters when the crackdown began on the night of June 3-4. The
government has not commented on shooting elsewhere in Beijing.
   Gen. Li Zhiyun told reporters today that troops were forced to
use violence to enter the city and clear Tiananmen because ``people
who didn't know the truth'' blocked them on the outskirts of Beijing.
   ``But still there were some thugs, they (were) still provocative
to the troops. At this time, some of the soldiers in our troops
directed their fire into the square,'' he said during the first news
conference for Western reporters since the crackdown began.
   At another point Li said of the deaths: ``It is not from any
instances from the soldiers directing their guns at the people. This
incident never happened within the area of Beijing.''
   He did not clarify the contradiction.
   News agencies were not allowed to attend the news conference.
Associated Press reporters viewed a videotape by CBS television that
showed Li speaking in Chinese through an army translator.
   The government's call for unity by the Communist Party's People's
Daily came as the state moved to expunge opposition through arrests,to
put out the blaze after it ran through a protest barricade,
killing six people.
   The three were the first to receive the death sentence of more
than 1,000 people arrested since nationwide protests broke out after
the crackdown in Beijing.
   Most of those arrested have been workers, but the government has
also issued all-point bulletins for 21 student leaders. Only three
of those have been arrested or reported to authorities.
   The People's Daily editorial praised the ``keen insight and
scientific judgment'' of the 84-year-old Deng in his June 9 address
to military officers involved in the attack in the capital.
   The government variously says 200 to 300 people, mostly soldiers,
were killed. Unofficial Chinese and Western intelligence reports say
troops fired on unarmed crowds and killed up to 3,000.
   The editorial said the rebellion in Beijing has been put down but
``some people still harbor ideological hangups.
   ``Therefore, it is necessary to seek unity of thinking covering
the whole party and the whole people by seriously studying the
important speech made by Deng Xiaoping.''
   In an interview with NBC news, Yuan Mu, an assistant to Premier
Li Peng, said today that ``certain individuals'' in China's
leadership were ``guilty of supprting counterrevolutionary turmoil.''
   ``But their questions will be dealt with soon and will be made
public,'' he said.
   Communist Party leader Zhao Ziyang has not been seen in public
since the day before Premier Li declared martial law on May 20. Zhao
expressed sympathy for the students.
   The newspaper said China must abide by ``one center and two basic
points.'' The center, it said, is the party and the people. It
defined the two points as principles of communist rule and socialism
in addition to continued open-door and reform policies.
   The editorial indicated the ruling party will no longer tolerate
criticism of its policies, as it did to a limited extent in the
months before the crackdown.
   In his June 9 speech, Deng said the Beijing protesters rallied
under the slogans ``down with the Communist Party'' and ``overturn   Although
many did praise Western democracy, their stated goals
were to open a dialogue with the government, guarantee a free press,
and end corruption among officials.
   Britain's Independent Television News said in London that Chinese
authorities today ordered two of its journalists to leave the
country within 24 hours.
   Reporter Vernon Mann and cameramen John Elphinstone, both based
in London, were detained on Wednesday while filming the aftermath of
the unrest in Sichuan province in western China, and had been held
under house arrest in their hotel, ITN said.
   Chinese authorities accused them of violating martial law
regulations, which ban coverage of the protests.
   On Wednesday, China ordered the expulsion of VOA Beijing bureau
chief Alan Pessin and Associated Press reporter John Pomfret on the
same charges.
   The American Committee of the International Press Institute today
issued a statement in Philadelphia deploring the expulsions as a
setback to the free exchange of information.
   ``It is essential ... that reporters or organizations such as The
Associated Press have the access and opportunity to report,'' said
Eugene L. Roberts, executive editor of The Philadelphia Inquirer and
committee chairman.
   ``We urge the leaders of the People's Republic to reinstate John
Pomfret and to increase, not decrease, access to events in China,''
he said.
</TEXT>
