<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Crime     06-16 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Crime,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush To Prosecutors: No Deals With Criminals Who Use Guns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors on Friday got orders to be
``especially vigilant'' on stern prosecution of violent offenders as
President Bush directed them not to make deals with criminals who
use guns.
   Bush continued touting the crime package he delivered to Congress
this week, by inviting the nation's 94 U.S. attorneys to the White
House Friday morning and later having lunch with a group of law
enforcement agency heads.
   In remarks to the U.S. attorneys, the president said, ``We're
going to up the stakes for those who calculate that our criminal
justice system is a crapshoot where the risks are worth the rewards.
And when criminals think about reaching for a gun, they're going to
know _ and they're gong to learn _ that they will do time. Hard
time.''
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh distributed guidelines to the
U.S. attorneys to implement the president's approach.
   Thornburgh wrote: ``In all but exceptional cases such as those in
which the defendant has provided substantial assistance to the
government in the investigation or prosecution of crimes by others,
federal prosecutors will seek conviction for any offense involving
the unlawful use of a firearm which is readily provable.''
   The guidelines said that sentencing should reflect ``the totality
and seriousness of the defendant's conduct.''
   ``The specific affirmation of these policies by the president
requires that you be especially vigilant about their full
implementation in your district,'' Thornburgh wrote.
   Bush called the prosecutors ``the commanders at the frontlines''
and urged them to help ``put away the nation's most wanted.''
   ``The situation in our streets has been aptly compared to a
shooting war,'' he told the gathering in the East Room of the White
House.
   The events Friday were to keep the spotlight on the $1.2 billion
legislation he sent to Congress on Thursday with his anti-crime
proposals.
   The package calls for $1 billion in new prison capacity, in
addition to hiring 1,600 new prosecutors to work under the U.S.
attorneys and 825 new federal agents.
   It also calls for doubling the mandatory penalty for use of
semi-automatic weapons in drug or violent crimes to 10 years.
</TEXT>
