<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1646EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SwindallTrial     06-16 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swindall Trial,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Declares Swindall a Liar in Emotional Closing Arguments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury began deliberating federal perjury charges
against Pat Swindall Friday after hearing a prosecutor describe the
former congressman as a liar who ``was willing to deal with the
devil'' _ but only in private.
   The jury got the case about 2:30 p.m. and planned to deliberate
about an hour before going home. U.S. District Judge Richard C.
Freeman said deliberations will continue Saturday.
   In his closing statement in the 4-week-old trial, Assistant U.S.
Attorney Craig Gillen said Swindall knew he was negotiating for an
illegal money deal, made plans to cover his tracks and then lied
repeatedly about it to a grand jury investigating money laundering.
   Defense attorneys said Swindall was guilty of poor judgment in
considering the money deal, but never did anything wrong and did his
best to recall the details for the grand jury.
   Swindall was indicted on nine counts of perjury for lying to a
grand jury on Feb. 2, 1988, about his negotiations with an
undercover agent posing as a money launderer and with a Swindall
associate concerning an $850,000 loan to finish building the former
congressman's luxurious home.
   Gillen noted that Swindall told the grand jury he couldn't recall
being told the money was drug-related and said he had ``walked away
from it, basically.''
   The prosecutor pointed out that in a Sept. 13, 1987, meeting with
the agent and Swindall associate Charles LeChasney, Swindall was
repeatedly told the money was drug-related, but continued to deal.
   ``He will deal with the devil,'' Gillen said. ``He sat there, and
listened to it, and he didn't walk away.''
   Gillen scoffed at the notion that Swindall didn't recall that
meeting with undercover agent Mike Mullaney at West Virginia's posh
Greenbriar resort.
   ``Do you think you would remember,'' Gillen asked the jury, ``if
you took a walk with a man you believed to be a criminal, at one of
the ritziest resorts in America? And he tells you narcotics dollars
are involved ... what he does violates currency laws?
   ``Do you think you would remember? Do you think you could ever
forget?''
   Swindall, who did not testify in his own defense, sat still, jaw
clenched, as Gillen accused him of lies.
   Swindall's lead defense attorney, Richard Hendrix, admitted to
the jury that Swindall is ``guilty of poor judgment, foolishness,
stupidity and just plain being dumb.''
   But he attacked the credibility of LeChasney, an admitted con man
who testified for the prosecution, and pointed out that former U.S.
Attorney Larry Thompson, advising Swindall before his grand jury
appearance, urged a postponement because of Swindall's fatigue.
   ``Did you believe Larry Thompson? Did you find him a credible
man?'' Hendrix asked. ``If you did, that's reasonable doubt on every
count.''
   Gillen angrily noted that Swindall was granted a postponement of
his appearance but refused in order to keep to his schedule.
   Defense attorney Thomas Thrash accused the government of
``inviting Swindall into a perjury trap'' in order to ``add a United
States congressman to the trophy case.''
   Thrash argued that, in his grand jury testimony, Swindall
acknowledged many of the things he is accused of misleading the
grand jury about. And he said that while Swindall ``is a sinner ...
he's not a criminal.''
   ``In the name of God,'' Thrash whispered to the jury, ``let this
nightmare end _ now.''
   Swindall, under the cloud of the perjury indictment against him,
lost his congressional seat in Atlanta's eastern suburbs to Democrat
Ben Jones last November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
