<SECOND>AM-BRF--Emergency Landing,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet Lands In Bismarck After Engine Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Airlines jet en route from
Seattle to Detroit made an emergency landing Friday after one of its
engines failed, authorities said.
   Flight 578, a twin-engine Boeing 757, developed problems with one
engine about 100 miles from Bismarck, said Northwest customer
service manager John Whitt. The plane carried about 140 passengers
and a crew of seven.
   ``This was the closest airport they could use. They made a nice
approach and landed safety,'' said Charles Cole, a Federal Aviation
Administration manager. ``The pilot did a real nice job.''
   Neither Whitt nor Cole knew the exact cause of the engine problem.
   ``Bismarck isn't quite the vacation place where everyone wants to
go,'' said passenger John Gabryszak, of Valparaiso, Ind.
   ``Nobody was really worried until we started seeing all the
emergency vehicles on the side of the road,'' Gabryszak said. ``But
the pilot and crew handled it really well. We all applauded when we
touched down.''
