<FIRST>r w AM-Cuba-Arrests     06-16 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Arrests,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department, Leading Senator Welcome Cuba`s Move On Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department and the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee chairman welcomed on Friday Cuba's arrest of a
decorated Army general on corruption charges as a potential turning
point in the country's approach to narcotics problems.
   South American drug dealers have been making increasing use of
Cuban air space and territorial waters for U.S.-bound narcotics
deliveries, an activity that U.S. officials last week said strongly
suggested the collaboration of Cuban authorities.
   Cuba is directly in the flight path between Colombia and south
Florida, and the number of suspicious northbound flights through
Cuban airspace has increased in the past several months, according
to administration officials.
   The Coast Guard also has detected an increase in air drops of
drugs into Cuban territorial waters. The cargo is then picked up by
speedboats for delivery to U.S. ports, the officials said.
   ``To the best of our knowledge, this is the first time the Cuban
government has admitted involvement of Cuban officials in drug
smuggling operations,'' Margaret Tutwiler, the State Department
spokesman, said of the arrest of Gen. Arnaldo Ochoa.
   The Cuban party newspaper Granma said Ochoa had been taken into
custoday because he engaged in ``grave acts of corruption and
dishonest use of economic resources.''
   Ochoa is a veteran of fighting in Angola and Ethiopia and also
served as commander of Cuban forces in Nicaragua in the mid-1980s.
According to Rafael Fermoselle, a Cuban exile and an expert on the
Cuban military, Ochoa was awarded the title ``Hero of the
Revolution'' in 1984.
   Ms. Tutwiler noted that the June 15 edition of Cuba's Commmunist
Party newspaper had accused Ochoa and and other officials ``of
making contacts with international drug traffickers and reaching
agreements with them.''
   She also pointed out that Cuba Radio reported that two armed
force officers and four ministry of interior officers had been
arrested, and quoted the report as saying that ``it is possible that
Ochoa and his accomplices cooperated in drug trafficking operations
near Cuban territory.''
   The spokeswoman said the administration hopes ``the charges
against Ochoa and the other officers will be investigated and, if
found true, will be prosecuted to the fullest extent possible.''
   Meanwhile, Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., Foreign Relations
Committee chairman, said, ``This arrest could open the way for
mutually beneficial cooperation between the United States and Cuba
to combat the narcotics trafficking that is taking place in the sea
and air space that we share.''
   Pell earlier proposed that the U.S. Coast Guard and the Cuban
border patrol cooperate on narcotics interdiction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
