<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Baseball     06-16 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Baseball,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>WSU Baseball Team Visits White House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush tried out his old baseball
throwing arm on Friday when the champion Wichita State University
baseball team visited the White House.
   Receiving the NCAA champs in the Rose Garden, Bush recalled his
own ball playing days for the Yale team, when he and his teammates
made it to the first College World Series finals in 1947 and 1948.
   He said his team had the misfortune of letting the other team's
pitcher, future Boston Red Sox star Jackie Jensen, ``hit a ball
that's still rolling in Kalamazoo, Mich.''
   ``Baseball can keep you humble,'' the president noted.
   He was joined in congratulating the Wichita team by their state's
Republican senators, Bob Dole and Nancy Kassebaum, and by Vice
President Dan Quayle.
   Bush then tossed a few throws with the team's catcher, Eric
Wedge, at one point making a deft but unsuccessful move to catch the
ball behind his back.
   Bush wore a glove, Wedge did not.
   ``I better go to work,'' Bush said laughingly after a few throws.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
