<DOCNO> AP890616-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1620EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Shooting     06-16 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Shooting,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Gives Contradictory Accounts of Army Shooting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY CHENAULT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army general said Friday that the People's
Liberation Army fired on unarmed civilians when it entered Tiananmen
Square because soldiers were provoked by ``thugs.''
   But at a confusing news conference, Gen. Li Zhiyun later
contradicted that statement, saying soldiers did not shoot at the
protesters.
   The government invited selected journalists to attend the news
conference, the first since it began its crackdown on the
pro-democracy movement, and a subsequent tour of the square.
   News agencies were not allowed to participate. Associated Press
reporters obtained Li's remarks by viewing a videotape made by CBS
News. He spoke through a translator.
   Li said troops were forced to use violence to enter the city on
June 3-4 because ``people who didn't know the truth'' blocked the
soldiers on the outskirts of Beijing.
   He said soldiers in tanks and armored personnel carriers
``exercised restraint'' in trying to clear student-led demonstrators
from Tiananmen.
   ``But still there were some thugs,'' Li said during the news
conference in the Great Hall of the People near the square. ``At
this time, some of the soldiers in our troops directed their fire
into the square and especially those troops that have wounded or
dead soldiers within their troops.
   ``The rest of the soldiers started fire to those thugs who were
provocative to them.''
   But at another point Li said of the deaths: ``It is not from any
instances from the soldiers directing their guns at the people. This
incident (soldiers firing on citizens) never happened within the
area of Beijing.''
   Li did not clarify the contradiction.
   The government previously had denied that a single shot was fired
in Tiananmen, but had not commented on shooting elsewhere in the
city.
   The government's actions Friday appeared to be part of a campaign
aimed at demonstrating that protesters were not shot while they were
inside the 100-acre square.
   Although Tiananmen Square was the focus of the demonstrations,
reporters on the scene said most of the shooting was on Changan
Avenue, the main road to the square. But there were conflicting
reports during the confused fighting in the darkness and some
students reported shooting inside the square.
   Other shooting incidents were reported from the edges of the
square and at the bridge at Muxudi, the western gateway to the inner
city. Reporters saw many wounded students treated at tents set up by
protesters in Tiananmen Square.
   Li said protesters in Tiananmen attacked soldiers with sticks and
threw stones and bricks, and that snipers fired on them from
buildings on the edge of the square.
   ``Some of the soldiers were beaten until they fainted, and even
some were beaten until death.'' Li said.
   The Xinhua News Agency said nearly 100 soldiers and police died
and that thousands were injured, while about 100 civilians died and
nearly 1,000 were injured. It did not account for the discrepancy
with government figures issued last week that said nearly 300 people
died altogether.
   Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources said the death
toll may have been as high as 3,000.
   Reporters in the square the night of the crackdown said there
appeared to be less firing there than in other parts of the city.
   There were reports in the Hong Kong media that tanks rolled over
tents in which students were sleeping, and that soldiers later
burned the bodies. Western reporters said they only saw tanks roll
over piles of bedding, but were not sure if people were crushed.
   Reporters saw soldiers firing indiscriminately at crowds as the
troops moved toward the square. Western reporters fled the square
shortly after the army began moving in.
   Students had occupied the square for several weeks before the
crackdown.
   Tiananmen is in the center of Beijing and is the symbolic heart
of China. On one side stands the former Imperial Palace, on another
is the Great Hall of the People, the seat of government.
   It remained closed to pedestrians on Friday.
</TEXT>
