<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-16 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By the time the Legislature's supposed 100-day
session adjourned at 6 a.m. Friday in its 159th day, the capital
showed the signs of what college students call an all-nighter.
   Staff members had changed into blue jeans or went barefoot. Empty
champagne bottles, cold cuts and pizza boxes littered a table in
Senate President Bob Usdane's inner office. House members threw wads
of paper at a likeness of Usdane.
   Disagreement between the two houses also was a problem in
neighboring Nevada, where the Legislature commemorated going into a
record 152nd day Friday with black balloons, black gum drops and
black humor.
   ``When do we qualify for food stamps?'' asked Assemblyman Bob
Gaston of Las Vegas.
   When Arizona Senate Majority Leader John Mawhinney warned that
the defeat of a prison-construction bill would leave no room for new
inmates, fellow Republican Sen. Pat Wright offered her office.
   Sen. Jaime Gutierrez, who had stopped shaving weeks ago to
protest the session's length, appeared on the floor without his
beard. He said his wife hadn't seen him in weeks and shaving was
``the quickest way to have my wife open the door.''
   A last glitch holding up lawmakers was an error in a bill to
correct technical mistakes in earlier bills.
   ``I think this exemplifies the session, where we have to send the
correction bill back to be corrected,'' said Rep. Henry Evans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NICHOLS HILLS, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Oklahoma City suburb, where the
police drive Volvos and pickup trucks must be hidden from view, has
taken a new step to preserve its aesthetic integrity.
   The City Council has approved new swimming pool and fence
ordinances aimed at keeping residents from building front-yard
swimming pools and extending fences to their front property line.
   City Manager Doug Henley said he had been asked by a non-resident
about whether building such a pool would be legal.
   ``There was nothing on the books that would prevent him from
doing that,'' he said.
   The city drafted and approved the ordinances, which went into
effect Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TABOR, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Let's Polka'' has been the cheer of the
annual Czech Days, which kicked off its 41st year Friday with music
and plenty of kolaches.
   The yearly two-day Bohemian celebration was expected to draw
10,000 vistors to Tabor, a town of 470 people in southeastern South
Dakota near the Missouri River.
   ``The Czechs have a fun-loving tradition,'' Sherry Povondra said.
``We go all-out for social occasions and we try to greet people with
friendliness.
   ``That tradition is carried on during Czech days.''
   Mrs. Povondra and her husband, Dennis, are this year's parade
marshals.
   The event began with Mass at St. Wenceslaus Catholic Church,
where ushers dressed in Czech costumes, and the pastor explained the
history of St. Wenceslaus.
   ``What this amounts to is a Christian celebration with a polka
beat,'' said the Rev. Carl Hermann.
   Along with the church, Tabor's main street also was to be given
over Saturday to music, dancing and the eating of kolaches, a
Czechoslovakian pastry that is usually filled with fruit.
