<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1652EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Glance     06-16 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Glance,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Developments on China at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are Friday's developments on China:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CRACKDOWN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   China's government intensified its campaign to absolve itself in
the deaths of the pro-democracy protesters. Gen. Li Zhiyun told
Western reporters that troops were forced to use violence because
``people who didn't know the truth'' blocked them on the outskirts
of Beijing. Li said troops fired into Tiananmen Square to clear the
area of demonstrators, but later reversed himself about the deaths,
saying: ``It is not from any instances from the soldiers directing
their guns at the people. This incident never happened within the
area of Beijing.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PARTY LEADERSHIP</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese government spokesman Yuan Mu, asked about the fate of
Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang, said: ``It is true that certain
individuals in the top Chinese leadership are guilty of supporting
the counterrevolutionary _ of supporting turmoil. But their
questions will be dealt with soon and will be made public.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FANG LIZHI</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Asked whether China might invade the U.S. Embassy in Beijing to
arrest dissidents Fang Lizhi and his wife, Li Shuxian, spokesman
Yuan Mu said: ``He must be brought to justice. We will deal with him
according to legal procedures.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ARRESTS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 100 more people were arrested nationwide for taking part
in protests, including Ma Shaofeng, a student leader named on a
wanted circular distributed Tuesday. Nearly 1,200 arrests have been
reported since the crackdown.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>JOURNALISTS EXPELLED</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese authorities ordered two more journalists to leave the
country within 24 hours. Reporter Vernon Mann and cameramen John
Elphinstone from Britain's Independent Television News, detained
Wednesday while filming in Chengdu, are accused of violating martial
law regulations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PRESS PROTEST</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The American Committee of the International Press Institute
criticized China for expelling two American journalists earlier this
week. ``It is essential to the free exchange of information that
reporters or organizations such as The Associated Press have the
access and opportunity to report,'' the committee said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DENG</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The official media lauded the hard-line tactics of senior leader
Deng Xiaoping and appealed for ``unity of thinking,'' indicating
that China's rulers intend to stamp out all political dissent. The
People's Daily called the demonstrators an ``ideological pimple''
and said Deng's words were ``the most powerful ideological weapon
for lancing (it).''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BUSH</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said President Bush
deplores the persecutions of Chinese demonstrators but has no
current plans to impose further sanctions on China. ``We believe
that dialogue and reform, not arrests and show trials, are the route
which offer the best hope for stability in China,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CHINESE REFUGEES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   At least two more Chinese diplomats in the United States have
been granted refuge, State Department sources said. Also, Canadian
External Affairs Minister Joe Clark confirmed that an unspecified
number of officials from the Chinese Embassy have asked to remain in
Canada as refugees.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>REAGAN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ronald Reagan said Chinese student demonstrators
might have pushed their goals too fast but he believed they had
widespread support.
</TEXT>
