<FIRST>u i AM-Greece     06-16 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Papandreou Ends Electoral Campaign With Giant Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou ended his
election campaign with a giant rally Friday, urging 500,000
supporters to give his Socialist Party another term to complete
reforms begun eight years ago.
   Recent opinion polls have indicated, however, that the
conservative New Democracy Party will get about 47 percent of the
vote in Sunday's election, compared with 36 percent for the
Socialists.
   The Supreme Court said 25 parties are participating, including
anarchists, fascists and the Coalition of the Left and Progress, a
new alliance of the Moscow-oriented Greek Communist Party and the
Greek Left party that is the country's the third-largest political
organization.
   If neither major party wins a majority in the 300-member
unicameral parliament, the Coalition could become a power broker.
Some polls give it 14 percent of the vote.
   Both New Democracy and the Socialists have said they would reject
Communist support in forming a government.
   Papandreou told the cheering crowd in Constitution Square the
Socialists need four more years to finish their tasks and prepare
``for the challenge in 1992,'' when Greece and the other 11 members
of the European Economic Community drop internal economic barriers
and become a single market.
   ``The four years leading to 1992 ... to a united Europe, compels
us to develop technology to a great degree,'' he said.
   People in the crowd waved flags of green, the party color, and
sang along with music blaring from giant loudspeakers before
Papandreou, 70, appeared on a platform in front of the Unknown
Soldiers Tomb.
   Approaching the platform, he was accompanied by his 35-year-old
mistress, former airline hostess Dimitra Liani. Papandreou said they
will marry soon.
   His divorce from his American-born wife Margaret became final
June 9, and on Friday their lawyers submitted the documents
necessary for the Greek Orthodox Church to end their 38-year
marriage.
   Fireworks exploded above the square and lit up the darkened
skies, giving the rally a carnival atmosphere. Papandreou shouted
into the microphone, but the noise of the crowd drowned most of his
speech.
   Departing from prepared remarks, the premier attacked New
Democracy and its leader, Constantine Mitsotakis.
   ``They cannot defeat us with their slander and mudslinging,'' he
said.
   The reference was to allegations that he and ranking members of
his party were involved in a $200 million embezzlement scandal at
the Bank of Crete.
   Papandreou has denied any wrongdoing, but at least eight
ministers in his adminstration have resigned, including Deputy
Premier Agamemnon Koutsogiorgas.
   New Democracy finished its campaign Thursday night in the same
square. No campaigning is permitted Saturday.
</TEXT>
