<DOCNO> AP890616-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1844EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DowFine     06-16 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dow Fine,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Proposes $1.13 Million Penalty Against Dow Chemical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency proposed
$1.13 million in civil penalties against Dow Chemical Co. Friday
because the company allegedly failed to promptly inform the agency
it was manufacturing a new chemical substance.
   Such notification is required under federal toxic substances
control laws. The law provides a civil penalty of up to $25,000 for
each day the notification provision is violated.
   The EPA said Dow, based in Midland, Mich., accumulated 227
separate violations because of the reporting lapses involving the
new chemical product, a clear plastic called polycarbonate.
   The company has 20 days to request a formal hearing on the
proposed penalties.
   Bill Donberg, Dow's business director for polycarbonates, said
the product has been manufactured by Dow in Freeport, Texas, since
1985. He said Dow determined no EPA notification was required
because some of the chemicals used in the product already were on
the EPA's list of toxic substances.
   Donberg said the company gave the EPA notification in 1987.
   ``What we're going to have to do is explore with the EPA to see
whether or not we did actually commit this violation and if we did,
what the appropriate penalty would be,'' Donberg said.
</TEXT>
