<HEAD>Party Leaders Look At Losses, Pledge Reform Will Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with Central Committee spokesman's
comments, demonstration, French president's departure. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Communist Party spokesman on Friday said
the party will need to institute reform to overcome its stinging
defeats in democratic parliamentary elections earlier this month.
   His pledge followed a party pep talk given by Prime Minister
Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, himself a loser in the June 4 elections.
Rakowski analyzed the losses in preparation for the second round of
voting Sunday.
   Jan Bisztyga, spokesman for the Communist Party's policy-making
Central Committee, told a news conference: ``We are aware that
increased social support for the party in the future, especially
support by youth, must be linked with further democratization of the
system and economic reforms.''
   In other developments Friday:
   _A small band of young protesters shouting anti-Soviet slogans
from the steps of a Warsaw church hurled gasoline-filled bottles
toward police, who detained several before the demonstration
dispersed without further incident and apparently without injuries.
   _President Francois Mitterrand of France called Poland's
Communist leaders courageous patriots for their recent steps toward
democracy and reiterated a promise of economic aid as he ended a
three-day state visit.
   Rakowski acknowledged in a televised speech to Wroclaw party
members Thursday night that the party underestimated the vigor of
the Solidarity-led opposition's campaign and was too slow to shed
Stalinism in favor of reform.
   The speech followed intensive consultations within the party
leadership and the rank-and-file members after the setback suffered
in the June 4 elections, the most democratic in Eastern Europe since
World War II.
   ``Counting on favorable results in the first round of the
elections proved to be a mistake,'' he said. ``Could this have been
avoided? In part yes, if we would have noticed the threatening
dangers, but we did not notice them.''
   Sunday's runoff is for candidates who failed to receive
majorities on June 4. Most of the races will be for seats reserved
for the Communist Party or its allies in the Sejm, or parliament.
   Candidates of the independent Solidarity movement won all but one
of the 161 seats open to the opposition in the 460-member
parliament. They won 92 of the 100 seats in the new, freely elected
Senate, with the remaining eight to be decided Sunday.
   Only three party coalition Sejm candidates _ reformers supported
by Solidarity activists in their regions _ won first-round
victories. And 33 of the 35 top government officials on a ``national
list'' of unopposed Sejm candidates did not receive the required 50
percent of votes cast.
   The defeated Rakowski says he will not run again for parliament
Sunday under a plan worked out with the opposition to fill the 33
seats and maintain an agreed-upon 65 percent Sejm majority for the
Communist coalition.
   However, he left open the possibility of continuing as prime
minister, which is possible under Polish law.
   The new government and possible changes in party leadership are
expected to be the main topic at a party plenum this month. The
party is expected to confirm Gen. Wojceich Jaruzelski as its
candidate for president, a new post to be filled by the vote of the
Senate and the Sejm.
   The president is to name the new prime minister.
   The plenum will ``deeply'' analyze the electoral defeat, Rakowski
said.
   Rakowski said public dissatisfaction with the government and
living conditions ``has made many Poles judge us one-sidedly and to
pin exaggerated hopes on the opposition.''
   He said the ``aggressiveness'' of the opposition's campaign took
many party leaders by surprise, according to a translation provided
by the state-run PAP news agency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
