<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0673 06-16 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0673,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Says Christians Will Attack Syrian Supply Routes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: 5 grafs SUB for final 4 grafs, 16-19, A cease-fire ... UPDATING
with Lebanese U.N. protest, New Israeli air raid.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Michel Aoun said Friday his Christian
troops will attack Syrian supply routes in retaliation for the
shelling of a tanker carrying gasoline destined for Lebanon's
besieged Christian enclave.
   Syrian artillery fire set the tanker ablaze Thursday evening as
it approached the Christian port of Tabarja, 15 miles north of
Beirut.
   ``Roads leading to capitals of occupation (forces) will not be
safe henceforth,'' Aoun said in a statement broadcast by government
radio. ``We shall confront this foreign enemy with the courage of a
warrior at the front.''
   Syria's 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon receive supplies over a
network of roads from Damascus, the Syrian capital about 50 miles
east of Beirut.
   Attacks on the roads would be a dramatic escalation of the
3-month-old confrontation between Aoun's forces and a Moslem
alliance of the Syrians and Druse militiamen, which has largely
consisted of artillery duels.
   At least 372 people have been killed and 1,450 wounded since the
fighting began March 8, two days after Aoun's Christian army units
blockaded illegal ports operated by Moslem militias.
   The general describes the Syrians as an occupation force and has
declared a ``war of liberation.'' President Hafez Assad of Syria has
had soldiers in Lebanon since 1976, the year after the Lebanese
civil war began, under a peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
   Christian gunners have shelled the supply routes several times in
recent weeks, mainly in the Syrian-controlled Bekaa Valley of east
Lebanon. Aoun did not say what other methods of attack he might use,
but commando raids, land mines and car bombs are among the
possibilities.
   Syrian forces have blockaded the 310-square-mile enclave where 1
million Christians live since the early days of the confrontation,
and shell the Christian-held coast north of Beirut to stop supplies
arriving by sea.
   Aoun's gunboats tried in vain to salvage some of the 660,000
gallons of gasoline from the tanker. The vessel still was burning on
Friday.
   Gunboats rescued 13 of the 14 crew members after they abandoned
ship and the other man is missing and presumed dead, police reported.
   Syrian shellfire destroyed fuel depots in the Christian enclave
March 30, creating a fuel shortage that has grown more acute.
   Dozens of small cargo ships carrying supplies and weapons
provided by Iraq, Syria's main Arab rival, have reached Christian
ports successfully but others either have been hit by Syrian fire or
turned back because of it.
   The tanker was shelled several hours after three Lebanese cargo
vessels used to run food supplies to the Christians were blown up in
the port of Sidon, 25 miles south of Beirut.
   Sidon is predominantly Sunni Moslem. The Sunnis have stayed out
of the fighting and merchants in Sidon have been shipping food to
the Christian ports by night.
   A cease-fire proclaimed by the Arab League in April has been
violated regularly.
   Lebanon's government and army have been split on sectarian lines
since a political crisis arose last September.
   At the United Nations in New York on Friday, Lebanon protested
Israeli air raids, even as Israel conducted another raid against a
Palestinian guerrilla base.
   Lebanon's permanent U.N. representative, Rachid Fakhoury,
protested a raid on Wednesday against Bshamun, southeast of Beirut,
in which he said several people were killed or wounded.
   Israeli warplanes Friday attacked targets at Rashidiyeh, Lebanon.
Police said two children were wounded in a house near the beachside
guerrilla base of Palestinian terrorist leader Abu Nidal's
Fatah-Revolutionary Council.
</TEXT>
