<DOCNO> AP890616-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 2113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GeorgiaJudgeships     06-16 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Georgia Judgeships,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Objects To 48 Georgia Judgeships</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department, exercising its
authority under the Voting Rights Act of 1965, objected Friday to
state legislation creating two judicial circuits and 48 Superior
Court judgeships in Georgia.
   The objection renders the judgeships ``null and void,'' said
Kathleen Wilde, an American Civil Liberties Union attorney. An ACLU
lawsuit challenging Georgia's method of election of all Superior
Court judges as racially discriminatory is pending in federal court.
   The Voting Rights Act requires that Georgia and other Southern
states submit all voting or election changes to the Justice
Department, which must determine that the changes have neither a
racially discriminatory purpose or effect before they can take
effect.
   The 48 judgeships covered by the department's objection Friday _
out of 137 total Superior Court judgeships in the state _ were
created since passage of the Voting Rights Act in 1965, Ms. Wilde
said
   Deborah Burstion-Wade, a spokeswoman for the civil rigts division
of the Justice Department, had no immediate comment on the
department's action.
   But Georgia Attorney General Mike Bowers said he had been
notified of the department's objection and was studying it.
   ``I'm not sure what this means,'' he said.
   Ms. Wilde said the Justice Department's objection was based on
Bower's refusal to provide the department with requested information
on the racial makeup of the new judicial districts.
   The lawsuit pending in Brunswick challenges the at-large method
Georgia uses to elect Superior Court judges. In an at-large
election, two or more judges are chosen by the voters of an entire
jurisdiction created by the state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
