<FIRST>u w AM-US-GermanAlert 2ndLd-Writethru   06-16 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-German Alert, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0754,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Warns of German Travel Alert</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Condenses earlier to top four grafs; remainder background from
Germany; adds byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department issued a travel alert
Friday to call attention to stepped-up anti-terrorist precautions at
Frankurt airport in West Germany and the conclusion of authorities
there that terrorist attacks ``cannot be ruled out.''
   The department did not advise travelers to avoid the airport,
believed by many investigators to have been the place where a bomb
was placed on the Pan American jetliner that exploded over Scotland
in December with 270 deaths.
   The alert quoted from a statement issued by German officials from
the state of Hesse, which said:
   ``Security measures at Frankfurt airport remain at a high level.
This is primarily due to the aggravated situation in the Arab
region. Terrorist actions, especially in the area of the Frankfurt
airport, cannot be ruled out. The security measures tie in with an
investigative proceeding against a terrorist organization which has
become active in the Frankfurt area.''
   In a similar announcement Tuesday, police in Frankfurt said they
were searching for Palestinian terrorists who might be planning
attacks in West Germany.
   Kurt Kraus, a Frankfurt police spokesman, said the search and
security alert was linked to ``recent activities of terror groups in
the Middle East'' and there appeared to be a connection with the
conviction of TWA hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, was sentenced to life in prison
after being convicted by a Frankfurt court in May on charges of air
piracy and murder in the 1985 TWA hijacking.
   A U.S. Navy diver was killed and 39 Americans were held for 17
days during the ordeal.
   Federal prosecutors have said they believe the suspected
terrorists to be members of a group called the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine-General Command.
   The Syrian-supported group has been mentioned as a prime suspect
in the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103.
   Police raids last October uncovered weapons and explosives and 14
Palestinians were arrested. Warrants have since been issued for four
of the suspects.
   Kraus said police suspect other members of the group are still at
large in West Germany.
</TEXT>
