<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 2110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ExplosivesFound     06-16 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Explosives Found,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Evacuated After Workers Find Dynamite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 7,500 people were evacuated from their
homes and businesses for about three hours Friday while authorities
burned nine cases of old dynamite found by a warehouse cleanup crew.
   The evacuees included 4,000 employees at Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber
Co. In addition, 150 residents of the Middlebury Manor nursing home
were taken to two high schools and hospitals, said police Capt.
David Whitmire.
   Workers at Guran Concrete &amp; Supply Co. found 450 sticks of
dynamite after prying off the lid of a container in a warehouse,
said fire Capt. John Robles. Authorities were alerted about 11 a.m.
   The evacuation was ordered about an hour later when the bomb crew
decided the best way to handle the dynamite was to slowly burn it in
a dirt bunker, Robles said.
   Elmer Guran, one of the company's owners, said the dynamite had
been in the warehouse for about 20 years but was not sure where it
came from.
   ``From what we can tell it was part of an acquisition of a
construction company that went bankrupt in 1969,'' said
   The dynamite was burned shortly after 3 p.m. Flames shot 15-20
feet high, but there was no explosion.
   Dan Testa, deputy fire chief, said the evacuation was necessary
because there was a small chance of an explosion.
   ``You hate to do some of the things necessary, but you are
dealing with people's lives,'' he said.
   The evacuation order took in a mostly industrial but partly
residential area within 2,000 feet of the dynamite. It also shut
down an Ohio Edison Co. substation, cutting power to 4,170
residential and business customers, said spokesman Bud Carter.
   In addition, natural gas service in the neighborhood was shut
off, officials said.
   ``Everything went amazingly well,'' said Sue Gregg, administrator
of the nursing home, although some of the patients didn't want to
go. When they got to the high school, they had lunch and a
singalong, she said.
   The evacuation was the second in Akron this year. About 2,000
residents were evacuated following a chemical train derailment Feb.
26.
   It also was the second time in Ohio since 1986 that residents had
to be evacuated because of dynamite.
   In October 1986, about 1,700 residents of Columbus' east side
were forced to flee their homes temporarily after employees of a
storage company found a dozen 50-pound cases of unstable dynamite in
a locker. Burning that dynamite without moving it caused about
$40,000 in damage.
   The owner of the Columbus dynamite, John G. Rieder of Kansas
City, Mo., was sentenced to six months in prison, fined $1,000 and
ordered to make restitution.
</TEXT>
