<FIRST>u w AM-GeorgiaJudges 1stLd-Writethru   06-16 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Georgia Judges, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0758,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Objects To 48 Georgia Judgeships</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Reorganizes throughout to incorporate Justice Department explanations
in grafs 2-3.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department objected Friday to
Georgia laws that created two judicial circuits and 48 elected
Superior Court judgeships over the past 24 years.
   The action was disclosed in a letter to state officials from
James P. Turner, an acting assistant attorney general in the civil
rights division. Under the 1965 Civil Rights Act, the objection
renders the laws legally unenforceable until the department's
objection is withdrawn or overturned in court.
   But Deborah Burstion-Wade, a spokeswoman for the civil rights
division, said the department's objection does not prevent the 48
sitting judges from continuing to fulfill their duties, nor does it
provide a basis for challenging their past decisions.
   The Voting Rights Act requires that Georgia and other Southern
states submit all voting or election changes to the Justice
Department, which must determine that the changes have neither a
racially discriminatory purpose nor effect before they can take
effect.
   The 48 judgeships covered by the department's objection Friday _
out of 137 total Superior Court judgeships in the state _ all were
created since passage of the Voting Rights Act.
   But the state of Georgia did not submit any of the 48 judgeships
to the Justice Department for approval until after a 1986 Supreme
Court ruling made it clear that the creation of elected judgeships
was an election change covered by the Voting Rights Act.
   Turner said in the letter that the department's objection was
based on the refusal of state officials to respond to requests for
additional information needed to determine if the new judgeships and
judicial circuits were free from racial discrimination.
   Turner said, however, that the department is ``ready and willing
to reconsider'' its objection if the state provides the requested
information on the racial makeup of the new judicial districts and
the General Assembly's rationale for creating them.
   Georgia Attorney General Mike Bowers said he was studying
Turner's letter. ``I'm not sure what this means,'' he said.
   Kathleen Wilde, an American Civil Liberties Union attorney whose
lawsuit challenging Georgia's method of election of all Superior
Court judges as racially discriminatory is pending in U.S. District
Court in Brunswick, said the Justice Department action ``will
strengthen my hand.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 2134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Irish 1stLd-Writethru   06-16 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0739,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Returns Indicate Prime Minister's Party Fails Fifth Attempt For Majority</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with 122 seats decided, indicating
Haughey's party falling short of majority. Pickup 13th graf `Foreign Minister...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Charles Haughey appeared to
fall short in his fifth attempt to achieve a majority for hs party
in parliamentary elections, state television said Saturday.
   The real surprises were the surge of the left, with gains for the
Labor Party and the Workers Party, and the collapse of the
center-right Progressive Democratic party, the electoral partner of
Fine Gael.
   Computer projections for the RTE network indicated that in
Thursday's election Haughey's Fianna Fail party won no more than 77
seats, a loss of three from its position when the Dail (parliament)
was dissolved in May.
   Ballot boxes were opened Friday morning, and by early Saturday
122 seats had been decided: Fianna Fail 55, Fine Gael 38, Labor
Party 12, Progressive Democrats 4, Workers Party 7, Democratic
Socialist 1, Green Party 1, independent and others 4.
   Roger Garland, the Green Party winner, was the first of his party
to win a seat in the Dail.
   If Haughey forms a coalition it would be the first time since
1969 that an Irish government won a second term.
   ``One of the disappointing things is that Irish politics may now
become polarized between right and left,'' said Des O'Malley, the
Progressive Democrat leader who won re-election. ``I think that
would be a great pity.''
   Fianna Fail's general secretary, Frank Wall, conceded that the
best his party could do would be 82 seats, one short of a majority.
   ``Mr. Haughey is now a five-time loser,'' Fine Gael party leader
Alan Dukes declared.
   Fianna Fail won 81 seats in 1987 and held 80 when the Dail was
dissolved. Fine Gael got 51 seats in 1987, Labor 12, the Progressive
Democrats 14, Workers Party 4 and others 4.
   Foreign Minister Brian Lenihan of Fianna Fail was the first
confirmed winner. He missed the campaign to undergo a liver
transplant at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., but easily held
his district in Dublin West.
   Haughey swept to a predictable victory in his own Dublin
constituency.
   In Ireland's complicated election system, a quota is set in each
constituency for the number of votes needed for election.
   Voters mark their ballots in order of preference, up to five
choices. If no candidate reaches the quota, the vote ``transfers''
to the voter's second choice, and so on.
   About 77 percent of the 2.4 million eligible voters turned out
Thursday in hot sunshine.
   Haughey, 63, has failed in four elections since 1979 to win a
majority, relying on the support of splinter groups and
independents. He called the latest election three years ahead of
schedule when his poll ratings were high and he sensed a chance for
a majority, but his ratings have dropped since.
   Despite his lack of a majority in the last parliament, Haughey
was able to implement a sweeping austerity program to ease the
country's debt and bring down interest rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 2148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Arrest     06-16 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Arrest,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Leader Says Salvadoran Police Tortured Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union leader said Friday he
was tortured by police agents who held him captive for four days and
threatened to kill him if he reported the incident.
   Jose Tomas Mazariego, a leader of the National Unity of
Salvadoran Workers, said he was seized Monday after he left the U.S.
Embassy where he went to pick up a visa for a trip to the United
States. He was released Thursday night.
   A communique issued by the Treasury Police, an agency that deals
with security, confirmed Mazariego had been detained and said he
suffered slight injuries while resisting police who took him into
custody.
   Mazariego, who sought the visa after he was invited to the United
States to address several union meetings, gave this account of his
detainment in an interview with The Associated Press:
   After he left the embassy accompanied by a friend ``I noticed
they (police) followed me in two cars.
   ``Armed men with rifles and dressed in civilian clothing detained
me violently and fired at my companion, who tried to impede the
capture. ... They did not identify themselves and hit me when I
protested.''
   ``After they captured me they blindfolded my eyes and I stayed
that way the whole time. They put a hood on me and kicked me in the
knees and the feet.
   ``They wanted to apply electric shock, but the apparatus didn't
work and they kicked me again. I hurt all over.'' He showed the
bruises on his legs.
   He was not allowed to sleep and his captors ``tried to get me to
admit participation in attacks by urban guerrillas of the FMLN
(Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front.'' The FMLN is a
coalition of leftist groups battling the U.S.-backed government.
   The Treasury Police communique said Mazariego was questioned
about belonging to a rebel organization and claimed he is a member
of the Armed Forces of Liberation. That group purportedly is a
branch of the Salvadoran Communist Party and one of the armed
organizations in the FMLN.
   The communique said Mazariego has been under investigation since
1987.
   Mazariego said that while he was being interrogated and beaten,
the police agents told him ``the former government was too slow and
with the arrival of (President Alfredo) Cristiani, they now have
complete license to finish with all the unions, which they called
facades for the FMLN.''
   Cristiani, leader of the conservative Nationalist Republican
Alliance, was installed in office June 1 after his party defeated
the incumbent Christian Democrats in the March elections.
   Mazariego said the police agents tried to link the National Unity
of Salvadoran Workers, El Salvador's largest labor organization,
with the FMLN and asked him about three union leaders, Humberto
Centeno, Marco Tulio Lima and Julio Cesar Portillo.
   He said the ``torturers'' told him Lima and Centeno ``should not
still be alive ... and when an opportune times, they (police) will
act.''
   Mazariego said when the blindfold was removed and he was freed
his captors told him he would be killed if he made any complaint.
   Denys Everingham of Local 1034 of the Communications Workers of
America in Trenton, N.J., said Tuesday that Mazariego had been
scheduled to speak at a union meeting in Philadelphia on Thursday.
He also said Mazariego, an official of the Salvadoran
Telecommunications Union, had planned to attend a union meeting next
Monday in New Jersey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
