<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     06-16 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Army Gunfire Kills Three Palestinians, Wounds 13, Reports
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed three Arabs and
wounded at least 13 in clashes in Rafah in the Gaza Strip Friday,
and soldiers used rubber bullets and clubs to curb a riot outside a
Gaza prison, Arab reports said.
   The army said it was investigating events in the occupied
territory. It confirmed one death but said it had no information
about the other two.
   In the occupied West Bank town of Tulkarem, masked youths Friday
attacked a fellow Palestinian accused of collaborating with Israel,
stabbing him with a knife and firebombing his car, Israeli and
Palestinian news reports said.
   The army confirmed that Bassam Akhras, 26, was slightly wounded.
   The 18-month revolt against Israeli occupation has killed 520
Palestinians and 22 Israelis.
   Army Chief of Staff Dan Shomron said on Israel radio that Israel
has the military force to quell the uprising but will not resort to
extreme measures to end the violence.
   Israeli columnist Zeev Schiff wrote in the Haaretz daily on
Friday that right-wing politicians have pressured the army to adopt
more brutal measures and to treat Palestinians as ``bona fide enemy
soldiers.''
   The army so far has rejected the call, refusing to do the
politicians' ``dirty work,'' Schiff said.
   Troops in Rafah fatally wounded Valid Omar Abu Abed, 23, in the
abdomen and he died at Nasser hospital in Khan Yunis, hospital
officials reported.
   The army confirmed the death, saying Abu Abed was shot during a
demonstration in which Palestinians hurled stones and metal bars at
soldiers.
   Arab reports said the death touched off riots at the crowded Idna
neighborhood and army reinforcements poured in.
   Palestinian reports and Israel radio said Amir Fuad Nasser, 25,
died of a gunshot wound to the head and 17-year-old Ahmed Abed Rabbo
Abu Oun was fatally shot in the head and abdomen, and that both were
immediately buried in Rafah.
   Officials at Nasser hospital said they treated at least 13 Arabs
with gunshot wounds, including two boys, aged 11 and 12, shot in the
legs.
   Four other Arabs were shot and wounded in clashes elsewhere in
Gaza and the West Bank, Arab doctors said.
   They said four more were struck with rubber bullets, including a
45-year-old Palestinian woman from Bethlehem who lost her right eye
and a 17-year-old youth struck in the head.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
</TEXT>
