<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-OAS     06-16 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-OAS,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>OAS Mission Fails Again To Achieve Dialogue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Organization of American States
mission to Panama failed in its second attempt to persuade the
government and opposition to agree to hold negotiations on the
country's political crisis, officials said Thursday.
   Diego Cordovez, Ecuador's foreign minister and veteran U.N.
negotiator in the Afghan conflict, said ``it is necessary and
urgent'' that Panama's conflicting sectors open a dialogue.
   The conflict arose after the May 7 presidential election, which
was later nullified by the government. International observers said
opposition candidates won.
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, commander of the Defense Forces,
told the mission the military is unwilling to participate in
negotiations and that civilian government officials should hold the
discussions.
   The opposition insists Noriega and the military hold the real
power.
   The mission is scheduled to deliver a report on its findings at a
July 19 meeting of OAS foreign ministers.
   Guatemalan Foreign Minister Mario Palencia said the commissioners
are willing to return to Panama ``when it is verified that a
dialogue is about to begin.''
   Two of the four ministers left Wednesday night. Cordovez went to
Peru and the OAS secretary general, Joao Baena Soarez, went back to
Washington. Palencia and Sahadeo Basdeo, foreign minister of
Trinidad and Tobago, returned home Thursday.
   Noriega was indicted by two federal grand juries in Florida last
year on drug-trafficking charges, charges he denies. Then-President
Eric Arturo Delvalle tried to fire him, but Noriega orchestrated his
ouster.
   The United States has frozen more than $140 million in Panamanian
bank deposits and canal payments, hobbling the banking indsutry and
leaving the government ill-equipped to meet payrolls or fund basic
social programs.
</TEXT>
