<FIRST>a a AM-PigeonRiver Adv19-1stAdd   06-16 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pigeon River, Adv 19-1st Add,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, June 19, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CANTON, N.C.: worked out.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Two years ago, the EPA tested a trout from the river and it had a
dioxin level of 90 parts per trillion, more than three times higher
than the consumption cutoff level recommended by the government.
Sludge taken from the river has tested as high as 260 parts per
trillion.
   ``If, after three years the company has met all of our
requirements, we will issue them a discharge release permit,''
Marlar said. ``Meanwhile, as long as they continue to operate
without a permit they are leaving themselves liable to possible
legal actions.''
   Blackwell estimated the compromise proposal would mean a 50
percent reduction of the mill's workforce over the next few years.
He said it will cost Champion about $300 million to install the
necessary technology.
   ``But,'' he added, ``it will allow us to remain in operation. So
we can live with this compromise if we have to.''
   Whether the people downstream can accept the three-year plan is
another matter.
   ``Something should be done, right away,'' Joe Hall said. ``It's
wrong to let a company destroy a beautiful river simply in the name
of profits.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Strat Douthat is the AP Southeast regional
reporter, based in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
