<FIRST>s w BC-Rich-PoorSchools Adv18   06-16 1172</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Rich-Poor Schools, Adv 18,1207</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 18, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kentucky Ruling May Signal New Life For School Finance Reform Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1964, a University of Chicago law student
named Arthur Wise got the novel idea that school funding formulas
based on unequal property taxes violated the constitution.
   Twenty-five years later, that legal theory by a fledgling lawyer
has helped change the shape of school finance in some three dozen
states.
   This month, Kentucky became the latest to feel its effects. That
state's highest court ordered the legislature to come up with a new
system of public schooling that gives rich and poor kids an even
shake.
   As radical as that may sound, nearly three decades of experience
with school funding reform suggests that change in Kentucky will be
slow in coming _ and probably hard fought.
   By 1967, Wise had spelled out his theories in a book, ``Rich
Schools Poor Schools.'' The idea, simple but elegant, was that
funding formulas used by virtually all states deny children in poor
communities ``equal protection of the law'' as guaranteed by the
14th Amendment.
   States, and even some educators, have countered that intangibles
like dedication count more than money in creating better schools.
Reformers like Wise insist that all the dedication in the world
won't provide kids foreign language teachers and decent science
labs. Only money can.
   Wise's 228-page book became the bible for the budding school
finance reform movement. The cause won big victories in the 1970s
when civil rights and equity topped the education agenda.
   One result: the average state share of education spending rose
from 40.9 percent in 1970 to an estimated 50.2 percent in 1989,
while the local share dipped from 51.8 percent to 43.6 percent,
according to National Education Association statistics. The
remaining share is federal aid.
   Finance reform faded through the 1980s as state money tightened,
the property tax revolt spread, and the education reform debate
shifted from equity to excellence.
   But the funding reform movement is showing signs of new life
lately. That's especially true in some agricultural states where
poor districts, already strapped by declining farm values and lower
property tax receipts, nonetheless must meet state mandates for
costly school reforms.
   Montana's Supreme Court declared that state's school funding
system unconstitutional in February. The Legislature opens a special
session on Monday to meet a July 1 deadline to devise a new one.
   A similar challenge in Texas is heading for that state's highest
court, as is one in New Jersey. A group of poor Tennessee districts
have banded together to sue that state.
   In Kentucky, the Supreme Court decision didn't stop at ordering
an overhaul of state school funding to make it fairer to poor
children. It said the whole school system had to change, top to
bottom.
   ``Lest there be any doubt, the result of our decision is that
Kentucky's entire system of common schools is unconstitutional,''
wrote Chief Justice Robert Stephens.
   Rich and poor alike ``must be given the same opportunity and
access to an adequate education,'' the court ruled in the case
brought four years ago by a coalition of 66 ``property poor''
Kentucky districts.
   Wise and other school finance experts called the ruling a
bombshell, probably the most sweeping of its kind. Yet history
suggests change may not be as quick or dramatic as the ruling
implies.
   ``Even when you win, you have to go to the state legislature and
start all over again,'' said Peter D. Veillette, a school finance
specialist at the National Education Association.
   It's been 16 years, for example, since New Jersey's highest court
ruled in Robinson vs. Cahill that that state's financing system
violated the state constitution's education clause guaranteeing a
``thorough and efficient system of free public schools.''
   But inequities persist, and lawyers representing poor New Jersey
students will reargue the case in state Supreme Court next September.
   Wise, now director of the RAND Corporation's Center for the Study
of the Teaching Profession in Washington, said that affluent
Moorestown, N.J., spends $3,000 more per pupil than East Orange,
N.J. One result is that Moorestown provides one computer per 11
students, compared to one per 43 East Orange pupils.
   New Jersey state education commissioners have criticized poor
districts for the weak quality of schooling ``but have failed along
with the Legislature to provide full equalization,'' Wise said.
   ``The powers that be would rather regulate than provide money.''
   That doesn't mean such lawsuits accomplish nothing. It does mean
that the national scorecard has been uneven.
   The legal principles underlying the funding reform movement have
fared badly in federal court. They flunked their biggest test in
1973 when the U.S. Supreme Court sustained Texas' funding system. It
held that inequality was an unfortunate but unavoidable byproduct of
the principle of local control over schools.
   That setback led reform advocates to focus on state courts where
they found greater success.
   A recent study of school finance cases by Robert Berne, associate
dean of New York University's Graduate School of Public
Administration, found that state courts have overturned funding
systems in 11 states since 1970: New Jersey, Kansas, Wisconsin,
California, Connecticut, Washington, West Virginia, Wyoming,
Arkansas, and this year, Montana and Kentucky.
   The first big decision, Serrano vs. Priest in California in 1971,
has meant that per pupil spending is now virtually equal _ within
$200 per pupil _ in 95 percent of that state's school districts. An
added factor was property-tax slashing Proposition 13, which led the
state to increase its share of education spending from 37.3 percent
in 1970 to 69.1 percent in 1989 to help bail out cash-starved
districts.
   But courts have sustained systems in 10 other states: Arizona,
Michigan, Idaho, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Georgia, Colorado, New
York and Maryland.
   Such states typically have defended their funding systems by
citing the Texas argument that the principle of local control of
schooling justified wide spending discrepancies among districts.
Many also cited ``effective-schools'' research suggesting that
dedication and sound school leadership mean more to learning than
money.
   Wise dismisses such arguments. No research has ever shown, he
said, ``that a school with high expectations and no German teacher
will produce students who speak German, or that a school with
orderly classrooms and no laboratory facilities will train its
students to be good scientists.''
   The recent history of school finance reform shows, above all,
that court rulings, even one so sweeping as in Kentucky, are but a
first step in a long, bitter and politically-charged process.
   As Michael W. La Morte, an education professor at the University
of Georgia, pointed out in a study published in November: ``Initial
responses by legislatures or state education agencies to
court-ordered reforms have frequently been brought back to courts
for later, and often protracted, rounds of deliberation.''
   School funding formulas die hard.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Mitgang, based in New York, has covered
education for the AP since 1981.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 18</NOTE>
