<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1715EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-AlaskaSpill-Changes Adv18   06-16 0880</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Alaska Spill-Changes, Adv 18,0901</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 18, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Spill Changes Tanker Operations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small navy of spill response vessels
being assembled in Prince William Sound is the most graphic evidence
of the changes affecting tanker traffic since the nation's worst oil
spill.
   ``We've had to scour the world for the equipment, and we're still
recruiting,'' says Tom Brennan of the Alyeska Pipeline Service Co.
The consortium of North Slope oil producers operates the
trans-Alaska pipeline that carries one-fourth of the nation's oil
supply, and the tanker terminal at Valdez.
   An interim plan Alyeska submitted in the face of criticism over
its handling of the Exxon Valdez spill provides for a response team
of 10 vessels and 48 people capable of skimming nearly 11,000
barrels an hour virtually anywhere in the sound within 10 hours. It
also calls for more pilots and escorts for tankers, and Breathalyzer
tests for tanker captains and crews.
   Crew members will be tested before entering the tanker terminal
if guards suspect they are intoxicated. Alyeska already has denied
three people access to their ships; drunken sailors previously were
turned over to their captains.
   Captains now are tested an hour before they sail; if they fail
they will be removed from their vessels and authorities will be
notified. All those tested apparently have passed the test Brennan
describes as very unusual. ``I don't think it's done anywhere else
in the world,'' he says.
   Under a plan in effect March 24, when the Exxon Valdez ran
aground on Bligh Reef and dumped almost 11 million gallons of oil,
Alyeska promised to have people and equipment on scene within five
hours. It took almost 12.
   Gov. Steve Cowper threatened to shut down the pipeline if Alyeska
didn't come up with something better, and six weeks later it offered
the new plan.
   Before the spill, one tugboat accompanied loaded tankers through
the Valdez Narrows into the sound. A state-licensed pilot got off
short of Bligh Reef.
   Under the new system, one tug and a 210-foot ``escort response
vessel'' will accompany every loaded tanker to Hinchenbrook
Entrance, leading from the sound to the Gulf of Alaska. The escort
vessel will have two skimmers, almost 14,000 feet of containment
boom and storage capacity of 4,000 barrels.
   Seventy-five to 80 loaded tankers leave Valdez a month, Brennan
says, and Alyeska will have three escorts, enough to handle the
tankers in the sound at any one time.
   State-licensed pilots will accompany tankers past Bligh Reef, the
last prominent obstacle between Valdez and Hinchenbrook. From there,
tankers must have a federally licensed pilot; some tanker captains
also are licensed pilots. Once past Hinchenbrook, all pilotage
restrictions are off.
   When traffic was backed up by weather or loading problems,
tankers have always anchored at Knowles Head, a sheltered area on
the southwest side of the peninsula between the Port of Fidalgo and
Port Gravina, about 30 miles south of Valdez.
   Under the new system, two more vessels will be anchored there
around the clock. One will be a tug with a barge capable of holding
140,000 barrels of oil. The other will have equipment to pump oil
off a damaged tanker and a storage capacity of 180,000 barrels.
Their only responsibility will be responding to a tanker accident.
   Two storage barges, with a combined capacity 136,000 barrels will
be kept in Valdez. Each will carry absorbent material and 16,000
feet of boom. Two tugs will be stationed there to tow the barges to
a spill and assist a grounded tanker. A vessel with boom deployment
equipment will round out the fleet.
   Another 8,000 feet of boom will be stored at the tanker terminal,
giving Alyeska a total of almost 39,000 feet _ almost twice as much
as was immediately available for the Exxon Valdez spill.
   It is still unclear what the new measures will cost. ``Obviously
it is in the millions of dollars. How many millions, we can't say
yet,'' Brennan says.
   One thing that hasn't changed is Coast Guard monitoring of tanker
traffic.
   Lt. Cmdr. Tom Falkenstein, second in command of the Port of
Valdez marine safety office, emphasizes that the Coast Guard's role
is purely advisory as an aid to navigation. ``We do not control
their movements. We're not like air traffic controllers.''
   The ultimate responsibility always rests with a ship's master,
and federal law would have to change to give the Coast Guard more
authority, he says. ``I don't anticipate that we're going to begin
controlling vessel movements.''
   The Coast Guard has asked for about $12,000 in computer equipment
to improve its monitoring, but Falkenstein says he doesn't forsee
installation of stronger radar. He estimates the cost of providing
radar coverage of the entire sound at $24 million, not including
personnel and housing.
   Under ideal conditions, he says, the radar will reach just beyond
Bligh Reef. Ideal conditions are rare in Prince William Sound, and
frequently radar coverage won't reach even to the reef.
   ``Tanker traffic in the port has not changed significantly'' from
the Coast Guard's perspective, Falkenstein says. ``It's not business
as usual by any stretch. But our procedures haven't changed because
there was nothing wrong to begin with.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 18</NOTE>
