<FIRST>r f PM-IntegratedResources     06-16 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Integrated Resources,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insurance Firm Can't Meet Debt Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Integrated Resources Inc.'s stock price plunged
nearly 50 percent after the insurance and mutual fund company said
it was halting payment on $864 million in short-term debt.
   Integrated, which has $7.8 billion in assets, said Thursday the
problem affects only the parent company and not its affiliates and
subsidiaries nationwide, which would continue to make payments to
creditors.
   On Wednesday, banks withdrew Integrated's access to short-term
credit markets amid signs of weakening financial condition at the
firm.
   Integrated said it did not have the money to pay off its debt,
including some $373 million in commercial paper and loan shares that
come due in the next 45 days. The debt payments amount to about $8
million a day.
   Integrated also has $491 million in short-term bank credit lines
mostly payable on demand.
   The company's stock plunged $5.75 to close at $6.25 a share in
New York Stock Exchange trading Thursday. Volume was 1.7 million
shares, about four times the trading activity on Wednesday. The
stock closed at $15.37{ on Tuesday.
   ``The company believes it has a short-term liquidity problem,''
Integrated spokesman David Caouette said. ``We're working with a
group of banks and ... negotiations are being closely held and
they're progressing.''
   Integrated, founded in 1969, is a diversified financial services
company with operations in mutual funds and money management,
limited partnerships, and life insurance and annuities. It has $1.1
billion in capital.
   Analysts said Integrated has fared poorly in recent years as it
expanded but was unable to establish a foothold in the insurance
field. The company also says it has had problems because of high
up-front costs such as fees, commissions and carrying costs for
investments later sold as partnerships.
   Integrated issued a statement saying it had scheduled a meeting
of creditors and short-term credit suppliers for Monday to discuss
reaching a debt restructuring package.
   Integrated has said it is trying to arrange new credit with some
of its banks and exploring other sources of capital. On Wednesday,
its investment banker, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., halted sales of
Integrated's short-term commercial paper.
   Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the debt-rating service, on Thursday
lowered Integrated's rating on bonds, preferred stock and commercial
paper affecting about $1.2 billion in securities. It was the second
rating downgrade in two days.
</TEXT>
