<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time-Paramount     06-16 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Paramount,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount Increasing Pressure on Time, Prods Board for Response</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc., still awaiting a
response to its unwanted $10.7 billion takeover bid for Time Inc.,
has stepped up the pressure on the media giant by indicating it
might sweeten its offer.
   But investors were unimpressed Thursday by the prospect of a
higher bid for Time. The company's stock fell $3.62{ to $171.50 a
share on the New York Stock Exchange on reports the Time board was
leaning toward making a cash tender offer for Warner Communications
Inc. as a way to foil Paramount's $175-a-share bid.
   Time and Warner previously agreed to merge in an all-stock deal.
   In a letter sent Thursday to Time's directors, Paramount Chairman
Martin S. Davis said, ``Since our offer commenced, no representative
of Time has contacted us to discuss our proposal.''
   The Time board, which was considering how to fight Paramount and
whether it could salvage Time's merger with Warner, seemed to be in
no rush to reply to the offer or Davis' letter.
   Time spokesman Edward Adler said the company had no comment on
the letter and would not say when it would respond.
   George Sard, a spokesman for Paramount, an entertainment and
publishing conglomerate, declined to comment on the purpose of the
letter, saying it ``speaks for itself.''
   However, observers said the letter was intended to pressure the
Time board. Davis said Paramount might be willing to raise its bid
if a review of Time's financial records justified a higher offer.
Davis called for a meeting between the two companies at which
Paramount could examine Time's books.
   Time stock _ which has traded as high as $182.75 a share since
the Paramount bid was announced _ fell on the prospect of a Time bid
for Warner, which cast doubt on the Paramount offer. Time has a $5
billion line of credit that it could use to help finance a bid.
   An offer for Warner was one of several options the Time board was
believed to be considering. The others included a recapitalization
of the company, a cash tender offer for Paramount or a continued
pursuit of its planned merger with Warner. Warner also could launch
a cash tender offer for Time.
   Stock in Paramount, formerly called Gulf &amp; Western Inc., was
unchanged at $59.50 a share Thursday, while Warner picked up 62{
cents to close at $55.62{ a share.
   Under the planned Time-Warner merger, Time stockholders would get
a share in the new company for each share they own while Warner
shareholders would get 0.465 of a share of the new company for each
of their Warner shares.
   However, if the two companies were to pursue their merger, it was
widely expected the deal would have to be renegotiated because
Time's stock price has soared from the $126 level it fetched before
Paramount announced its bid.
   In a separate development Thursday, Time and Warner said New York
city officials approved the proposed transfers in ownership of the
six cable franchises in the city owned by either Time or Warner.
   Time and Warner together own cable systems serving about 5.5
million subscribers, but must get permission from local cable
authorities in each case to combine their respective operations
under a Time Warner umbrella.
</TEXT>
