<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-16 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Suffers Biggest Plunge in Recent Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: version also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar today suffered its biggest
single-day plunge in recent years against the Japanese yen, traders
said, while stock prices gained moderately.
   The dollar closed at 145.05 yen, down from Thursday's closing of
151.30 yen.
   The 6.25-yen drop was reportedy the dollar's largest daily
fluctuation between sessions ever, though an official of the Bank of
Japan, the nation's central bank, said no records were available.
   Several traders contacted by The Associated Press said they could
not remember a larger day-to-day loss.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
489.90 points Thursday in its largest single-day loss this year,
recouped 142.08 points, or 0.43 percent, to finish the week at
33,055.17.
   Volume traded on the first section totaled 500 million shares, up
from 650 million the previous day.
   Traders attributed the dollar's retreat to concerted intervention
overnight by the U.S. and European central banks in overseas markets.
   The Bank of Japan was reported to have sold $200 million to $300
million this morning to accelerate the currency's downward trend,
they said.
   An official of Fuji Bank, a major Japanese commercial bank, said
the dollar ``made a major correction'' after weeks of excessive
rallies against other currencies.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Thursday the nation's
merchandise trade deficit fell to $8.26 billion in April from
March's revised deficit of $9.54 billion.
   Stock dealers said trading was thin in anticipation of the
release of further U.S. economic indicators, including the nation's
consumer price figures for May, due later today in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
