<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     06-16 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rallies Despite Intervention, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: version also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rallied somewhat today in early
European trading after plunging in the United States and Tokyo.
   Gold prices were higher.
   Traders said reports of coordinated central bank intervention _
intended to bring the U.S. currency down _ had tended to strengthen
the dollar.
   They said sentiment remained much in favor of the dollar and
attributed Thursday's substantial single-day drop in the United
States to technical selling.
   ``The (dollar's) drop was just too much. Sentiment cannot have
changed so radically,'' said one Italian trader. He said the central
bank intervention wasn't heavy enough to affect rates and the dollar
remained well bid.
   Another Italian trader noted that ``many European banks found the
dollar at relatively cheap levels this morning and started buying
the U.S. unit.''
   The West German Bundesbank started the intervention early today
and was followed by several other European central banks. However,
traders said the intervention was modest.
   In Tokyo, the dollar suffered its biggest single-day plunge in
recent years today but rallied in later European trading. The dollar
fell 6.25 yen to a closing 145.05 yen in Tokyo. Later in London, it
was quoted at a higher rate of 147.05 yen.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.53075 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5195 late Thursday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday
included: 2.0055 West German marks, down from 2.0235; 1.7290 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7490; 6.8068 French francs, down from 6.8680;
2.2459 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2915; 1,451.50 Italian lire, down
from 1,472.00, and 1.1985 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1993.
   Gold opened in London at $365.80 a troy ounce, compared with late
Thursday's $362.50. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $365.35.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $365.80 compared with $361.71 late
Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose $5.10 to close at $366.67.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.31 a troy ounce, up from
Thursday's $5.29.
</TEXT>
