<FIRST>r f PM-Searle-Settlement     06-16 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Searle-Settlement,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Searle Settles Some IUD Claims, Still Faces About 350 More</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SKOKIE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   G.D. Searle &amp; Co. has agreed to settle the
claims and lawsuits of more than 100 people linked to its Copper-7
contraceptive device, but a spokeswoman said about 350 other cases
still are pending in courts.
   The agreement, which requires approval from the affected clients
of the Minneapolis law firm of Robins, Kaplan, Miller and Ciresi,
bars disclosure of any details, said Searle spokeswoman Kay Bruno.
   The settlement also bars the parties from disclosing how many
individuals were covered by the settlement, although the law firm
previously said it represented more than 100 people.
   Even so, Ms. Bruno said the settlement leaves about 350 other
Copper-7 lawsuits in state and federal courts.
   ``At last count, 330 cases involving the Copper-7 had been
disposed of in our favor. Of the 19 that went to trial, we won 15
and lost four,'' said Ms. Bruno.
   ``Two of those are pending appeal and of the two completed, we
have paid a total of about $300,000,'' she added.
   Ms. Bruno confirmed the June 9 agreement in response to questions
from reporters. She also said the settlement ``does not have a
materially adverse effect'' on the financial positions of Searle or
its parent, Monsanto Corp.
   Women who have brought lawsuits against the Skokie-based
pharmaceutical concern contend the Copper-7, once one of the
nation's most widely prescribed intrauterine devices, caused pelvic
inflammations, ectopic pregnancies or perforation of the uterus, and
could result in infertility.
   A Baltimore lawyer whose firm is representing clients in 40
lawsuits and evaluating the claims of several hundred more called
the settlement ``a hopeful sign.''
   ``I couldn't estimate what the settlement may have been worth. My
guess is, that like our firm, Robins, Kaplan, Miller had one group
of cases pending in court and a second group whose cases were being
investigated for possible lawsuits,'' attorney H. Robert Erwin Jr.
said from Baltimore.
   ``Typically, IUD cases can range from $10,000 if the causation is
weak and the injury nominal to $250,000 or more if you have a young,
married couple rendered childless due to an infection from an IUD.''
   Searle pulled the product from the market, along with a second
IUD, in January 1986, citing the high costs stemming from hundreds
of lawsuits. The company has maintained in court documents the
product ``cannot cause the various injuries plaintiffs claim.''
   Esther Kociemba, represented by the Minneapolis firm, was awarded
$8 million last year by a jury in St. Paul, Minn. It could not be
determined whether that case was part of the settlement.
   Michael Ciresi, who has been the firm's lead attorney in Copper-7
cases, did not return messages left with his office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0801EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GarbageMagazine     06-16 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Garbage Magazine,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Magazine: `Garbage' Promises to Get Down and Dirty</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new magazine devoted to the pros and cons of
biodegradable diapers and other ways of dealing with debris promises
to do more than just talk trash.
   If you say, ``What garbage!'' you're not a likely reader of
Garbage.
   But the publishers of this new magazine say the ``throwaway
society'' has gone beyond the concern of the counterculture to
become a mainstream issue.
   ``I think we all feel vaguely uneasy and vaguely guilty when you
bring the groceries home and realize that 60 percent of what you've
bought is packaging,'' said editor-publisher Patricia Poore.
   Formally known as ``Garbage: The Practical Journal for the
Environment,'' it will start publishing in August. Ms. Poore, 33,
said it will have a pro-environment tilt but she promises to be
even-handed.
   ``You have to be pro-environment if you want any quality of life
and possibly if you want any life at all,'' she said, but her
magazine will also print the downside to proposed solutions to
environmental problems.
   When an environmentally sound way of doing things turns out to be
more costly, especially for the poor, Garbage will so report, said
Ms. Poore. ``There often is no easy solution,'' she said.
   The first question the magazine had to confront was whether it
should be printed on recycled paper. The answer may seem obvious,
Ms. Poore said, but it was not.
   ``The editor in me wanted recycled paper,'' she said. ``The
publisher in me didn't.
   ``Recycled paper looks like whole wheat,'' she said. (This was
the publisher speaking.) ``It has gooky things in it. They say it
will break on the press.
   ``The publisher in me said there was nothing wrong with premium
paper. And the printer told us they would charge 30 percent more to
print it on recycled paper!''
   But the art director and the managing editor marched in and said
Ms. Poore would be a hypocrite if she printed Garbage on virgin
paper. The printer, in environmentally conscious Burlington, Vt.,
relented and promised to charge nothing extra for the first three
issues and see how things come out.
   Research located a recycled paper that ``is very white, and film
coated and is easily recyclable itself,'' Ms. Poore said, so the
environment (and the editor) won the battle, for the moment.
   Ms. Poore owns The Old-House Journal, which, like Garbage, is
based in Brooklyn, N.Y. The Old-House Journal was a neighborhood
paper for owners of brownstones in Brooklyn when she bought it 11
years ago, just as the preservation movement was catching on. It now
has a circulation ``approaching 165,000.''
   Garbage, she said, will be the only environmental magazine that
is not issued by activists and therefore free ``to have a sense of
humor.''
   ``If you're the Sierra Club, you've got to take a worst-case view
and a sense of humor is a dangerous thing to have,'' she said.
   The pros and cons of biodegradable diapers will be examined in
the first issue.
   Pro: they self-destruct.
   Con: they introduce human waste into landfills and possibly water
tables.
   The magazine's conclusion: cloth diapers are better, from the
environment's point of view.
   In a solicitation for subscriptions that was mailed to 700,000
homes a week ago (printed on recycled paper, too), Ms. Poore
explains the choice of the magazine's name:
   ``Here we were, planning a new environmental journal, but my
staff and I found ourselves referring to it as `the garbage
magazine.' It dawned on us that that was the right name ... It
doesn't beat around the bush, but goes right to the heart of the
problem: our throwaway society.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Fathers-Guilt     06-16 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fathers-Guilt,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fathers Feel Torn Between Careers, Family, Too</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fathers who take time off for the birth of a
baby will become the majority in the coming decade, says a new study
that finds dads joining moms in the struggle to cope with work and
family responsibilities.
   ``Balancing work and family responsibilities is becoming a total
work force issue, not just a women's issue,'' reports Sandra Burud
of Burud &amp; Associates in Pasadena, Calif., in the analysis ``The
1990s Father: Balancing Work &amp; Family Concerns.''
   ``We tend to think working moms have a monopoly on guilt, but
it's not true,'' added James Levine of Bank Street College of
Education in New York.
   While fathers continue to face traditional pressure to do well at
work, they also want to spend more time with their children,
reported Levine.
   He and Burud were among several researchers included in the study
compiled by the Bureau of National Affairs, an independent
Washington research group.
   Men are ``feeling that they're repeating the same pattern of
their own fathers, not being around enough,'' noted Levine in the
analysis issued to coincide with Fathers Day.
   A generation ago it would not have occurred to most new fathers
to take time off for the birth of a child, an increasingly common
practice today, said Barney Olmstead, co-director of New Ways to
Work in San Francisco.
   Joseph Pleck of Wheaton College in Norton, Mass., predicts that
fathers taking time off for the birth of a child will become
increasingly commonplace.
   In the 1990s, he said, ``it will become the dominant pattern for
fathers to take one or two weeks off and that the proportion of
fathers who take longer periods of time will grow.
   ``Men are spending more time with their kids, and men and women
are sharing the time they're staying home with sick children,''
reported Carol Ann Rudolph of Child Care Management Resources in
Bethesda, Md. ``But when child-care arrangements break down, it
still is the woman who misses work more often than the man.''
   Fran Rodgers of Work-Family Directions reported that many men are
beginning to seek a balance between work and family _ ``they don't
want to work overtime, they don't want to relocate, and they don't
want their performance measured in terms of hours put in on the
job.''
   ``The intensity of feelings is greater for women, but they're
there for both'' she said.
   While so-called ``family-friendly'' company policies have largely
concentrated on women, more and more they will need to consider
males also, according to the study.
   ``Fathers still define themselves primarily in the family as the
provider,'' observed Stephen Segal of the Philadelphia firm Family
Partners. But, he added, they also are increasingly wanting to be
with their children.
   ``Fathers are connecting with their kids, their young kids, in a
stronger way, and there are expectations for them to connect in a
stronger way than their fathers had, and that sets up the conflicts
for the father as he moves through his career,'' Segal said.
   But, he added, ``It's not altogether socially acceptable for men
to stay home when their kids are sick and such.''
   Some companies are in the early stages of developing ways to aid
working fathers, commented Levine, who operates the Fatherhood
Project at Bank Street College.
   The BNA study said that where child-care facilities are provided,
fathers are increasingly likely to use the facilities and
increasingly often are the ones taking children to medical
appointments and for other obligations.
   Yet, said Patricia D. Hawkins of the U.S. Department of Health
and Human Services, these are relatively rare occasions. ``You
either have to be in a very senior position where you can call your
own shots, or be a specialist,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UnemploymentTax     06-16 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unemployment Tax,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subcommittee Votes Increase in a Tax, First of Bush Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time since President Bush was
elected on a no-tax-increase pledge, a congressional subcommittee
has voted to raise taxes.
   The House Ways and Means subcommittee on human resources is
calling for a boost in the tax that employers pay for federal
unemployment benefits, which would bring in an estimated $10.6
billion over the next five years. When fully in effect in 1992, it
would cost employers an additional $4 a year for each employee.
   The increase would finance improvements in jobless benefits and
higher spending for child care and welfare. It would also leave $161
million next year, and $1.7 billion over five years, toward reducing
the budget deficit.
   The package was approved by the subcommittee on a voice vote over
Republican opposition. It now goes to the full committee.
   Before the vote, Kenneth W. Gideon, assistant treasury secretary
for tax policy, said the administration is strongly opposed. In the
first place, he said, the unemployment fund does not need more money
_ a statement that was challenged by Democrats on the panel.
   ``Second,'' Gideon wrote, ``increasing the amount of wages
subject to federal unemployment tax is a tax increase and is opposed
by this administration.''
   Bush was elected after a campaign in which his opposition to a
tax increase was repeated several times a day. He also has predicted
that if taxes were raised, Congress would spend the money rather
than cut the deficit.
   ``It's basically a $10 billion tax increase ... and a wish list
of social spending,'' Rep. Hank Brown, R-Colo., a member of the
subcommittee, said of the bill. ``Many of the proposals have merit
but I don't think we have the money.''
   He predicted the tax increase will make it far more difficult for
the Ways and Means Committee to meet its deficit-reduction goal.
   Present law requires employers to pay a tax of 0.8 percent of the
first $7,000 earned annually by each employee, a maximum of $56 per
worker. The rate is due to drop to 0.6 percent in 1991.
   The subcommittee's bill would raise the taxable wage to $8,000 in
1990, $9,000 in 1991 and $10,000 in 1992. Thus, the employer's
maximum tax per employee would rise to $60.
   Rep. Thomas Downey, D-N.Y., chairman of the subcommittee,
rejected the administration's argument that the trust funds from
which unemployment compensation are paid need no extra money.
   ``These accounts currently do not have enough funds on reserve to
cover increased outlays if a recession occurs in the next few
years,'' Downey wrote in presenting his recommendation to the
subcommittee. He noted the administration's estimates are based on
economic assumptions that many economists say are too rosy.
   ``Even with the administration's optimistic assumptions over the
next five years, the administration has projected that the loan
account (which helps states replenish their jobless benefits) will
not have enough reserves by the end of 1994, when its shortfall will
be $3.5 billion,'' Downey said.
   Gideon also opposed the tax increase on grounds that because of
the way the unemployment-benefits system is structured, raising the
federal tax would automatically increase employers' state taxes.
   Among the spending improvements voted by the subcommittee were a
$1.77 billion increase in federal grants to states for such social
services as Meals on Wheels and child-care services; a boost in
Supplemental Security Income, a welfare program for elderly and
disabled, of $2 a month for individuals (to $370) and $3 a month for
couples (to $553); and making it easier for states to trigger
payment of extended unemployment benefits for the long-term jobless.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0803EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AlcoholTesting     06-16 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alcohol Testing,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Department Taking First Step Toward Alcohol Testing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department is taking the
first step toward nationwide random alcohol testing of airline
pilots, train engineers, ships' officers, pipeline workers and bus
and truck drivers.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner told Congress on Thursday
he had asked department lawyers to examine rule-making that would
expand the department's random drug-testing program to include
alcohol. Rules on drug testing of 4 million transportation workers
take effect at the end of the year.
   Skinner said alcohol testing raises complex issues and should not
begin hastily as proposed in a House bill requiring random testing
for both drugs and alcohol among railroad workers. Skinner said he
would recommend that President Bush veto that bill, if adopted,
because it would require the department to start over with its
testing program.
   Skinner testified at a hearing of the Senate Commerce, Science
and Transportation Committee which is considering its own version of
mandatory drug and alcohol testing for transportation workers.
   The Transportation Department last November ordered drug testing
programs in private transportation industries, but the programs face
several court challenges and the congressional bills would give
testing the force of law.
   The Supreme Court has approved some drug testing but has yet to
rule on random testing.
   At the hearing, the proposed Senate bill brought general support
from transportation industry representatives and strong objections
from groups representing the employees who would be tested. The bill
is nearly identical to measures passed by the Senate, but not the
House, in both 1987 and 1988.
   ``I have decided that we must step forward and address the issue
of alcohol misuse in transportation now,'' Skinner told the
committee.
   He noted that a Coast Guard program of mandatory post-accident
alcohol testing for the maritime industry begins in December, but
said more thought is needed before extending the testing to other
modes of transportation. He noted that alcohol is legal while the
drug testing covers illegal substances.
   Skinner said the House version of the anti-drug bill would
mandate random alcohol test rules just 90 days after enactment of
the bill. ``I look to the long term, and I know that to develop a
program that will achieve its objective and withstand legal
challenge requires more care and consideration,'' he said.
   Committee Chairman Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., said alcohol and
drug use by transportation workers cannot be ignored. He said
railroad accidents linked to drug or alcohol occurred once every 12{
days last year.
   ``Call it intimidation. Call it whatever you will,'' Hollings
said. ``But the fact is that random testing is the only method we
have to reasonably ensure that transportation employees will not use
drugs on the job.''
   Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, sponsor of the House drug bill, said
the bill requiring random testing of railroad workers has bipartisan
support. He accused Skinner of wanting anti-drug measures left to
the ``whims of the transportation secretary.''
   Richard B. Stone of the Air Line Pilots Association said errors
in testing could result in the loss of 200 pilots.
   Stone said no crash of a scheduled airliner has been linked to
alcohol abuse. The National Transportation Safety Board blamed a
January 1988 Colorado crash on cocaine use by the pilot, but Stone
said other possible causes of that crash were not adequately
investigated.
   Stone said random testing would cost the industry millions of
dollars but ``would not produce much.''
   Michael O'Connell, lawyer for a national association of
owner-operated trucks, said ``millions of innocent drivers will be
victimized'' by random tests.
   O`Connell introduced Sandy Craig of Anderson, Ind., who owns and
drives a single truck with her husband, as an example of a driver
who would have to give random urine samples.
   Mrs. Craig, interviewed after the hearing, said she opposes
roadside random testing because it would delay her trips, ``and I
think the procedure proposed is humiliating.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0804EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Britain-Fusion     06-16 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Fusion,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Scientists Say They Cannot Duplicate Cold Fusion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers at Britain's Atomic Energy Authority
say they were unable to reproduce cold fusion, something two
University of Utah scientists earlier this year claimed to have
achieved.
   After spending $480,000 over three months trying to repeat the
experiment, the scientists at the British Atomic Energy Authority's
Harwell Laboratory near Oxford said Thursday they failed.
   ``Not every mad idea works out,'' saidteam leader David Williams,
who nonetheless spoke admiringly of the previous work by the two
scientists.
   But one of the two, Martin Fleischmann of Southampton University,
stood by his findings.
   He told Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, ``We
cannot find any flaw in our technique, and we are very happy with
the work we have done so far.''
   Fleischmann and Stanley Pons, of the University of Utah, said on
March 23 they had generated energy with palladium and platinum
electrodes dipped in a beaker of heavy water at room temperature.
   Heavy water is made of oxygen and deuterium, a form of hydrogen
with a neutron in the nucleus.
   In fusion, tremendous amounts of energy are released when the
nucleus, or core, of one hydrogen atom fuses with the nucleus of
another hydrogen atom.
   In contrast, nuclear power plants generate energy from fission,
which is the splitting of atoms.
   Nuclear fusion is the energy source of the sun, and thousands of
researchers have been trying to achieve it for 20 years.
   Reporting on his team's results, Williams said it was unable to
detect a single neutron, the key sign indicating a fusion process is
occurring. It also found no heat produced.
   Williams told the British Broadcasting Corp: ``We've used three
different types of heat-flow instrument, we've used all sorts of
different types of neutron counters, we've used them upside down,
inside out, changed the solution. We've checked, we've calibrated:
everything.''
   ``We're very disappointed. This would have been a very
significant discovery,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
