<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0847EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UAWConvention     06-16 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAW Convention,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Autoworkers Gather for Constitutional Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers will gather for their
triennial constitutional convention just down the street from
Disneyland next week, but the atmosphere inside the convention
center may rife with hard feelings.
   Underneath the speeches, political wrangling and hoopla in
Anaheim, Calif., will be rumblings of dissent.
   Union President Owen Bieber, the Administration Caucus he runs
and the union's increasingly cooperative attitude toward management
have been sharply criticized by the New Directions movement,
spearheaded by Jerry Tucker of St. Louis, Mo., and Don Douglas of
Detroit.
   While the two are seeking seats as regional directors, they may
be dark-horse candidates. In local delegate elections, New
Directions candidates in Tucker's and Douglas's regions came up
short.
   Nevertheless, Tucker, who goes into the convention as director of
one of the UAW's largest regions in a position he won through a
federally supervised election last year, has said the New Directions
movement has widespread support, and that could show up in reports
from the convention's credentials and resolutions committees.
   The credentials committee certifies the seating of delegates.
It's possible that challenges could by mounted by New Directions
forces, which have contended that some delegate elections were won
by Administration Caucus supporters through questionable, and in
some cases illegal, means.
   Tucker has asked the union's hierarchy to review some of the
elections and has hinted that lawsuits could be filed over local
delegate elections. After all, Tucker has said in the past, that's
how he was elected director of UAW Region 5 in the first place.
   New Directions supporters also may show up around the middle of
the week-long convention if a resolution surfaces that would seek
delegate endorsement of more UAW representation on automakers'
boards of directors.
   Bieber sits on the board of Chrysler Corp., a position granted
during the early 1980s when the UAW signed concession contracts with
the nation's No. 3 automaker. The Detroit News reported Thursday
that the resolution also would support increased union cooperation
with management.
   Both of the issues are at the core of New Directions' arguments
with Bieber and the Administration Caucus.
   Despite potential challenges, Bieber is virtually assured of
election to a third, three-year term at the head of the huge union,
which during his administration has looked outside the auto industry
for members.
   Joining the traditional delegates from auto factory shop floors
will be representatives of Michigan state workers, clerical workers
from New England colleges and jai alai players.
   Among those addressing the convention are newly elected House
Majority Leader Richard Gephardt, Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, Sen. Edward Kennedy, former Rep. Barbara Jordan, New York
Gov. Mario Cuomo and NAACP President Benjamin Hooks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
