<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks     06-16 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Stocks Firmer At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were higher at midday Friday as
investors were relieved that the latest British inflation report
contained little to provoke an immediate hike in interest rates.
   One trader said participants felt a ``modicum of comfort'' after
the data showed a 0.6-percent increase in Britain's retail price
index for May, compared with a 1.8-percent rise in April. This put
the annual inflation rate at 8.3 percent.
   At midday, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was
up 9.4 points, or 0.4 percent, at 2,139.0.
   Turnover at midday registered 273.2 million shares.
   Traders said the market headed higher from the outset, bolstered
by sterling's renewed strength and a perception that the pressure on
an imminent rise in interest rates had eased.
</TEXT>
