<DOCNO> AP890616-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 0929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-KraftContest 1stLd-Writethru   06-16 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kraft Contest, 1st Ld-Writethru,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kraft Offers to Make Amends in Fouled-Up Contest, Not All Pleased</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5-6th grafs pvs, `At least...', with 4 grafs to UPDATE
number of lawsuits to at least three sted at least two; add that Kraft
official attributes error to other, unidentified company. Picks up 7th
graf pvs, `The promotion ...'. SUBS 15th graf, `Kraft's offer...', with
two grafs to add background, quote on attorneys general's role, picking
up 16th graf pvs, `Kraft said...' also moving general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   CHICAG0 (AP) _ Kraft's efforts to appease winners in its botched
``Ready to Roll'' game aren't winning over everybody.
   ``I don't mean to sound greedy, but the settlement offer is kind
of skimpy and it's a far cry from what was being offered,'' says
Larry Bernstein, who matched game pieces for a $17,000 van.
   Bernstein was one of an estimated several hundred people who
matched game pieces for a Dodge Caravan in a contest designed to
have only one van winner. Kraft on Thursday offered those winners
$250 and a special drawing for four vans.
   ``I'm not really too pleased,'' he said. ``You're talking $17,000
versus $250. I suspect lots of people will want to go ahead with the
lawsuits.''
   At least three class-action lawsuits have been filed against the
company.
   The suburban Chicago-based company, known formally as Kraft
General Foods Group of Philip Morris Cos., also offered to make up
for the mistake by quadrupling the number of prizes and giving away
cash to all winners.
   Kraft told the Sun-Times the mistake was made by the unidentified
companies that prepared the game, not Kraft.
   ``There was a mistake, obviously, but it was clearly
unintentional,'' said Mitch Weinick, president of Refrigerated
Products for Kraft USA. ``Because our customers are so good-natured
and good-humored, we're trying to do right by them.''
   The promotion was run only in the Chicago and Houston
metropolitan areas. The contest required consumers to match left
halves of a pictured van contained in specially marked packages of
Kraft Singles cheese with right halves appearing in coupons in
Sunday newspaper advertisements.
   Bernstein wasn't the only one balking at the deal.
   ``I look at it this way,'' said Sharon LaMont, who also had
matched game pieces for a van. ``If they had cheese on sale for
$1.39 and I offered to buy it for 14 cents, do you think they'd let
me have it?''
   The Skokie resident joined one of the class-action lawsuits.
   ``We have five secretaries just taking the calls,'' said attorney
Burton Weinstein, who filed a lawsuit. He said his firm is
representing at least 300 people.
   Diana Redmond, a Rockford resident who hasn't decided whether to
join the lawsuit, said a drawing that included everyone who matched
game pieces for the van wouldn't be fair.
   ``I'm one of the people who followed instructions specifically
and put the entry in the mail on Monday. I feel I should have a
little better chance.
   ``Instead,'' she said, ``they're giving a lot of
Johnny-come-latelies ... the people who started scrounging through
their garbage after they read about this, the same chance as me to
win.''
   In separate negotiations with Illinois and Texas officials, Kraft
entered into voluntary compliance agreements that, in effect, free
the company from charges of violating consumer laws in its ``Ready
to Roll'' game. Under the agreements, Kraft is voluntarily offering
the extra contest payments and holding the alternative drawing.
   Investigators ``have found no ground to suggest that there was
any effort to deceive or otherwise violate any consumer protection
law,'' said Illinois Attorney General Neil Hartigan.
   Kraft said virtually every package of cheese contained a game
piece that matched the pieces found in Sunday newspaper inserts.
   After hundreds of people called Sunday night to claim they'd won
the grand prize, Kraft declared the contest null and void. The
company also pulled packages of the cheese slices from grocery store
shelves.
   Kraft spokesman Mike Caruso said the company's attorneys believe
it's not liable for the prizes because ``of the nature of the
mistake. It was appropriately revoked.''
   In addition to the van, Kraft had planned to award 100 bicycles,
500 skateboards and 8,000 packages of cheese.
   The company said in addition to the $250 cash prizes for those
who matched game pieces for the van, it would award $50 to bicycle
winners, $25 to skateboard winners and $5 to cheese winners. The
drawing for the vans was set for July 14.
   Only one winner will be allowed per household. The deadline for
submitting winning entries is midnight Friday.
</TEXT>
