<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     06-16 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0356</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock market trading got off to a powerful start
today and share prices were mixed.
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange surged to 107.85 million
shares in the first 30 minutes of trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 6.16 to 2,481.16
by 10 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Declining issues outpaced advances on the Big Board, with 561
down, 359 up and 499 unchanged. The NYSE composite index of all its
listed common stocks was unchanged at 178.97.
   Investment analysts attributed the unusually heavy trading volume
on Wall Street to manuevers associated with the expiration of
stock-index futures, index options and options on individual stocks.
This ``triple witching hour'' takes place once a quarter.
   The June contract on Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index ceased
trading on Thursday and settled based on today's opening stock
market prices. The S&amp;P 500-stock index futures is the most heavily
traded contract of its kind.
   Reports on inflation and the housing industry went largely
ignored in the early crush of business.
   The Labor Department said the Consumer Price Index rose a sharp
0.6 percent in May, pushed up by strong increases in food and
gasoline costs. Last month's rise, close to analysts' estimates,
followed a 0.7 percent April increase.
   Meanwhile, the Commerce Department said housing construction
continued to decline in May and starts on new homes fell 2.1 percent
from the previous month to the lowest level since the last recession
in 1982.
   In the early going, Eastman Kodak rose \ to 49. The company said
it is consolidating some operations which could cause the
elimination of some jobs.
   Exxon led the list of actively trading NYSE issues, rising [ to
43~.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average tumbled 28.36 to
2,475.00.
   The NYSE's composite index fell 1.86 to 178.97.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances on the NYSE, with 1,078
down, 444 up and 466 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 179.48 million shares, against 170.54
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
