<HEAD>Crop Futures Gain On Weather Outlook</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were slightly higher in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting
growing confidence among traders that the Midwestern weather is due
for a change.
   Forecasters continued to predict hot, dry conditions in the Corn
Belt by late next week, and some traders were even beginning to take
a bullish view of the dampness that has prevailed in the region this
week.
   ``Crop development is being impeded by this cold, wet weather,''
said Gerald Zusel, manager of Board of Trade floor operations for
Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   Temperatures dropped so low Thursday that some frost damage to
corn was reported in northern Iowa and southern Minnesota, but crop
losses were not extensive.
   The advancing winter wheat harvest kept a lid on early gains in
the wheat market.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.95} a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
to 2{ cents higher with July at $2.61} a bushel; oats were 1\ cents
to 1{ cents higher wiith July at $1.67} a bushel; soybeans were 3{
cents to 6 cents higher with July at $7.37{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .40 cent higher with June at 71.82
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .18 ent higher
with August at 81.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .18 cent to .50
cent higher with June at 48.15 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .35 cent to .53 cent higher with July at 34.65 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Thursday.
</TEXT>
