<FIRST>r f PM-RadiationExposure     06-16 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Radiation Exposure,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Records Indicate Rockwell Workers Overexposed To Radiation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of workers at two Rockwell
International facilities in Southern California were exposed to
excessive levels of radiation in the 1960s, federal documents show.
   No overexposures were shown for subsequent years.
   The documents, released Thursday by the Department of Energy
under the Freedom of Information Act, exclude two overexposure
incidents Rockwell officials have confirmed took place in the 1970s
and '80s.
   Also omitted from the records were the settlements Rockwell paid
recently in at least three workers compensation cases involving
cancer deaths allegedly caused by radiation exposure. Rockwell
didn't admit liability when it paid the settlements in 1987-88.
   The released documents are called unusual occurrence reports. The
Energy Department requires contractors such as Rockwell to file such
reports after safety or equipment problems.
   ``We fully recognize we have a very serious responsibility to the
public, and that's why we monitor our activities so closely,'' said
Pat Coulter, spokesman for Rockwell's Rocketdyne division. ``That's
why when there is a deviance, we record it and make sure it doesn't
happen again.''
   Most of the unusual occurrence reports described minor equipment
malfunctions that apparently didn't involve worker or environmental
safety.
   The two facilities, one in the Canoga Park area and the other the
company's Santa Susana Field Laboratory in the hills bordering Los
Angeles and Ventura counties, have worked for more than 30 years for
the energy and weapons programs of the Energy Department and its
predecessor, the Atomic Energy Commission.
   Workers during several episodes between 1960 and 1967 were
exposed to higher-than-acceptable limits of rems per year at the two
plants, according to the documents. Allowable limits, measured by
film badges worn by workers, are three rems per calendar quarter or
five rems per year.
   A report, for example, on a 1961 incident shows that an employee
was assigned to work in a nuclear reactor room although his
quarterly exposure was already near the 3 rem limit, prompting his
dose to rise to 3.455 rem.
   Five rems is equivalent to between 100 to 200 chest X-rays or
about 50 times the natural background radiation from the sun, rocks
and soil.
   Experts say five rems isn't considered a high radiation dose, but
warned a worker exposed to that level for 30 years has up to three
extra chances in 100 of dying of cancer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
