<FIRST>r f PM-HealthInsurance 1stLd-Writethru f0032 06-16 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Health Insurance, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0032,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polls: Doctors, Public Favor Mandatory Health Insurance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT quote, costs tripled over eight years
sted three. ADDS 1 graf with background on American Medical News. Also
on general news wires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most employers should be required to provide
health insurance, according to polls of doctors and the public, but
a manufacturing group is worried about the cost.
   ``The cost of health care for American business has tripled over
the past eight years,'' said Laura Brown, a spokeswoman for the
National Association of Manufacturers. ``We haven't seen parallel
improvements in quality.''
   Mandated coverage, she said, would only worsen an ``enormous''
financial drain on revenues that could otherwise go for capital
improvements, worker training and industrial technology.
   A poll, published in today's issue of American Medical News, said
that 57 percent of the public and 34 percent of doctors questioned
believed all employers should be required to provide
health-insurance coverage.
   An additional 22 percent of the public and 36 percent of the
physicians surveyed believed that coverage should be required in
most cases, but that small businesses and part-time employees should
be exempt.
   Only 19 percent of the public and 27 percent of the physicians
said the government should not mandate coverage; 3 percent in both
surveys were undecided, the report said.
   The Gallup Organization conducted the polls for the American
Medical Association, whose House of Delegates meets here for its
annual policy meeting next week.
   The polls did not specify whether employers would pay the full
cost.
   More than 35 million Americans lack health insurance, according
to some estimates, and AMA trustees in March said the government
should require that all employers gradually provide health insurance
for full-time employees.
   A bill sponsored by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass. to mandate
coverage for employees who work more than 17{ hours a week and their
dependents is before a Senate committee. The bill applies to all
businesses, but contains a clause under which small companies could
get government subsidies.
   Gallup questioned 1,500 randomly selected U.S. adults via
telephone during late January and early February, with a sampling
error estimated at 2.5 percentage points.
   For the doctors' poll, Gallup queried 1,004 U.S. physicians from
the AMA's list in late January and early February. The margin of
error is calculated at 3.5 percentage points.
   American Medical News is the weekly newspaper of the
Chicago-based American Medical Association.
</TEXT>
