<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0354</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed late this morning and
the pace of activity eased after a powerful trading surge in the
early going.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 4.29 to 2,479.29 by
noon on Wall Street.
   Declining issues outpaced advances on the New York Stock
Exchange, with 656 down, 570 up and 571 unchanged. The NYSE
composite index of all its listed common stocks was up 0.07 to
179.04.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 155.33 million shares at midday,
up from 84.31 million shares at the same point in the previous
session.
   Stock trading got off to a brisk start before settling down; more
than 107 million shares changed hands in the first half hour of
trading.
   Investment analysts attributed the unusually heavy trading volume
on Wall Street to manuevers associated with the expiration of
stock-index futures, index options and options on individual stocks.
This occurence commonly called the ``triple witching hour'' takes
place once a quarter.
   Reports on inflation and the housing industry had little impact
on stocks.
   The Labor Department said the Consumer Price Index rose a sharp
0.6 percent in May, pushed up by strong increases in food and
gasoline costs. Last month's rise, close to analysts' estimates,
followed a 0.7 percent April increase.
   In a separate report, the Commerce Department said housing
construction continued to decline in May and starts on new homes
fell 2.1 percent from the previous month to the lowest level since
the last recession in 1982.
   Warner Communications led the list of actively trading NYSE
issues, climbing 3] to 59 on volume of more than 3.9 million shares.
   Time today launched a $70 a share tender offer for Warner and
rejected a $10.7 billion buyout bid from Paramount Communications.
   Time stock fell 5 to 166{ and Paramount was off | at 58~.
   Eastman Kodak rose \ to 49. The company said it is consolidating
some operations which could cause the elimination of some jobs.
