<HEAD>Pan Am, Davis, Union In; MEI Out In Northwest Bidding</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `A group... to UPDATE with no comment from
Checchi; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Northwest stock...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<HEAD>AP Business Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. submitted a revised bid for
Northwest Airlines today that includes an additional $200 million in
equity while oil billionaire Marvin Davis said he has revised his
offer for the carrier for the last time.
   Northwest's machinists' union also met today's deadline for
revised offers, the union's president said, but previous bidder MEI
Diversified of Minneapolis said it would not make a new offer.
   Northwest parent NWA Inc. had set today as a deadline for revised
offers after rejecting all offers in the first round of bidding.
   A group led by Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi is the only
other suitor known to have met the initial deadline. Checchi said
today he would not comment on whether the group would submit a new
offer. KLM Royal Dutch Airlines is an equity partner in the Checchi
group.
   Northwest stock rose 12{ cents to $107.62{ a share today in
mid-morning trading on the New York Stock Exchange. Analysts have
said the winning bid could be as high as $120 a share, but the
company repeatedly has said it may not sell the airline.
   Pan Am Chairman Thomas Plaskett said his revised bid for the
nation's fourth-largest airline includes $200 million in equity from
Corporate Partners, an investment fund organized by Lazard Freres &amp;
Co. and managed by Lester Pollack and Ali E. Wambold. That brings
the total amount of equity in the Pan Am proposal to $600 million,
Plaskett said.
   No other details were disclosed, but Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela
Hanlon said the bid still includes bank financing and subordinated
debt placed with private institutions. The earlier Pan Am bid
included $2.7 billion in bank financing.
   ``This new equity has allowed us to make a proposal that is
vigorously competitive and attractive to NWA's shareholders,
employees and others who have a strong stake in Northwest's
long-term future,'' Plaskett said.
   Plaskett said Pan Am met with First Boston, Northwest's financial
adviser, before revising its proposal. He said he believes the new
offer ``addresses the concerns'' NWA had about the original Pan Am
bid. NWA appointed a special committee to review the offers.
   A spokesman for Davis, who opened the bidding for Northwest on
March 28 with an offer of $2.7 billion, or $90 a share, said the oil
mogul has submitted a ``new and very full'' offer.
   ``It's one which he and his advisers believe provides the
greatest value to shareholders while at the same time ensuring that
the company is not overly leveraged,'' the spokesman said. ``This is
Mr. Davis' final bid for the company.''
   Guy Cook, president of the International Association of
Machinists District Lodge 143, said the union has submitted a
revised bid, but he did not disclose details. The machinists' union
accounts for about 20,000 of Northwest's 35,000 employees.
   MEI Diversified, led by Minneapolis banker Carl Pohlad, issued a
statement saying it would not revise its offer. The group includes
Minneapolis financier Irwin Jacobs.
   Two other rumored bidders for NWA _ the New York takeover firms
of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. and Forstman, Little &amp; Co. _ have
declined comment.
   The four-member committee of the NWA board announced June 5 that
it had rejected all the first-round bids and asked for ``enhanced''
revisions. It has not identified bids or bidders, but it said it
would favor a high price, a low level of debt and an ability to
complete a deal quickly.
   Analysts expect the special committee to make a decision on the
revised bids next week. The company asked bidders to keep their
offers open through June 30.
</TEXT>
