<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Inflation     06-16 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Inflation,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual Rate Rises to 8.3 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's annualized inflation rate rose to 8.3
percent in May from 8 percent in April, the government said Friday.
   The latest rate was lower than financial markets had expected but
was higher than the peak of 8 percent that Chancellor of the
Exchequer Nigel Lawson had forecast in March.
   The Department of Employment said its retail price index rose 0.6
percent in May from the previous month.
   The index stood at 115 in May, compared with 114.3 in April and
106.2 in May 1988. The index uses a January 1987 base of 100.
   Market forecasts called for an 8.4-percent annual rate and a 0.7
percent monthly rise.
   Employment Secretary Norman Fowler said that if mortgage interest
payments were excluded the rate of inflation would have been 6
percent in May.
   He said inflation ``is likely to fall back later in the year as a
result of policies already in hand.''
   ``There is continuing evidence that the action taken by the
chancellor is beginning to work,'' Fowler said, pointing to a recent
slowdown in retail sales and consumer borrowing growth as well as
moderation in the rate of increase of producer prices.
   The government has pushed up interest rates 10 times in the last
year to 14 percent from 7.5 percent in an effort to fight resurgent
inflation.
   The annual inflation rate in May 1988 was 4.2 percent.
</TEXT>
