<FIRST>r f BC-GENegotiations     06-16 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-GE Negotiations,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Electric Reaches Tentative Agreement With Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Corp. reached a tentative
agreement Friday with 700 union workers, averting a threatened
strike at three plants, a company official said.
   Details of the three-year agreement with members of Local 241 of
the International Federation of Professional and Technical Engineers
were not released.
   The workers are employed at GE plants in Camden, Moorestown and
Gibbsboro in southern New Jersey.
   Don Norton, a company spokesman in Valley Forge, Pa., said union
members are to vote Sunday on the agreement.
   Union president Frank Ward had said the union was seeking an 18
percent increase over three years.
   Last Sunday, about 500 union members overwhelmingly rejected
management's latest offer, which included a 2 percent salary
increase over three years and cash incentive bonuses worth $1,200,
officials said.
   The current contract expired at 12:01 a.m. Friday and union
members had planned to strike, Ward said.
   The union represents technical engineers, laboratory personnel,
writers and illustrators. The average salary is about $25,000, Ward
said.
</TEXT>
