<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices move higher Friday after a rebound in
the value of the British pound.
   Traders also were relieved that British inflation was in line
with expectations at 8.3 percent in May.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 14.3
points, or 0.7 percent, higher at 2,143.9, its peak for the day. The
day's low came at the opening, when the index was down 5.5 points.
   Volume was 513.8 million shares, compared with 593.4 million
Thursday.
   Some selective buying at the outset of a new two-week trading
account also helped boost prices late in the day. London's stock
exchange divides trading into two-week and three-week trading
periods for accounting purposes.
   The pounds's performance against the dollar was the major source
of encouragement for the market, which has been plagued recently by
worries that British interest rates might be pushed higher to
bolster the pound.
   The pound was quoted late in the day at $1.5340 up from $1.5195
late Thursday.
</TEXT>
