<FIRST>r f AM-HomeShopping-GTE     06-16 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Shopping-GTE,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home Shopping Network, GTE Head to Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civil trial is to begin Monday on Home
Shopping Network's $1.5 billion lawsuit alleging that faulty GTE
Corp. equipment kept thousands of customers on hold waiting for idle
sales operators.
   The trial in Pinellas Circuit Court also includes Stamford,
Conn.-based GTE's countering slander suit against the video
retailer. The case is expected to last six weeks.
   Home Shopping Network sued GTE; a subsidiary; and GTE Florida,
the local telephone company in 1987 alleging fraud linked to
telephone equipment. The St. Petersburg-based video retailer is
seeking $500 million in damages and $1 billion in punitive damages.
   The newtork claims it lost $500 million in revenue because GTE
telephone equipment kept thousands of customers waiting for sales
operators who weren't busy.
   The GTE companies have denied wrongdoing and sued alleging
slander and libel. They claim Home Shopping is blaming the
telecommunications companies for its own managerial problems.
   The 12 counts in the original Home Shopping complaint have been
reduced to four _ fraud, negligent misrepresentation, breach of
trust and confidence, and breach of fiduciary duty.
   Home Shopping maintains that GTE employees lied to the cable
television retailer and installed malfunctioning equipment and later
covered up the problems.
</TEXT>
