   The stock market remained mixed this afternoon as
traders awaited an expected surge in activity later today due to the
expiration of various futures and options.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 1.49 to 2,476.49
at 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Declining issues outpaced advances on the New York Stock
Exchange, with 731 down, 617 up and 553 unchanged. The NYSE
composite index of all its listed common stocks was up 0.11 to
178.86.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 184.22 million shares with two
hours left to go, exceeding Thursday's full-day volume of 179.48
million shares.
   Stock trading got off to a brisk start before settling down; more
than 107 million shares changed hands in the first half hour of
trading.
   Another surge in volume is expected to take place as the market
closes.
   Investment analysts attributed the unusually heavy volume on Wall
Street to manuevers associated with the expiration of stock-index
futures, index options and options on individual stocks. This
occurence commonly called the ``triple witching hour'' takes place
once a quarter.
   Reports on inflation and the housing industry had little impact
on stocks.
   The Labor Department said the Consumer Price Index rose a sharp
0.6 percent in May, pushed up by strong increases in food and
gasoline costs. Last month's rise, close to analysts' estimates,
followed a 0.7 percent April increase.
   In a separate report, the Commerce Department said housing
construction continued to decline in May and starts on new homes
fell 2.1 percent from the previous month to the lowest level since
the last recession in 1982.
   Warner Communications led the list of actively trading NYSE
issues, climbing 3 to 58| on volume of more than 5.7 million shares.
   Time today said it was launching a $70 a share tender offer for
Warner and rejected a $10.7 billion buyout bid from Paramount
Communications.
