<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Goldome     06-16 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Goldome,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Goldome Drops Employee Secrecy Order, Announces Layoff Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goldome bank on Friday rescinded its
controversial policy of threatening to cut the severance pay of
laid-off workers unless they signed an agreement not to talk about
losing their jobs.
   ``Our intention, to help assure the confidentiality of employee,
customer and corporate information ... has been submerged by
misperceptions of the agreement. This makes its continued use
counterproductive,'' Thomas Cooper, the chief executive, said in a
statement.
   Cooper said Goldome wants to cut staffing levels by 20 percent,
or about 980 jobs nationwide. He said the company has already
completed more than half of the job cuts, either through layoffs,
attrition or the sale of business units.
   Goldome, one of the nation's largest thrifts, has lost $167
million in it last six quarters. Sources within the company said
Cooper wanted to keep the layoffs secret so customers would not lose
confidence and withdraw their money.
   As many as 150 people had been terminated in the last 10 days and
asked to sign the agreement, which prevented them from suing Goldome
or discussing their layoff with anyone except ``counsel, personal
tax adviser, immediate family or as required by law.''
   If laid-off employees refused to sign, their severance benefits
would have been cut to two weeks pay, down from a maximum of six.
   Nearly all of Goldome's laid-off workers signed the agreement
because they could not afford to lose the money, sources said.
   Goldome, based in Buffalo, employs 4,900 nationwide and has
operations in two dozen states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
