<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-16 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Advance; Wheat Ends Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices posted strong
gains Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, boosted by forecasts for
warm, dry weather in the Midwest next week. Wheat futures closed
mixed.
   Meteorologists are continuing to call for a change to warmer and
drier-than-normal conditions in the Corn Belt by late next week,
stirring memories of last year's drought.
   Corn futures also were supported by expectations that the
Agriculture Department will extend certain corn loans to farmers
that would keep some corn in storage that otherwise would move onto
the market.
   The dollar's weakness was another bullish factor, since a weaker
dollar could encourage foreign purchases of U.S. grain.
   ``The soybean complex has been trading with a kind of a wary eye
on that dollar situation,'' said Dale Gustafson, a grain-market
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Improving harvest weather in the Great Plains kept pressure on
wheat prices.
   At the close, wheat was \ cent lower to 3\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.94 a bushel; corn was \ cent to
4\ cents higher with July at $2.63{ a bushel; oats were unchanged to
1{ cents lower with July at $1.65 a bushel; soybeans were unchanged
to 9{ cents higher with July at $7.34 a bushel.
</TEXT>
