<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Maintenance     06-16 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Maintenance,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney Accuses FAA of Shirking on New York Airport Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney representing a fired Eastern Airlines
manager said Friday the Federal Aviation Administration has been lax
in taking action against falsification of records that led to fuel
contamination at New York's LaGuardia Airport.
   Ira J. Furman, an attorney in Woodmere, N.Y., said he represents
a former Eastern maintenance manager at LaGuardia who has talked to
the FAA, the FBI and the U.S. Attorney's Office about alleged
violations that occurred at least a year ago.
   The former manager, whose was not identified, has said he
initialed documents saying tests were made on jets parked overnight
at LaGuardia when no tests actually were made, Furman said. The
tests are to ensure the plane's fuel does not have too much water in
it. Excess water can damage an engine or cause engine failure.
   ``This is like a whitewash,'' Furman said. ``The FAA should have
shut down operations at LaGuardia.''
   ``It has taken a while for us to look into this case,'' said
Kathleen Bergen, a spokeswoman in FAA's Eastern District office.
However, she said the delay was ``in the interest of thoroughness.''
   Furman, a deputy director of the National Transportation Safety
Board until 1987, said his client was granted immunity in the case
last September.
   Eastern's maintenance and safety operations have come under
increased scrutiny since the walkout of its Machinists union on
March 4, with regulators trying to determine whether the strike has
led to unsafe practices in Eastern's maintenance.
   Early last month, Eastern surrendered its repair station
certificate at New York's John F. Kennedy International Airport
after the FAA determined the carrier failed to properly record and
inspect maintenance work.
   The suspension of the JFK certificate was for actions that
predated the start of the Machinists strike that was joined by
pilots and flight attendants. The walkout virtually grounded
Miami-based Eastern and pushed it into bankruptcy court
reorganization.
   On May 12, the FAA completed a special investigation of
record-keeping at Eastern's maintenance posts in Miami and Atlanta
to determine if violations of record-keeping rules such as those
found at Kennedy were widespread.
   The final report hasn't been submitted to acting FAA
Administrator Robert E. Whittington. But Jack Barker, an FAA
spokesman in Atlanta, said Monday the agency told Eastern informally
that the inspection had revealed no irregularities.
   The former manager at LaGuardia asserted that Eastern's
maintenance department there didn't even have the necessary tools to
conduct the fuel tests and said he sometimes signed documents using
made-up initials for nonexistent managers, Furman said.
   Jim Ashlock, a spokesman for Eastern at its Miami headquarters,
said there are no indications that aircraft safety was compromised
at LaGuardia. He said the airline has cooperated with the FAA in
examining all available records relevant to the manager's
accusations.
   The former Eastern manager said he became concerned after a
superior told him they would not hire a lawyer for him if an
accident occurred as a result of the non-testing. He refused to
falsify any more documents, Furman said. Two weeks later the manager
was fired on what he says are false charges that he smoked marijuana
on the job, Furman said.
   The manager alerted the FAA and the Justice Department about the
allegations in 1987 after losing an arbitration case over his
firing, and has given the FAA tape recordings and written documents,
Furman said.
   The manager ``has put himself on the line,'' the attorney said.
``The FAA had it laid out on a silver platter for them.''
   The FAA's inaction ``calls into question the effectiveness of the
FAA in rooting out problems at Eastern,'' Furman said.
   Since 1983 176 accidents, resulting in 45 deaths, were caused by
excess water in fuel, according to the National Transportation
Safety Board. None involved jets or major commercial carriers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
