<FIRST>u f AM-Robins Bjt   06-16 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robins, Bjt,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Approves $2.5 Billion for Dalkon Shield Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Guerry in 3rd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court Friday approved the
bankruptcy reorganization of A.H. Robins Co., including $2.5 billion
for women who claim they were injured by the company's Dalkon Shield
birth control device sold widely in the 1970s.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld all parts of the
long-awaited restructuring of Robins, which will become a subsidiary
of New York-based American Home Products Corp. in a $700 million
stock swap.
   ``I think it's just tremendous news for all Dalkon Shield
claimants,'' said Guerry Thornton, attorney for the Dalkon Shield
Victims Association in Atlanta. ``It means the decade wait for fair
treatment and vindication of their rights is almost over.''
   Robins, a Richmond-based pharmaceutical manufacturer, sought
Chapter 11 federal bankruptcy protection from creditors in August
1985.
   The company faced millions of dollars in damage claims from women
who said they suffered injuries including infections, sterility,
miscarriage and having children born with birth defects caused by
the Dalkon Shield intrauterine device.
   Robins distributed about 4.5 million Dalkon Shields in the United
States and abroad before taking the device off the market in 1974.
Robins paid about $520 million to settle 9,400 of some 15,000 Dalkon
Shield lawsuits before seeking bankruptcy protection.
   Alan B. Morrison, attorney for the Public Citizen Litigation
Group in Washington, D.C., lead lawyer for opponents of the
reorganization plan, said no decision had been made whether to
appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.
   In a series of four unanimous opinions, a three-judge panel of
the appeals court upheld the entire scope of Robins' reorganization.
   In addition to a $2.5 billion settlement trust fund for about
200,000 Dalkon Shield claimants, the reorganization includes full
payment to Robins' other creditors.
   The restructuring was designed over three years and approved in
July 1988 by U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr. and U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Blackwell N. Shelley, who presided jointly in the
case.
   The ruling includes approval of a one claimant-one vote plan by
which 95 percent of Dalkon Shield claimants ratified the settlement,
and a separate cash settlement by Robins' insurance company.
   Lawyers for a group of claimants who opposed the plan contended
that ratification vote Dalkon Shield users was flawed. They argued
before the appeals court in December that women with larger claims
should have had a greater voice in deciding the issue.
   The reorganization plan also bars claimants from filing
third-party lawsuits to seek damages from Robins' officers or its
insurer, another aspect opposed by some claimants.
   Aetna Casualty &amp; Surety Co., Robins' insurer, paid $425 million
to the trust to settle any claims against it. The claimants
contended Aetna was an active participant in marketing the Dalkon
Shield and should have been liable for claims beyond those covered
by the $2.5 billion trust.
   But the three-member appeals court panel rejected the argument,
citing the likelihood of conflicting decisions on liability if Aetna
had to face trial in different courts on essentially the same
question.
   The court also ruled that while the one claimant-one vote method
of approving the reorganization denied weighted voting, ``at most,
harmless error was committed'' because almost 95 percent of
claimants endorsed the plan.
   Based on expert testimony, $2.5 billion was the estimated cost of
full compensation for all Dalkon Shield claimants, Robins attorney
James C. Roberts said.
   Only $100 million of the $2.5 billion compensation package to
Dalkon Shield claimants has been available during the appeal.
   Michael Sheppard, director of the trust fund's claims resolution
facility, said $52 million of the initial $100 million already has
been paid to 77,662 claimants.
   Also at issue on appeal was whether Judge Merhige interfered with
the five-member trustee board handling the claimants' compensation
fund.
   Last November, Merhige removed three of the trustees because of
slow progress in setting up a procedure for resolving initial
claims. The appeals court on Friday upheld the judge's action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1705EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Robins-Chronology     06-16 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Robins-Chronology,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Robins Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of the main events in the history of the
Dalkon Shield birth control device and its distributor, A.H. Robins
Co.
   June 1970 _ Robins buys the rights to make and sell the Dalkon
Shield.
   January 1971 _ Robins begins national distribution of the
intrauterine device.
   June 1971 _ A physician tells the company that his wife developed
a pelvic infection requiring a hysterectomy after wearing the IUD.
   June 1972 _ Robins receives three reports of septic spontaneous
abortions.
   May 1974 _ Robins sends a letter to doctors nationwide to notify
them of abortions and four deaths among Dalkon Shield wearers.
   June 1974 _ Robins suspends sales of the IUD in the United States.
   January 1975 _ The first verdict in a Dalkon Shield lawsuit is
returned against Robins.
   June 1975 _ Robins suspends sales of the IUD abroad.
   October 1984 _ Robins launches a campaign telling women it will
pay for removal of the device.
   July 1985 _ U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr. in Richmond
turns down a request by Robins to certify a class action on punitive
damages in Dalkon Shield cases.
   Aug. 21, 1985 _ Robins files for Chapter 11 protection from
creditors under federal bankruptcy law.
   September 1985 _ The Internal Revenue Service makes a surprise
$61 million claim against Robins for back taxes and interest.
   January 1986 _ Robins begins a $4 million campaign to tell people
worldwide how to file claims.
   March 1986 _ The U.S. attorney's office, citing payments by
Robins of some pre-bankruptcy debts, asks for the appointment of a
trustee to take over management of the company during reorganization.
   April 1986 _ More than 300,000 claims are received by the filing
deadline.
   June 1986 _ Merhige finds Robins in contempt for paying
pre-bankruptcy debts illegally but decides to appoint an examiner to
oversee the company rather than bring in a trustee to manage it.
   February 1987 _ The American Home Products Corp. offers to buy
Robins and pay $1.75 billion to Dalkon Shield claimants and $22.50
per share to stockholders. The offer is withdrawn a week later.
   March 1987 _ The Rorer Group Inc. matches the AHP offer but
withdraws it in a few days when negotiations are not concluded.
   April 1987 _ Robins formally offers $1.75 billion to Dalkon
Shield claimants.
   June 1987 _ Rorer make a second offer to buy Robins, keeping the
$1.75 billion compensation figure but raising the per-share offer to
$30.
   November 1987 _ Robins and Rorer sign a definitive merger
agreement as Merhige opens hearings to determine the value of Dalkon
Shield injury claims against Robins.
   December 1987 _ Merhige sets $2.5 billion as the compensation
required for Dalkon Shield claimants, and a French company, Sanofi
SA, competes with Rorer to acquire Robins.
   January 1988 _ Robins announces plans to be acquired by AHP after
three-way discussions that also involved Rorer and Sanofi.
   March 1988 _ Robins and AHP announce a definitive merger
agreement to exchange $700 million in stock and provide $2.5 billion
in compensation to Dalkon Shield victims.
   April 1988 _ Five trustees are appointed to oversee the Dalkon
Shield claimants fund. Rorer seeks $34 million in compensation for
the breakup of its merger deal with Robins.
   July 1988 _ Merhige confirms the Robins reorganization plan,
including a $2.5 billion trust fund to compensate Dalkon Shield
victims and acquisition of Robins by AHP. About 95 percent of
claimants ratify the plan.
   December 1988 _ The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals hears
arguments in the appeal of the Robins reorganization.
   June 16, 1989 _ A three-judge appeals court panel upholds the
reorganization package.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
