<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-16 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Bernd in 4th graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rally in the dollar fizzled Friday one day
after a sharp sell-off, leaving it higher against the British pound,
Canadian dollar and Swiss franc but lower against other major
currencies.
   The dollar rose from late Thursday levels in Asian and early
European trading despite central banks' dollar sales, but it failed
to hold ground after a U.S. report showed inflation in May at the
high end of expectations.
   Thursday's panicky selling appeared to have altered the bullish
psychology that had carried the dollar to its highest levels since
1987 or late 1986 against some currencies, traders said.
   ``The same inflation number last week would have pushed the
dollar definitely higher,'' said Bernd Becker, chief trader for
Oesterreichische Laenderbank in New York.
   The Commerce Department said the Consumer Price Index rose 0.6
percent in May. High inflation increases the chance the Federal
Reserve will keep interest rates high to keep the economy from
overheating.
   Higher rates attract global money into dollars. But nervous
speculators used the report as an opportunity to sell.
   Also pushing down the dollar, Becker said, was a report out of
Japan quoting sources saying the central banks of Japan and West
Germany had agreed to intervene jointly to hold down the dollar
outside their home markets.
   ``I think the market really got shaken by what happened,'' Becker
said, referring to Thursday's session, in which the dollar lost 2.5
percent or more of its value against the pound, West German mark and
Japanese yen.
   ``Billions of dollars were bought at top levels when it looked
like it was a one-way street up. Now speculators are going to use
any higher levels to sell,'' he said.
   Dealers said trading was erratic, with the dollar's movement
exaggerated by thin volume. Many market players chose to stay on the
sidelines after being burned by Thursday's sharp swings.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5340 to buy one pound, more than $1.5195 late Thursday. In New
York the pound fell to $1.5410 from $1.5510 late Thursday in New
York.
   The dollar fell 6.25 yen to a closing 145.05 yen in Tokyo. Later,
in London, it was quoted at 145.50 yen. In New York the dollar fell
to 144.70 yen from 145.40 on Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.9810 West German marks, down from
1.9845; 1.7110 Swiss francs, up from 1.7095; 1.1973 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1966; 6.7290 French francs, down from 6.7390; and
1,441 Italian lire, down from 1,443.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday:
1.9915 West German marks, down from 2.0235; 1.7213 Swiss francs,
down from 1.7490; 6.7620 French francs, down from 6.8680; 2.2385
Dutch guilders, down from 2.2915; 1,443.50 Italian lire, down from
1,472.00; 1.1973 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1993.
   Gold prices rose overseas, catching up with gains made Thursday
in the United States. But they fell in U.S. trading.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $5.10 a troy ounce to close at a bid
$366.67. Gold rose in London to a late bid of $363.75 from
Thursday's $362.50. In Zurich, gold rose to a bid $363.75 from
$361.71 late Thursday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $365.10 an ounce from $367 on Thursday. Later,
Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $364 as of 4
p.m. EDT, down from $366.80 late Thursday.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.27 a troy ounce, compared with
Thursday's $5.29. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery fell to $5.285 an ounce from $5.309 Thursday.
</TEXT>
