<FIRST>u f AM-Kodak Bjt   06-16 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kodak, Bjt,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Consolidates Divisions, To Cut Hundreds of Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. said Friday it will
consolidate its consumer photography products and picture finishing
operations, cutting costs and hundreds of jobs.
   Four operations will be merged in the newly created Consumer
Imagery Division, said company spokesman Paul Allen.
   Kodak said the move would strengthen its consumer photography
business, part of the firm's imaging segment, which made a dismal
showing when Kodak's first-quarter earnings were announced in May.
   By year's end, the new division will include the consumer
products, photofinishing and United States sales divisions, he said.
It also will include the administrative service area within the
photo products group, said Allen.
   ``If you look at the stock over the last couple of weeks, there
has been a lot of speculation after the first-quarter earnings
release... that there could be a major restructuring or a hostile
takeover or spinoff,'' said Alex Henderson, an analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   ``I am very strongly of the opinion that those basic rumors that
got the stock to rally ... are unfounded.''
   Kodak stock fell 12{ cents Friday to $48.62{ in consolidated New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   Kodak profits were down 23 percent in the first quarter and the
company had problems making money selling products overseas, caused
by the increasing strength of the U.S. dollar overseas and foreign
competition. Kodak has also had to absorb costs from last year's
purchase of Sterling Drug Co.
   In the imaging segment, operating earnings fell from $201 million
in last year's first quarter to $160 million the same period this
year.
   Kodak's plan included cutting several hundred jobs from the work
force, but the exact number would not be determined until summer's
end, said Allen.
   The job cuts would occur in support areas and would be primarily
confined to the company's Rochester headquarters, said Allen.
   ``There will be no major impact in the field among our sales
force or at our manufacturing facilities,'' Allen said.
   Kodak Vice Chairman J. Phillip Samper said the company ``will
view consumer photography as single business'' driven by the
recognition that ``consumers see photography as a natural sequence
involving cameras, films and photofinishing.''
   Separately, Xerox Corp. announced in Rochester that 680 employees
nationwide have been accepted in a voluntary reduction program that
Xerox announced in March, including 170 in the Rochester area where
Xerox has its largest manufacturing work force.
   While the voluntary reductions won't guarantee against future
layoffs, said spokesman John Rasor, Xerox had originally predicted
that only 250 to 350 would take advantage of the program.
</TEXT>
