<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-16 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Tumble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices fell sharply Friday as
the market relaxed its concerns over supply problems and traders
cashed in gains achieved earlier in the week, analysts said.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, finished 62
cents lower at $19.95 a barrel. The drop retraced most of the 69
cents the contract had gained since last Friday's $19.88 close.
   Other contract months showed smaller declines.
   Among refined products, unleaded gasoline for July delivery
dropped 1.30 cents to 58.14 cents a gallon, while July heating oil
fell 0.55 cent to 45.71 cents a gallon. Other product contracts also
declined.
   Analysts said the market had been overbought in recent days.
   ``You're bound to see profit-taking coming in basically as a
result of it,'' said Nauman Barakat, vice president of energy
investments at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Some observers had attributed the recent rise in July crude oil
to concerns about pipeline distribution problems that resulted in
some customers receiving foreign crude in place of West Texas
Intermediate.
   Although the delivered crude met specifications, customers used
to receiving West Texas Intermediate were concerned about supplies,
analysts said.
   ``The short-term scare is over,'' said James Steel, an analyst
with Refco Inc. ``That led to a relaxation in the market and made
the market go down.''
</TEXT>
