<FIRST>u f AM-HoneywellLayoffs     06-16 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honeywell Layoffs,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honeywell To Cut 300 Corporate Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc. will cut its corporate staff by
300, mostly through layoffs, the defense contractor and building
controls maker said Friday.
   Seventy-five of the jobs will be lost to attrition, while the
balance of the cuts will be made with layoffs and some early
retirements, said Susan Eich, a company spokeswoman.
   The company's stock jumped $1.50 a share Friday to close at
$75.12{ in composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Employees will know by June 26 if they are going to be laid off,
Eich said. The same day, Honeywell will open an office designed to
find new jobs outside the company for the laid-off workers, she said.
   About 200 of the cuts will be made at the company's Minneapolis
headquarters in such departments as human resources, legal,
communications and general office services. Honeywell has about
18,000 employees in the Twin Cities and 78,000 employees worldwide.
The rest of the cuts will be scattered in field offices across the
country, she said.
   The company said it was trimming its workforce to save money.
   In 1988, Honeywell lost $435 million. In the first quarter of
1989 it had earnings of $62.9 million, or $1.36 a share.
   The layoffs announced Friday followed a cut of 1,200 employees
announced in December.
