<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1806EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern     06-16 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Agrees to Sell Philadelphia Assets to Midway Instead of USAir</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines has agreed to sell
its eight Philadelphia airport gates, 16 jets and other assets to
Midway Airlines for $206.5 million, Eastern said Friday.
   The move heads off threatened antitrust action by the Justice
Department to block Eastern's earlier proposed sale of the
Philadelphia gates and two U.S.-Canadian routes to USAir Group Inc.
   Eastern announced the Midway deal at a federal bankruptcy court
hearing over its earlier agreement with Washington-based USAir. U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland gave Eastern permission to
terminate that agreement, but still must approve the sale to
Chicago-based Midway.
   Eastern sought bankruptcy protection from creditors on March 9,
five days after the start of a strike by Machinists that was joined
by pilots and flight attendants.
   The sale of the Philadelphia assets is part of Eastern's plan to
reorganize as a smaller carrier and sell $1.8 billion in assets.
Lifland on Wednesday had approved Eastern's agreement to sell 15
aircraft for $277.5 million to UAS-Invest Inc.
   The unions have opposed the plan, but have been unsuccessful in
finding a buyer for the entire airline.
   On Thursday, William Winpisinger, president of the International
Association of Machinists, said he saw a ``seven-in-10 chance'' that
the bankruptcy court would approve Eastern's downsizing plan.
   Referring to Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent Texas
Air Corp., Winpisinger said, ``It's distinctly possible he can win
and survive.'' Winpisinger made his remarks to the Indiana State
AFL-CIO annual convention in French Lick, Ind.
   A buyout plan for Eastern proposed by the unions and Chicago
commodities trader Joseph Ritchie remains under discussion, but
Lifland has said the first priority should be talks over the
airline's proposed reorganization.
   Midway agreed to purchase Eastern's eight Philadelphia gates, its
routes from Philadelphia to Toronto and Montreal, two landing slots
at New York's LaGuardia Airport, two slots at Washington National
Airport, and 16 McDonnell Douglas DC-9 aircraft.
   Used DC-9 jets generally fetch around $3 million each, industry
experts say.
   Eastern attorney Bruce Zirinsky told Lifland the airline held
negotiations through Thursday night and into Friday morning with
officials of Midway, which previously had expressed interest in
Eastern's Philadelphia assets.
   The Justice Department planned to sue to block the planned $85
million sale to USAir of Eastern's airport gates in Philadelphia and
its Philadelphia-Toronto route. The sale also would have included
Eastern's Philadelphia-Montreal route but the department didn't
object to that element.
   The department contended the sale to USAir threatened to lessen
competition in airline service between Philadelphia and other
cities. USAir already has nearly a third of the flights into and out
of Philadelphia.
   The state of Pennsylvania also challenged the proposed USAir
purchase, saying the transaction could lead to higher ticket prices.
   ``Obviously, we're disappointed in what happened. But the deal is
over. That's it,'' said USAir spokesman John Bronson in Pittsburgh.
   Dan Ashby, a spokesman for the pilots union, said the unions
planned to object in court to the proposed Midway sale.
   ``We believe that Philadelphia is an integral part of the Eastern
system,'' Ashby said. He contended Lorenzo wants to sell Eastern's
assets in that city because they compete with Continental Airlines'
hub in nearby Newark, N.J. Continental, a non-union carrier, is a
Texas Air subsidiary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890616-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-16 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cattle Futures Expected To Rally After Surprising USDA Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Live cattle futures prices posted modest gains Friday on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange and experts predicted a surge next week
after a government report showed an unexpectedly sharp drop in May
placements of cattle on feedlots.
   On other markets, energy prices tumbled; grains and soybeans were
mixed; and precious metals retreated.
   Live cattle settled .13 cent to .30 cent higher with the contract
for delivery in June at 71.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were
unchanged to .18 cent lower with August at 80.97 cents a pound; live
hogs were .05 cent to .60 cent higher with June at 48.22 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .38 cent lower to 1.15 cents higher
witth July at 33.92 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures prices had been rising ahead of the Agriculture
Department's monthly cattle-on-feed report.
   Expectations were that it would show about a 15 percent decline
in the number of cattle placed on feedlots last month in the seven
largest producer states compared with the record-high placements of
May 1988.
   But the USDA indicated an even sharper drop in May placements,
reporting 25 percent fewer cattle were moved from pastures to
feedlots last month than a year ago.
   The seven-state total of 1.6 million cattle was 11 percent below
the 10-year average and represented the lightest May placements
since 1981. The placements brought the total number of cattle on
feed in the seven states to 7.5 million, 3 percent below a year ago.
   There are two major reasons for the lower placements. Last year's
drought dried up pasturelands and forced calf-and-cattle producers
to sell more of their animals to feedlots earlier in the year than
normal, which led to record-high placements in May 1988.
   This year's spring rains had the opposite effect.
   ``The rain improved your pasture conditions and just slowed down
that movement of cattle off of pastures into the feedlots,'' said
Dale Durchholz of Agri-Visor Services Inc. in Bloomington, Ill.
   The low placements will result in tighter supplies of
slaughter-ready cattle in late summer and early fall, and will
likely push cattle and beef prices higher.
   Analysts said the contracts for August and October cattle
deliveries should see the greatest gains on Monday, with prices
expected to open .50 cent to 1 cent higher.
   Petroleum futures prices plummeted on the New York Mercantile
Exchange on signs of easing supplies of crude oil for prompt
delivery and reports that the OPEC cartel may raise its production
ceiling by 1 million barrels per day in September.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 62 cents
lower with July at $19.95 a barrel; heating oil was .21 cent to .63
lower with July at 45.71 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was 1.34
cents lower to .10 cent higher with July at 58.14 cents a gallon.
   Most corn and soybean futures posted strong gains on the Chicago
Board of Trade, boosted by forecasts for a warmup in the Midwest
next week. Wheat futures closed mixed.
   Corn futures also were supported by expectations the Agriculture
Department will extend certain corn loans to farmers, which would
keep in storage some corn that would otherwise move onto the market.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 3\ cents higher with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.94\ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to 3{
cents higher with July at $2.62} a bushel; oats were \ cent to 2
cents lower with July at $1.64{ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower
to 7{ cents higher with July at $7.33 a bushel.
   Gold and silver futures prices fell modesty after rising for four
straight days on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled $1.90 to $2 lower with August at $368.80 a troy
ounce; silver was 0.6 cent to 2.5 cents lower with July at $5.305 a
troy ounce.
</TEXT>
