<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   06-16 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved ahead Friday in the
heaviest trading volume in about five months as buyers braved the
``triple witching hour.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 11.38 to 2,486.38,
but lost 27.04 points from a week earlier.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 9 to 7 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 811 up, 626 down and
544 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 244.51 million
shares, up from 179.48 million in the previous session.
   The unusually heavy volume on Wall Street reflected trades
associated with the expiration of stock-index futures, index options
and options on individual stocks. The set of expirations occur once
each quarter in something commonly called the ``triple witching
hour.''
   Most of the trading was concentrated around the opening and
closing of the session.
   Traders paid little attention to two government economic reports.
   ``I don't think the market moved on economic news today,'' said
Newton D. Zinder, analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., adding
that traders were preoccupied with ``triple witching hour''
strategies.
   The Labor Department said the Consumer Price Index rose 0.6
percent in May, driven up by strong increases in food and gasoline
costs.
   Last month's rise, close to analysts' estimates, followed a 0.7
percent April increase and was taken as a sign that inflation
continues to be a problem for the American economy.
   In a separate report, the Commerce Department said housing
construction continued to decline in May and starts on new homes
fell 2.1 percent from the previous month to the lowest level since
the last recession in 1982.
   Warner Communications dominated the list of actively traded
NYSE-listed stocks on news that Time intends to launch a $70-a-share
tender offer for Warner instead of merging with Warner in a stock
swap.
   More than 8.2 million Warner shares changed hands in
NYSE-composite trading and the stock wound up with a gain of 3| at
59\.
   Time, which also said it has rejected a $175-a-share takeover bid
from Paramount Communications, tumbled 9 to 162{. Paramount pulled
back by 1] to 58[.
   Another media stock, MCA, gained 1\ to 60 in response to a
Business Week magazine report that the company may be a takeover
candidate.
   Eastman Kodak shed [ to 48|. The company said it is consolidating
some operations which would cause hundreds of job cutbacks.
   A.H. Robins rose 3[ to 29~. A federal court approved Robins'
bankruptcy reorganization plan, which includes $2.5 billion for
women who claim they were injured by the company's Dalkon Shield
birth control device sold widely in the 1970s.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 274.12 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market gained $8.297 billion, or 0.26
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.62 to 179.59.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index increased 1.54 to 367.74, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index closed at 321.35, up 1.27.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market edged
up by 0.11 to 447.21. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 361.83, up 0.83.
</TEXT>
