<FIRST>u f AM-RobinsReax     06-16 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robins Reax,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>End of Wait Near for Claimants</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Robins Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Court approval Friday of A.H. Robins Co.'s
reorganization should end more than a decade of waiting for
thousands of women seeking compensation for injuries from the Dalkon
Shield birth control device.
   ``There is some justice in the world,'' said Karen Hightower,
director of the Dalkon Shield Victims' Association in Atlanta and a
claimant. ``This is absolutely wonderful.''
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed A.H. Robins
bankruptcy reorganization plan with $2.5 billion set aside for women
claiming injuries from the intrauterine device sold widely in the
early 1970s.
   The money cannot be distributed until appeals to the plan are
exhausted. About 200,000 claims against the Richmond-based
pharmaceutical manufacturer are outstanding.
   An appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court is possible, but analysts and
attorneys said the high court is unlikely to hear the case because
the appellate court gave an across-the-board ratification.
   Constance Miller of the International Dalkon Shield Victims
Education in Seattle, who opposed the plan, said she believes the
reorganization does not provide adequate compensation.
   ``I feel very disappointed,'' Ms. Miller said. ``We're not being
treated fairly in this whole business.''
   She said the ruling means women who have not yet filed claims or
gotten medical records together need to do so before time runs out.
   Sandy Reina, a claimant who leads a victims' association in Baton
Rouge, La., said the decision is important for women awaiting
payments before they can undergo reproductive surgery or attempt in
vitro fertilization.
   ``A lot of the women here are about to fall apart from wondering
what was going to happen,'' Ms. Reina said. ``I think most of us are
ready to go forward and get this thing over with.''
   Ms. Reina said she had a total hysterectomy after years of pain
from wearing the Dalkon Shield.
   ``For me personally, it's time to let the manufacturers wake up
and tell them `Don't put any more things out there and use us as
guinea pigs,''' she said.
   Robins distributed about 4.5 million Dalkon Shields in the United
States and abroad before taking the device off the market in 1974.
Robins paid about $520 million to settle 9,400 of some 15,000 Dalkon
Shield lawsuits before seeking bankruptcy protection in 1985.
   Ms. Hightower said she has received calls ``daily and nightly''
from claimants worried because the appeals decision had taken since
December to be handed down.
   ``So many of them believed they had been used by A.H. Robins and
were beginning to doubt the court system,'' she said. ``Now they can
see there's a light at the end of the tunnel.''
   Ms. Hightower, who became pregnant in 1972 while using the Dalkon
Shield and gave birth to a brain-damaged child, said approval of the
plan will help ease some of her anger toward A.H. Robins.
   ``Once these women get a check in their hands, it won't
compensate for their injuries or the children they don't have, but
it's proof that they did something about it,'' she said.
</TEXT>
