<HEAD>At Least Four Bidders Submit Revised Bids For NWA; One Drops Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs with closing stock price; PICKS UP 6th graf
pvs, `MEI Diversified...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four groups said Friday they remain in the
running to buy Northwest Airlines parent NWA Inc., a major takeover
firm also was rumored to be a front-runner and one former suitor
dropped out.
   Pan Am Corp., oil billionaire Marvin Davis, Northwest's
machinists' union and a group led by Los Angeles investor Alfred
Checchi said they met Friday's deadline for revised bids for the
owner of Northwest Airlines, the nation's fourth-largest carrier.
   Two of those bidders, who asked not to be identified, said they
believed the New York takeover firm Kohlberg Kravis &amp; Roberts Co.
also submitted an offer. Kohlberg Kravis would not comment.
   Analysts have said the winning Northwest bid could be as high as
$120 a share, or $3.5 billion.
   NWA stock closed up 12{ cents at $107.62{ Friday on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   MEI Diversified Inc. of Minneapolis, led by Minnesota Twins owner
and banker Carl Pohlad and including financier Irwin Jacobs, said it
would not revise its initial offer. MEI President Donald Benson did
not return telephone calls seeking comment on why MEI was dropping
out.
   A four-member committee of the NWA board announced June 5 it had
rejected all first-round bids. It asked for ``enhanced'' revisions,
saying it would favor a high price, low level of debt and an ability
to complete a deal quickly in lieu of takeover scrutiny by federal
regulators.
   NWA has declined to identify the bidders or say when a decision
would be made.
   NWA Chairman Steven Rothmeier has said the board may decide not
to sell the company, possibly opting instead for a special dividend
payment to shareholders, acquisition of another company, liquidation
of the airline or sale of more than 20 percent of NWA stock to a
friendly third party.
   ``I don't think the bidding will go a third round and I think
you'll get a decision next week,'' said Mike Hamilton, an analyst
with Piper Jaffray &amp; Hopwood of Minneapolis.
   KKR, which specializes in buying companies with borrowed money in
deals known as leveraged buyouts, completed the largest deal in
history with the $24.53 billion takeover of RJR Nabisco Inc. earlier
this year.
   Checchi, a former Marriott Corp. executive, has been described by
Rothmeier as a friendly suitor. His group includes Gary Wilson, a
former NWA board member, and Frederic Malek, an unsuccessful
candidate for the president's job at United Airlines who once headed
Marriott's hotel group.
   KLM Royal Dutch Airlines is an equity partner in the Checchi
group, which also has backing from Elder IXL Ltd., an Australian
investment holding company.
   A source in the Checchi group confirmed it met Friday's bidding
deadline but declined to elaborate.
   Pan Am Chairman Thomas Plaskett said his company's revised bid
includes $200 million in equity from Corporate Partners, an
investment fund organized by Lazard Freres &amp; Co. and managed by
Lester Pollack and Ali E. Wambold.
   That brings the total amount of equity in the Pan Am proposal to
$600 million, Plaskett said.
   No other details of the offer were disclosed but spokeswoman
Pamela Hanlon said the bid still includes bank financing and
subordinated debt placed with private institutions. The earlier Pan
Am bid included $2.7 billion in bank financing.
   Analysts said Pan Am has an uphill battle for Northwest because a
merger probably would result in more debt than any other proposed
deal.
   Pan Am, the nation's eighth-largest carrier, is more than $900
million in debt and Plaskett has said the company needs to acquire
another airline or be acquired.
   A spokesman for Davis, who opened the bidding for Northwest on
March 28 with a $90-a-share or $2.7 billion offer, said Davis has
submitted a ``new and very full'' offer.
   No details were disclosed, but the spokesman said it was Davis'
final bid.
   Guy Cook, president of the International Association of
Machinists District Lodge 143, would not disclose details of the
union's revised bid. The machinists account for about 20,000 of
Northwest's 35,000 employees.
</TEXT>
