<FIRST>r f AM-ShopperRewards 1stLd-Writethru f0316 06-16 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shopper Rewards, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0316,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safeway Provides Frequent Shoppers With Rewards For Loyalty</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th graf, `The program...' with one graf to ADD Publix
stores. Montine Clapper in 2nd graf is cq. Also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BURKHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supermarkets in four states plan to hand out
coupons in exchange for purchases, which will be tracked by special
cards distributed to customers, a spokeswoman said Thursday.
   The program in supermarkets in Colorado, Illinois, Florida and
New York is aimed at encouraging customer loyalty and finding out
what people buy, said Montine Clapper of Safeway Stores.
   The cards will electronically record the items bought and their
value, Clapper said.
   In Colorado, participating customers can earn up to seven coupons
a month at the rate of one coupon for every $50 spent in Safeway
stores, she said.
   Each month, participants will get a list of about 100 name-brand
products that qualify for discounts and a statement detailing their
purchases and how much credit they've earned.
   At the end of three months, customers will receive a voucher that
can be applied toward purchases at the store.
   The program will work similarly at Pathmark, Vons, Publix and
Giant Food stores in the other states, Clapper said.
   ``It's free and convenient ... no register tapes to count,'' she
said. ``We're getting information on our customers as to shopping
habits, trends, what they're interested in ... so we can better turn
around and see what they're interested in seeing in our Safeway
stores.''
   Safeway's program began with a test in Greeley about 1{ years
ago, then expanded into Colorado Springs, Fort Collins and Denver
area stores, Clapper said. By the end of the summer, more than
three-fourths of the 93 Safeway stores in the state will offer the
program.
   The program is run by Citicorp POS Information Services Inc. of
Stamford, Conn., which provided the computer hardware and software,
Clapper said. POS stands for point of sale.
</TEXT>
