<FILEID>AP-NR-06-16-89 1858EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     06-16 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices edged lower Friday following the
government's report that consumer prices rose sharply in May.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond slipped 3-16 point,
or $1.87 for every $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in
the opposite direction from price, was unchanged from late Thursday
at 8.30 percent.
   Analysts said bond prices were weakened by the Labor Department
report that the Consumer Price Index rose 0.6 percent in May,
sending inflation to an annual rate of 6.7 percent for the first
five months of the year.
   High inflation is a bad sign for credit markets because it erodes
the value of fixed-income securities such as bonds.
   ``The CPI number scared a few people,'' said John Sebastian,
executive vice president of Clayton Brown &amp; Associates in Chicago.
   The market had rallied in recent weeks on the dollar's rapid
advance and signs that the economy was moderating. But bond prices
declined sharply Thursday when the dollar tumbled in foreign
exchange. The inflation report made traders more apprehensive.
   ``We've seen the slowdown in the economy. Unfortunately we
haven't seen the slowdown in the inflation numbers,'' said Steven A.
Wood, an economist with BankAmerica Capital Markets Group in San
Francisco.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term government issues slipped 1-16 point to 5-32 point,
intermediate maturities also declined 1-16 point to 5-32 point, and
20-year issues fell 5-32 point, according to figures provided by
Telerate Inc., a financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 1.16 at 1,169.25.
   In corporate trading, industrials also declined. Moody's
Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return
on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, slipped 1.69 to 322.50.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 7-32 point. The average yield to
maturity was 7.30 percent, down from 7.33 percent late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 8.40 percent as the
discount increased 5 basis points to 8.13 percent. Yields on
six-month bills rose to 8.38 percent as the discount jumped 7 basis
points to 7.95 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 8.54
percent as the discount soared 7 basis points to 7.94 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest banks charge each other for
short-term loans, was quoted late Friday at 97-16 percent, unchanged
from late Thursday.
</TEXT>
