<FIRST>r f AM-Trump-Atlantis     06-16 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trump-Atlantis,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gaming Regulators Approve Trump Casiono Purchase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State gaming regulators Friday approved
Donald Trump's $63 million offer for the Elsinore's Atlantis Casino
Hotel, ending a struggle over New Jersey's first failed casino.
   The commission said it was not convinced Trump was gaining too
much power in Atlantic City and voted to approve the billionaire
developer's purchase of the closed casino, which Trump plans to turn
into a luxury hotel.
   ``I am satisfied ... that the proposed acquisition of Atlantis
would not unacceptably affect the competitive climate that exists in
Atlantic City,'' commission chairman Walter Read said before the 5-0
vote.
   The commission rejected recommendations by the Division of Gaming
Enforcement to impose several major conditions on the deal,
including a ban on future Trump acquisitions of casino-zoned real
estate.
   Trump representatives told the commission the conditions would
end the deal. Trump already owns two Atlantic City casinos and has a
third under construction.
   Over objections from two commissioners, the panel did require
Trump to gain commission approval before building more hotels or
buying more land zoned for casinos.
   The Atlantis acquisition leaves Trump with control of 34 percent
of the city's casino hotel rooms, 31 percent of casino floor space
and revenue, and 48 percent of casino meeting and exhibition space,
according to the commission.
   Commissioners Frank Dodd and David Waters said the restrictions
amounted to meddling into Trump's affairs, which they said could
inhibit further investment in the resort city.
   ``We want Atlantic City to develop but we're stifling the
potential,'' Dodd said.
   Trump did not attend the meeting. His brother Robert, executive
vice president of The Trump Organization, said he was ``delighted''
by the vote and did not object to the conditions.
   Trump plans to keep the hotel open and more than 600 employees
working while refurbishing begins. Elsinore had warned its
increasingly bleak finances threatened to close the hotel in coming
days.
   The commission this spring denied Atlantis' owners a new license,
citing Elsinore's chronic and worsening debt. It was the first time
a New Jersey casino lost a bid for relicensing since casino gambling
was established more than a decade ago.
   Elsinore and Trump struck a deal in April shortly before the
license expired and a state-appointed conservator was to take title.
Trump then announced plans to end gambling at the boardwalk property
and remake it into a luxury hotel.
   Conservator Joseph Nolan and a lawyer for the gaming division had
said they suspected Elsinore ignored offers from others who would
revive the gaming hall to the benefit of casino competition.
   Approval of the Trump sale came at the end of a three-day hearing.
   John L. White, the conservator's lawyer, argued the Trump deal
would harm competition in Atlantic City and give the New York
developer a dangerous level of control over the state's gaming
industry.
   ``The minute this organization does something to increase or
decrease prices, the competition is going to have to fall into line
or face going out of business,'' White said.
   Trump representatives denied the accusation, saying Trump's
holdings are not large enough to give him unusual influence in New
Jersey gaming.
</TEXT>
