<FIRST>r f AM-GrandMet-Wimpy     06-16 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grand Met-Wimpy,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Met Mentioned As Possible Bidder For U.K. Burger Chain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Grand Metropolitan PLC, owner of
Burger King, has been mentioned in a British press report as having
a possible interest in buying Britain's largest hamburger chain,
Wimpy International.
   Wimpy owner United Biscuits PLC said Wednesday it is negotiating
with several companies to sell its restaurant division, which also
includes 284 Pizzaland and Perfect Pizza restaurants. Thursday's
Financial Times of London listed Grand Met as one of several British
restaurant companies that might have an interest in buying the
business. Grand Met declined to comment.
   Wimpy has 386 outlets in Britain, compared with McDonald's 305.
   Stephen Carnes of Dain Bosworth Inc., an analyst in Minneapolis,
said Grand Met could possibly convert some of the restaurants into
Burger Kings. The restaurant locations are valuable because Britain
is a tight market, Carnes said.
   ``Over there it's really full up,'' Carnes told the Star Tribune
of Minneapolis. ``They grow vertically.''
   The Star Tribune said the two other companies most often
mentioned in the British press as potential buyers are Whitbread and
Co. PLC, a major brewer, and Allied Restaurants.
   Grand Met acquired Burger King in January when it bought
Minneapolis-based Pillsbury Co. for $5.7 billion. The Burger King
subsidiary is based in Miami.
</TEXT>
