<FIRST>r f AM-China-HongKong     06-16 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Hong Kong,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senior Hong Kong Chinese Official Offers Reassurance on Colony's
Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hong Kong's trade minister expressed confidence
Friday that China will honor its vow to protect the freewheeling
British colony's capitalist system after the 1997 takeover, despite
new anxiety raised by the bloody political repression in Beijing.
   ``The situation in China must have raised doubts as to whether
the Sino-British agreement on the future of Hong Kong will be fully
and faithfully implemented,'' John Chan, secretary for trade and
industry, told the National Committee on U.S.-China Relations and
the Hong Kong Association in a speech.
   ``It is important not to lose heart, not to be defeatist,'' he
said. ``If anything, the tragic events in China have served to
accentuate the importance of the Joint Declaration to Hong Kong, not
detract from it.''
   Hong Kong will become part of China in 1997 under a
Chinese-British declaration signed in 1984. China has pledged to
maintain Hong Kong's way of life for 50 years after the takeover
under what Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping has called the principle of
``one country, two systems.''
   Speaking to reporters before the speech, Chan said he was
confident China would abide by the agreement because it has an
excellent record for honoring international commitments.
   ``What gives the agreement its teeth is that it's a binding
agreement,'' he said.
   Chan, senior Hong Kong-Chinese member of the British colonial
government, was in the United States for an official visit scheduled
prior to China's June 3-4 military crackdown on pro-democracy
protesters in Beijing.
   The crackdown jolted Hong Kong's stability, led to a surge in
emigration requests and raised new questions about the colony's
future under Chinese rule. It has been the major topic in Chan's
talks with U.S. officials and business executives during his visit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
